{"title_page": "Aaron Bastani", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Bastani\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Aaron Bastani, The World Transformed.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Bastani (left) in 2017\n| birth_name         = Aaron John Peters<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=272710177:7666&d=bmd_1583829598 FreeBMD Entry Info<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1984}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bournemouth]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Broadcaster, writer, commentator and activist\n| known_for          = \n}}\n\n'''Aaron John Bastani''' (born February 1984 as '''Aaron John Peters''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/8r28VnikO13PzB_oq_nbpGCmYOA/appointments|title=Aaron John BASTANI - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> is a British [[Pundit|political commentator]], [[writer]], broadcaster and [[Activism|activist]]. He is a Contributing Editor of [[Novara Media]], which he co-founded.\n\n== Early life ==\nBastani was raised by his mother in Bournemouth. He took his Iranian father's surname in 2014.<ref name=autogenerated3>https://www.ft.com/content/0e99fc98-4872-11e8-8ae9-4b5ddcca99b3</ref> He was educated at [[University College London]] before completing his doctorate at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]] in 2015. His thesis was entitled \"Strike! Occupy! Retweet!: The Relationship Between Collective and Connective Action in [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|Austerity Britain]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewchadwick.com/phd-students|title=PhD Students|website=Andrew Chadwick|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2010, Aaron Bastani co-founded the left-wing online news network, Novara Media, of which he is a Senior Editor and the main broadcaster. He co-hosts Novara Media's weekly podcast, NovaraFM, also broadcast on Resonance FM. Bastani has interviewed such figures as the economist [[Yanis Varoufakis]], Marxist geographer [[David Harvey]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] [[Lists of United Kingdom MPs|MP]] [[Caroline Lucas]], and the journalists [[Owen Jones]] and [[Paul Mason (journalist)|Paul Mason]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Gent|first=Craig|title=Alternative Media: A New Factor in Electoral Politics?|date=2018-11-24|work=Political Communication in Britain|pages=117\u2013128|publisher=Springer International Publishing|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-030-00822-2_8|isbn=978-3-030-00821-5|last2=Walker|first2=Michael}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/media/2017/09/luxury-communism-now-rise-pro-corbyn-media|title=\"Luxury communism now!\" The rise of the pro-Corbyn media|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for a number of publications including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Vice Media|Vice]]'' and the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' blog<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/aaron-peters|title=Aaron Bastani {{!}} The Guardian|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ppxpdm/luxury-communism-933|title=We Don't Need More Austerity: We Need Luxury Communism|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2015-06-12|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/aaron-bastani|title=Aaron Bastani \u00b7 LRB|last=LRB|website=LRB Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> and appeared on television broadcasters such as [[CNBC]], ''[[Channel 4 News]]'', and [[Sky News]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2015/08/18/corbyn-man-of-the-millennials.html|title=Corbyn: Man of the millennials?|date=2015-08-18|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/corbyn-is-a-game-changer-for-the-left|title=Labour entryists: the left activists joining to back Corbyn|website=Channel 4 News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Aaron Bastani on Sky News on Jeremy Corbyn's Shadow Cabinet|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SWdrzC0E98A|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, his political manifesto \"Fully Automated Luxury Communism\" was published.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Fully_Automated_Luxury_Communism.html?id=LewoswEACAAJ|title=Fully Automated Luxury Communism|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2019-06-11|publisher=Verso Books|isbn=978-1-78663-262-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/59385289-fully-automated-luxury-communism-a-manifesto|title=Fully Automated Luxury Communism|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Political views and activities ==\nBastani describes his political views as [[Anarcho-communism|libertarian communist]] and [[Feminism|feminist]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Aaron Bastani Speaks At Wysing Art Centre|url=https://soundcloud.com/novaramedia/aaron-bastani-speaks-at-wysing-art-centre|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AaronBastani/status/114462674829586432|title=Fuck off Vere - I'm a man and feminism is awesome and needed now more then ever #newsnight|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2011-09-15|website=@AaronBastani|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> He supports the political aspiration of \"fully automated luxury communism\", describing a post-scarcity economy with provision of a [[Basic income|universal basic income]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2016/06/17/the-long-read-what-will-we-do-in-the-post-work-utopia-by-mareile-pfannebecker-and-j-a-smith/|title=Long Read Review: What Will We Do in the Post-Work Utopia? by Mareile Pfannebecker and J.A. Smith|last=June 17th|last2=2016{{!}}Arts|date=2016-06-17|website=LSE Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24|last3=reviews|first3=Literature book|last4=Reviews|first4=Comparative|last5=reviews|first5=Economics book|last6=reviews|first6=Politics book|last7=Sociology|last8=Comments|first8=Anthropology book reviews{{!}}15}}</ref>\n\nBastani was found guilty of attacking a [[HSBC]] bank in London in March 2011 during an anti-austerity protest by using a wheelie bin to break the door open, before waving other protesters inside. Bastani was convicted of a public order offence, given a suspended prison sentence and ordered to perform [[community service]].<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/comey-swayed-by-trump-sex-dossier-a3869581.html The Londoner: Comey swayed by Trump sex dossier | London Evening Standard<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHe has been a member of the Green Party and a supporter of their London mayoral candidate, [[Si\u00e2n Berry]]. He endorsed the [[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sianberry.london/endorsements/|title=Endorsements|website=Sian Berry AM|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016]], Bastani initially campaigned for the [[United Kingdom|UK]] to leave the [[European Union]] but changed his position on pragmatic grounds two weeks before the referendum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novaramedia.com/2016/04/18/why-the-left-should-vote-to-leave-the-eu/|title=Why the left should vote to leave the EU|website=Novara Media|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novaramedia.com/2016/06/09/why-ive-changed-my-mind-about-brexit/|title=Why I've Changed My Mind About Brexit|website=Novara Media|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Bastani was reported as making a video in which he described the [[Poppy Appeal]] as \u201cgrotesque\u201d, \u201cracist\u201d and \u201cwhite supremacist\u201d and called for the [[Royal British Legion]] to be shut down. [[Mark Francois]] MP said Bastani's views was \"hysterical\" whilst former Labour MP [[Baron Mann|John Mann]] called for him to be expelled from the party. Bastani said that his comments had been taken out of context and he had worn the poppy himself. He said that his concern was the homelessless of and lack of support for veterans.<ref>https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/top-jeremy-corbyn-supporter-aaron-15389415</ref><ref>[https://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/tom-swarbrick/corbynista-aaron-bastani-tory-british-legion-axed/ Corbynista Sparks Fury From Tory MP After Calling For British Legion To Be Axed - LBC<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Libel suit ==\nIn April 2020, Bastani apologised to [[Maajid Nawaz]] and paid legal costs and a donation in lieu of damages to [[Quilliam (think tank)|Quilliam]] after calling him a \"former terrorist\" on Twitter. Bastani said: \"By falsely accusing a Muslim who I disagree with of terrorism, I have engaged in anti-Muslim bigotry. I am sorry I have engaged in the repetition of such an anti-Muslim trope\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bastani |first1=Aaron |url=https://twitter.com/AaronBastani/status/1246188035932336132 |website=Twitter |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBastani is an amateur [[ornithologist]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastani, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal Holloway, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:British broadcasters]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:British political commentators]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Bournemouth]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Aaron Bastani\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Aaron Bastani, The World Transformed.jpg\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Bastani (left) in 2017\n| birth_name         = Aaron John Peters<ref name=autogenerated2>[https://www.freebmd.org.uk/cgi/information.pl?r=272710177:7666&d=bmd_1583829598 FreeBMD Entry Info<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{Birth year and age|1984}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bournemouth]]\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = Broadcaster, writer, commentator and activist\n| known_for          = \n}}\n\n'''Aaron John Bastani''' (born February 1984 as '''Aaron John Peters''')<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/8r28VnikO13PzB_oq_nbpGCmYOA/appointments|title=Aaron John BASTANI - Personal Appointments (free information from Companies House)|website=beta.companieshouse.gov.uk|language=en|access-date=2020-01-25}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2 /> is a British [[Pundit|political commentator]], [[writer]], broadcaster and [[Activism|activist]]. He is a Contributing Editor of [[Novara Media]], which he co-founded.\n\n== Early life ==\nBastani was raised by his mother in Bournemouth. He took his Iranian father's surname in 2014.<ref name=autogenerated3>https://www.ft.com/content/0e99fc98-4872-11e8-8ae9-4b5ddcca99b3</ref> He was educated at [[University College London]] before completing his doctorate at [[Royal Holloway, University of London]] in 2015. His thesis was entitled \"Strike! Occupy! Retweet!: The Relationship Between Collective and Connective Action in [[United Kingdom government austerity programme|Austerity Britain]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.andrewchadwick.com/phd-students|title=PhD Students|website=Andrew Chadwick|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 2010, Aaron Bastani co-founded the left-wing online news network, Novara Media, of which he is a Senior Editor and the main broadcaster. He co-hosts Novara Media's weekly podcast, NovaraFM, also broadcast on Resonance FM. Bastani has interviewed such figures as the economist [[Yanis Varoufakis]], Marxist geographer [[David Harvey]], [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]], [[Green Party of England and Wales|Green Party]] [[Lists of United Kingdom MPs|MP]] [[Caroline Lucas]], and the journalists [[Owen Jones]] and [[Paul Mason (journalist)|Paul Mason]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Gent|first=Craig|title=Alternative Media: A New Factor in Electoral Politics?|date=2018-11-24|work=Political Communication in Britain|pages=117\u2013128|publisher=Springer International Publishing|language=en|doi=10.1007/978-3-030-00822-2_8|isbn=978-3-030-00821-5|last2=Walker|first2=Michael}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newstatesman.com/politics/media/2017/09/luxury-communism-now-rise-pro-corbyn-media|title=\"Luxury communism now!\" The rise of the pro-Corbyn media|website=www.newstatesman.com|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nHe has written for a number of publications including ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[Vice Media|Vice]]'' and the ''[[London Review of Books]]'' blog<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/profile/aaron-peters|title=Aaron Bastani {{!}} The Guardian|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/en_uk/article/ppxpdm/luxury-communism-933|title=We Don't Need More Austerity: We Need Luxury Communism|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2015-06-12|website=Vice|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lrb.co.uk/contributors/aaron-bastani|title=Aaron Bastani \u00b7 LRB|last=LRB|website=LRB Blog|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> and appeared on television broadcasters such as [[CNBC]], ''[[Channel 4 News]]'', and [[Sky News]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/video/2015/08/18/corbyn-man-of-the-millennials.html|title=Corbyn: Man of the millennials?|date=2015-08-18|website=CNBC|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{Cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/corbyn-is-a-game-changer-for-the-left|title=Labour entryists: the left activists joining to back Corbyn|website=Channel 4 News|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=Aaron Bastani on Sky News on Jeremy Corbyn's Shadow Cabinet|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SWdrzC0E98A|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2019, his political manifesto \"Fully Automated Luxury Communism\" was published.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Fully_Automated_Luxury_Communism.html?id=LewoswEACAAJ|title=Fully Automated Luxury Communism|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2019-06-11|publisher=Verso Books|isbn=978-1-78663-262-3|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/59385289-fully-automated-luxury-communism-a-manifesto|title=Fully Automated Luxury Communism|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\n== Political views and activities ==\nBastani describes his political views as [[Anarcho-communism|libertarian communist]] and a [[Feminism|feminist]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Aaron Bastani Speaks At Wysing Art Centre|url=https://soundcloud.com/novaramedia/aaron-bastani-speaks-at-wysing-art-centre|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/AaronBastani/status/114462674829586432|title=Fuck off Vere - I'm a man and feminism is awesome and needed now more then ever #newsnight|last=Bastani|first=Aaron|date=2011-09-15|website=@AaronBastani|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> He supports the political aspiration of \"fully automated luxury communism\", describing a post-scarcity economy with provision of a [[Basic income|universal basic income]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blogs.lse.ac.uk/lsereviewofbooks/2016/06/17/the-long-read-what-will-we-do-in-the-post-work-utopia-by-mareile-pfannebecker-and-j-a-smith/|title=Long Read Review: What Will We Do in the Post-Work Utopia? by Mareile Pfannebecker and J.A. Smith|last=June 17th|last2=2016{{!}}Arts|date=2016-06-17|website=LSE Review of Books|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24|last3=reviews|first3=Literature book|last4=Reviews|first4=Comparative|last5=reviews|first5=Economics book|last6=reviews|first6=Politics book|last7=Sociology|last8=Comments|first8=Anthropology book reviews{{!}}15}}</ref>\n\nBastani was found guilty of attacking a [[HSBC]] bank in London in March 2011 during an anti-austerity protest by using a wheelie bin to break the door open, before waving other protesters inside. Bastani was convicted of a public order offence, given a suspended prison sentence and ordered to perform [[community service]].<ref name=autogenerated3 /><ref>[https://www.standard.co.uk/news/londoners-diary/comey-swayed-by-trump-sex-dossier-a3869581.html The Londoner: Comey swayed by Trump sex dossier | London Evening Standard<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\nHe has been a member of the Green Party and a supporter of their London mayoral candidate, [[Si\u00e2n Berry]]. He endorsed the [[Labour Party leadership of Jeremy Corbyn]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sianberry.london/endorsements/|title=Endorsements|website=Sian Berry AM|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\nIn the run-up to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|United Kingdom European Union membership referendum, 2016]], Bastani initially campaigned for the [[United Kingdom|UK]] to leave the [[European Union]] but changed his position on pragmatic grounds two weeks before the referendum.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novaramedia.com/2016/04/18/why-the-left-should-vote-to-leave-the-eu/|title=Why the left should vote to leave the EU|website=Novara Media|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://novaramedia.com/2016/06/09/why-ive-changed-my-mind-about-brexit/|title=Why I've Changed My Mind About Brexit|website=Novara Media|language=en|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Bastani was reported as making a video in which he described the [[Poppy Appeal]] as \u201cgrotesque\u201d, \u201cracist\u201d and \u201cwhite supremacist\u201d and called for the [[Royal British Legion]] to be shut down. [[Mark Francois]] MP said Bastani's views was \"hysterical\" whilst former Labour MP [[Baron Mann|John Mann]] called for him to be expelled from the party. Bastani said that his comments had been taken out of context and he had worn the poppy himself. He said that his concern was the homelessless of and lack of support for veterans.<ref>https://www.birminghammail.co.uk/news/midlands-news/top-jeremy-corbyn-supporter-aaron-15389415</ref><ref>[https://www.lbc.co.uk/radio/presenters/tom-swarbrick/corbynista-aaron-bastani-tory-british-legion-axed/ Corbynista Sparks Fury From Tory MP After Calling For British Legion To Be Axed - LBC<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n\n== Libel suit ==\nIn April 2020, Bastani apologised to [[Maajid Nawaz]] and paid legal costs and a donation in lieu of damages to [[Quilliam (think tank)|Quilliam]] after calling him a \"former terrorist\" on Twitter. Bastani said: \"By falsely accusing a Muslim who I disagree with of terrorism, I have engaged in anti-Muslim bigotry. I am sorry I have engaged in the repetition of such an anti-Muslim trope\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Bastani |first1=Aaron |url=https://twitter.com/AaronBastani/status/1246188035932336132 |website=Twitter |accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBastani is an amateur [[ornithologist]].{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bastani, Aaron}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Royal Holloway, University of London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College London]]\n[[Category:British activists]]\n[[Category:British broadcasters]]\n[[Category:British male writers]]\n[[Category:British political commentators]]\n[[Category:Left-wing politics in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:People from Bournemouth]]\n", "name_user": "Jontel", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical views and activities", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Bastani"}
{"title_page": "String Quartet No. 6 (Villa-Lobos)", "text_new": "{{Use Harvard referencing|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Heitor Vila-Lobos (c. 1922)part.jpg|thumb|Heitor Villa-Lobos]]\n'''String Quartet No. 6''' (\"Brazilian\") is one of seventeen works in the medium by the Brazilian composer [[Heitor Villa-Lobos]], and was written in 1938. A performance lasts approximately 24 minutes.\n\n==History==\nVilla-Lobos composed his Sixth Quartet during 1938 in Rio de Janeiro, and it was first performed in the same city by the Quarteto Haydn on 30 November 1943, on the same programme as the premiere of the [[String Quartet No. 7 (Villa-Lobos)|Seventh Quartet]]. The published score bears no dedication, but the manuscript is dedicated to the violist Orlando Frederico {{harv|''Villa-Lobos, sua obra''|1972|loc=85}}, who many years earlier had participated in the premieres of both the [[String Quartet No. 2 (Villa-Lobos)|Second]] and [[String Quartet No. 3 (Villa-Lobos)|Third Quartets]]. Together with the [[String Quartet No. 5 (Villa-Lobos)|Fifth Quartet]], this work is marked by a deliberate move toward a more \"popular\" style, incorporating elements of Brazilian popular music, and the Sixth is regarded as the most [[Musical nationalism|nationalistic]] of all Villa-Lobos's string quartets {{harv|B\u00e9hague|2003|loc=294}}. Villa-Lobos originally planned to designate this work as the second \"popular quartet\" (the Fifth Quartet is subtitled \"Quarteto popular no. 1\"), but in the end abandoned the idea of such a series {{harv|B\u00e9hague|1994|loc=123}}. At the same time, it is with this quartet that the references to the quartets of [[Joseph Haydn|Haydn]], which continue throughout the composer's later quartets, become clear for the first time {{harv|Salles|2012|loc=94}}\n\n==Analysis==\nThis composition, like all of Villa-Lobos's quartets except the first, consists of four movements:\n# Poco animato \n# Allegretto \n# Andante, quasi adagio \n# Allegro vivace\n\nInstead of the usual [[Sonata form|sonata-allegro form]], the first movement  presents a [[Sectional form|sectional structure]]. Four contrasting sections (with transitions between the first and second, and between the third and fourth) are followed by a [[Recapitulation (music)|recapitulation]] of the first section, and an extended coda. There is no [[development section]] {{harv|Farmer|1973|loc=49}}.\n\nThe second movement is in a three-part, [[Ternary form|ABA song form]] in the character of the Brazilian improvised serenade known as the [[choro]] {{harv|Farmer|1973|loc=58\u201359}}. The A section is homophonic, while the central B section features imitative textures and a xang\u00f4-like theme set against a syncopated accompaniment in quadruple time ({{harvnb|Farmer|1973|loc=67}}; {{harvnb|Tarasti|2009|loc=238}}).\n\nThe third movement is also in ternary form, but with a variation. The A section falls into two parts, which are reversed in order when A is recapitulated after the central B section {{harv|Farmer|1973|loc=67\u201368}}. The tonal language and textural features of the outer sections resemble those of the ''[[Bachianas Brasileiras]]'', especially parts of the first movement of ''Bachianas'' No. 5. The middle section features a [[fugato]] on a [[Subject (music)|subject]] related to the cantilena (xang\u00f4) motive from the second movement. This passage is the first occurrence of the [[Atonality|atonal]], chromatic, legato style found often in Villa-Lobos's subsequent quartets {{harv|Tarasti|2009|loc=238}}.\n\nThe finale is similar in structure to the first movement, consisting of three successive, contrasting sections and a recapitulation of the first, concluding with a short coda {{harv|Farmer|1973|loc=71}}. Unlike the first movement, however (and unlike all of the composer's earlier quartets), there is a certain thematic kinship amongst the sections, with a recurrence of a falling-third figure and the use of pseudo-Indian motifs influenced by [[Anton\u00edn Dvo\u0159\u00e1k]]'s [[String Quartet No. 12 (Dvo\u0159\u00e1k)|\"American\" Quartet]] {{harv|Tarasti|2009|loc=238}}.\n\n==Discography==\nChronological by date of recording.\n*Heitor Villa-Lobos: Quartet no. 6 in E (Quartetto brasileiro no. 2). Stuyvesant String Quartet (Sylvan Shulman, Bernard Robbins, violins; Ralph Hersh, viola; [[Alan Shulman]], cello). Recorded at the [[Majestic Theatre (Broadway)|Majestic Theatre]], New York City, 7 May 1947. Standard groove, 3 discs: 12&nbsp;in., 78&nbsp;rpm, monaural. International Records 301. International Master Series. New York: International Records, [1947]. Reissued on LP, 1 disc: 12&nbsp; 33\u2153&nbsp;rpm, monaural. Concert Hall CHC-19. New York, N.Y.: Concert Hall, 1949. Reissued on CD with quartets by Paul Hindemith and Quincy Porter. Parnassus PACD 96026. Woodstock, NY: Parnassus Records, 2000.\n*[[William Walton]]: String Quartet in A Minor; Heitor Villa-Lobos: String Quartet No. 6. Hollywood String Quartet ([[Felix Slatkin]], Paul Shure, violins; Paul Robyn, viola; [[Eleanor Aller]] [Slatkin], cello). Recorded between 1951 and 1953. LP recording, 1 disc: analog, 33\u2153&nbsp;rpm, monaural, 12&nbsp;in. Record Society 6010. Melbourne: Record Society, [195?]. Villa-Lobos also issued as part of:\n**Heitor Villa-Lobos: String Quartet No. 6; [[Zolt\u00e1n Kod\u00e1ly]]: String Quartet No. 2, Op. 10. Hollywood String Quartet. LP recording, 1 disc: analog, 33\u2153&nbsp;rpm, monaural, 12&nbsp;in. Capitol P 8472. Hollywood: Capitol Records, 1959. \n* [[Radam\u00e9s Gnatalli]]: ''Quarteto popular''; [[C\u00e9sar Guerra-Peixe]]: Quartet No. 2; Alceo Bocchino: ''Seresta suburbana''; Heitor Villa-Lobos - Quarteto n\u00ba 6. Quarteto Brasileiro da UFRJ (Santino Parpinelli and Henrique Morelenbaum, violins; Jacques Nirenberg, viola; Eugen Ranevsky, cello). LP recording.\n**Reissued on CD, CID 02027. 1999.\n**Reissued on CD, Albany TROY 420. [S.l.]: Albany Records, 2001.\n**Villa-Lobos quartet (only) reissued as part of  Heitor Villa-Lobos: String Quartets nos. 1, 6, and 17. Quarteto Brasileiro da UFRJ. CD recording, 1 sound disc: digital, 12&nbsp;cm, stereo. [S.l.]: Albany Records, 2005.\n**''Hollywood String Quartet''. [[Maurice Ravel]]: Introduction and Allegro; [[Claude Debussy]]: ''Danse sacr\u00e9e et danse profane''; [[Joaqu\u00edn Turina]]: ''La oraci\u00f3n del torero'', Op. 34; Villa-Lobos: String Quartet No. 6; Paul Creston: String Quartet, Op. 8. Ann Mason Stockton, harp (Ravel and Debussy); Arthur Gleghorn, flute (Ravel); Mitchell Lurie, clarinet (Ravel); Concert Arts Strings, Felix Slatkin, conductor (Debussy); Hollywood String Quartet. CD recording, 1 disc: 12&nbsp;cm, monaural. [England]: Testament, 1994. \n*Heitor Villa-Lobos: String Quartets Nos. 4, 6 and 14. [[Danubius Quartet]] (Judit T\u00f3th and Ad\u00e9l Mikl\u00f3s, violins; Cecilia Bodolai, viola; Ilona Wibli, cello). Recorded at the Hungaroton Studios in Budapest, 18\u201319, 22\u201325 April, and 20\u201323 May 1991. CD recording, 1 disc: digital, 12&nbsp;cm, stereo. Marco Polo 8.223391. A co-production with Records International. Germany: HH International, Ltd., 1992.\n* Villa-Lobos: String Quartets, Volume 1. Quartets Nos. 6, 1, 17. [[Cuarteto Latinoamericano]] (Sa\u00fal Bitr\u00e1n, Ar\u00f3n Bitr\u00e1n, violins; Javier Montiel, viola; Alvaro Bitr\u00e1n, cello). Recorded at the Troy Savings Bank Music Hall in Troy, NY, April 1994. Music of Latin American Masters. CD recording, 1 disc: digital, 12&nbsp;cm, stereo. Dorian DOR-90205. Troy, NY: Dorian Recordings, 1995. \n**Reissued as part of ''Heitor Villa-Lobos: The Complete String Quartets''. 6 CDs + 1 DVD with a performance of Quartet No. 1 and interview with the Cuarteto Latinoamericano. Dorian Sono Luminus. DSL-90904. Winchester, VA: Sono Luminus, 2009.\n**Also reissued (without the DVD) on Brilliant Classics 6634.\n*Villa-Lobos: Quatuors a Cordes Nos. 4/5/6. Quatuor Bessler-Reis ([[Bernardo Bessler]], Michel Bessler, violins; Marie-Christine Springuel, viola