{"title_page": "Police of Denmark", "text_new": "{{short description|Police agency}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = State Police\n| nativename      = Politiet\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      = \n| abbreviation    = \n| patch           =\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            =Logo de la Police Danoise (Politi).svg \n| logocaption     =\n| badge           =\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           = \n| mottotranslated = Insight, vision and foresight <ref>{{cite web |title=About Police (danish: Om Politiforbundet) |url=https://politiforbundet.dk/om-politiforbundet |publisher=Politiforbundet}}</ref>\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1919\n| formedmonthday  = \n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     =\n| employees       = \n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = \n| countryabbr     =\n| national        = Yes\n| map             =\n| mapcaption      =\n| sizearea        =\n| sizepopulation  =\n| legaljuris      =\n| governingbody   = Rigspolitiet\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Copenhagen]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       =\n| sworn           = \n| unsworntype     = Civilian\n| unsworn         = 14 000\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      =\n| chief1position  =\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    = \n| child2agency    = \n| child3agency    = \n| child4agency    = \n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        =\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = [https://www.politi.dk/da/servicemenu/forside/ www.politi.dk]\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\n[[Image:MHE - Politibetjente.jpg|thumb|right|Police officers in daily utility uniform]]\n[[Image:Politi arbejde.jpg|thumb|right|Parked police vehicle]]\n[[Image:Eskorte.jpg|thumb|right|Police motorcycles escorting an [[ambulance]]]]\n[[Image:Hestepolitiet.jpg|thumb|right|Mounted police officers]]\n[[Image:MHE_-_Afsp\u00e6rring.jpg|thumb|right|Police line made by [[caution tape]]]]\n[[Image:DK-POL-VW-LT35.jpg|thumb|right|2nd gen. LT35 operated by the Danish police]]\n\nThe '''[[police]] of Denmark''' ({{lang-da|Politiet}}, {{lang-fo|L\u00f8greglan}}, {{lang-kl|Politiit}})) is the interior part of the Danish security forces (the [[Danish Defence|Danish military]] being the exterior) in the Kingdom ([[The unity of the Realm]]: Denmark (proper), Greenland, Faroe Islands). The police are empowered to enforce the law and to effect public and social order, as well as being responsible for [[border control]].<ref>{{cite book |chapterurl=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/e-library/documents/policies/borders-and-visas/schengen/docs/handbook-annex_01.pdf |chapter=Annex 1: List of national services responsible for border control |title=Practical Handbook for Border Guards (Schengen Handbook) |date=6 November 2006 |publisher=[[European Commission]] |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe police of Denmark consists of 12 districts each managed by a director and two minor districts in [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]], run by a local chief of police.\nThe district of [[Copenhagen]] is somewhat differently organized due to its size and tasks.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nBesides the regular districts other organizations exist that work outside the general police:\n* [[Rigspolitiet]] - a nationwide police force with specialized tasks such as ''Budgets and Accounts'', ''Building Surveying Department'' and the ''Data Investigating Department''\n* [[Politiets Efterretningstjeneste]] - the national security intelligence agency of Denmark\n* [[Politiets Aktionsstyrke]] - the special forces unit of the Danish police\n\n==Equipment==\n===Uniform===\nThe common uniform is a light blue shirt with the police insignia on the sleeve. Usually a tie is also worn. Rank-insignia is worn on the shoulders. The trousers are dark blue with reflective patches. Black shoes are also included in the standard uniform. Special tactical suits are made of flame-resistant materials and are worn in situations requiring such equipment. The tactical suit also includes a protective helmet.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} \n\n===Vehicles===\nFor daily duties, the patrol-vehicles are white and dog-patrols are mostly dark blue. They have a blue strobe-light or flashing light and the word \"POLITI\" painted on the side in clear reflective paint. The most commonly used patrol vehicles are [[Ford Mondeo]], [[Volkswagen Passat]] and [[Opel Vectra]], with 2.0 to 2.2 litre engines. In 2009, the 3.6 litre [[\u0160koda Superb]] was added to the fleet. Unmarked cars are usually fitted with engines with a size of around 1.6 to 2.2 litres. In addition a large number of small unmarked cars are used like [[Peugeot 307]], [[Opel Astra]], [[Ford Focus (international)|Ford Focus]] and Toyota Yaris - with engine size of around 1.2 to 1.6 litre. The [[Peugeot 607]] is used by a security attachment for cabinet members and the royal court. The [[Toyota Landcruiser]] and VW Touareg are used for special tasks. Small detachments typically use [[Volkswagen Transporter|VW Transporters]], while [[Volkswagen LT|VW LTs]] and [[Ford Transit]] mini-buses are used in larger operations, which require a lot of manpower (demonstrations, football matches and larger civil unrests). In extreme events, a variation of the [[Mercedes-Benz Vario|MB Vario]] is used. It is generally known as the ''Dutchman's vehicle'' (in Danish ''Holl\u00e6ndervogn''). This name derives from the fact that these vehicles are kitted out in the Netherlands as [[Armoured personnel carrier|light APC's]] with reinforced windows, wheels and metal parts and [[Fireproofing|fire-resistant]] coating. They are used both as light APCs in event of demonstrations or public disturbances, and as general transportation of large numbers of detainees.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Other vehicles in use are the [[Mercedes-Benz Vito]] (used by both Central Patrol Leaders, a kind of on-street watch commanders) and [[Nissan Patrol]]s used by the mounted police squads with a horse carrier attached.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe traffic police also use unmarked vans for automatic traffic control. These are primarily VW Transporters, Mercedes Benz Vitos, [[Toyota Hiace]]s, but others are used as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.10-20.dk/fotovogn.htm |title=Fotovogne i Danmark |trans-title=Photo vehicles in Denmark |website=10-20.dk |language=da  |accessdate=7 November 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020021815/http://www.10-20.dk/fotovogn.htm |archivedate=20 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nSome rural police officers use civilian vehicles with a dismountable magnetic roof beacon.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nFor traffic regulation and VIP and ambulance escorts [[motorcycle]]s are also used, primarily [[Yamaha FJR1300]]A, [[Honda ST1300]]a,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politi.dk/da/aktuelt/nyheder/2005/motorcykler_220905.htm |title=Politiet f\u00e5r nye motorcykler |trans-title=Police get new motorcycles |date=22 September 2005 |website=Politi.dk |language=da |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref> [[BMW K1200R]]S and [[BMW K1200GT]] (over time replacing older [[BMW motorcycles#K Series|BMW K1100LT]] and [[BMW motorcycles#R Series|BMW R1100RT]]).\n\n===Weapons===\nThe standard service handgun is the [[Heckler & Koch USP|H&K USP Compact]] 9mm [[pistol]]. For special tasks the [[Heckler & Koch MP5|H&K MP5]] [[sub-machine gun]] is used. Officers are also equipped with batons and pepper spray cans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politi.dk/NR/rdonlyres/20DE43AF-33F4-48C5-A710-6A58457E35D2/0/Engelskresum%C3%A9afendeligrapport.pdf |title=The use of police firearms in Denmark |first=Frode Z. |last=Olsen |date=2008 |website=Politi.dk |accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Law about police enforcement==\nThe operation of [[Denmark|Danish]] [[police]] is regulated in the ''Act on Police Enforcement'' (da: ''Lov om politiets virksomhed''), commonly known as ''The Police Act'' (da: ''politiloven'') of 20 August 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/forms/R0710.aspx?id=143225 |title=Lov om politiets virksomhed |trans-title=Law on Police Activity |language=da |website=Retsinformation.dk |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIts first section states that:\n\n\"The police must work to ensure security, safety, peace and order in society. The police must promote this purpose through prevention, assistance and enforcement.\"\n\nThe second section states that other areas of police jurisdiction include:\n\n# preventing criminal actions, disturbances of the public peace and order and danger to individual citizens and public safety\n# stopping criminal actions and investigating and prosecuting criminal actions\n# supporting citizens in dangerous situations\n# carrying out checking and inspecting under current rules and regulations\n# supporting other agencies under current rules and regulations\n# performing other tasks under current rules and regulations, as well as handling other tasks which are naturally associated with police duties.\n\nLastly, the third section states:\n\"The police may in other situations than those mentioned in statutory law only interfere with citizens under this Act.\"<ref group=note>Though this may seem obvious, it is a precaution that clearly states that the police may under no circumstances act towards the citizens in ways not stated by law (da: ''hjemlet''). This ensures that the police cannot make their own interpretations of laws or regulations.</ref>\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\nIn Denmark, the local prosecution service is part of the police. Since 2014, only Chief Prosecutors wear uniforms; other prosecutors, such as senior prosecutors, prosecutors, associate prosecutors, and advocates, do not.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"50\" | '''Rank'''\n! align=\"left\" width=\"260\" | Rank titles<ref name=\"Gradstegn2014\">{{cite web |url=https://politi.dk/-/media/mediefiler/dokumenter/landsdaekkende/om-politiet/hr/distinktioner-i-politiet.pdf?la=da&hash=8986DE4231A0AD29201BE5D764512DB2D6B32A45 |title=Distinktioner I Politiet |trans-title=Danish Police rank insignia |date=July 2017 |website=Politi.dk |language=da |access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" |Rank insignia<ref name=\"Gradstegn2014\"/>\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Personnel category\n! align=\"left\" width=\"260\" | English equivalent\n|-\n| 1. || [[Rigspolitiet|Rigspolitichef]] || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Rigspolitichef.svg|34px]]  ||Senior manager|| [[Police commissioner]]\n|-\n| 2. || Politidirekt\u00f8r<br/>Direktionsmedlem i Rigspolitiet<br/>Politimester i [[Politiets Efterretningstjeneste|PET]]<br/>Politimester i Gr\u00f8nland<br/>Politimester p\u00e5 F\u00e6r\u00f8erne || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Politidirekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]] || Senior manager|| [[Chief constable]]\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"3\"| 3. || Stabschef<br/>Afdelingschef i Rigs-<br/>politiet || align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"| [[File:Dansk Chefpolitiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]]  || Senior manager|| [[Assistant Chief Constable]]\n|-\n|  Chefanklager   || Lawyer || [[Crown Prosecutor|Chief Crown Prosecutor]]\n|-\n|  Chefpolitiinspekt\u00f8r    || Police || [[Chief Superintendent]]  \n|-\n| 4. || Vicepolitimester i Gr\u00f8nland<br/>Vicepolitimester p\u00e5 F\u00e6r\u00f8erne<br/>Vicepolitimester i Rigspolitiet<br/>Politiinspekt\u00f8r || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Politiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]]  ||  Police || [[Superintendent (police)|Superintendent]]\n|-\n| 5. || Vicepolitiinspekt\u00f8r || align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Vicepolitiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]] || Police || [[Police Inspector]] \n|-\n| 6. || Politikommiss\u00e6r ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politikommiss\u00e6r.svg|34px]] || Police ||  [[Police Sergeant]] \n|-\n| 7. || Politiassistent  ||  align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politiassistent 2.svg|34px]] ||Police||  Police Constable with 12 years service\n|-\n| 8. || Politiassistent ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politiassistent 1.svg|34px]] || Police ||Police Constable with 7 years service\n|-\n|9. || Politibetjent ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politibetjent.svg|34px]] || Police || [[Police Constable]] \n|-\n| 10. || Politikadet ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politikadet.svg|34px]] || Police || Police Cadet\n|}\n\n==Military police==\n\n[[File:Danish military police Mercedes.JPG|thumb|right|Danish military police]]\n\nThe [[Military Police#Denmark|military police (MP) in Denmark]] are police units within the armed forces branches. Each branch has its own MP corps, although they often work together and wear similar insignias.\n\nMP personnel typically wear either specific display dress uniforms with white MP shoulder markings or the branch-common daily [[Battle Dress Uniform|battle dress uniforms]] with a red [[beret]].\n\nMP personnel generally do not have any legal jurisdiction over civilians in non-military locations, but only over military personnel and over everyone on military installations (also publicly accessible places such as the [[Holmen Naval Base]] in [[Copenhagen]]), in the buildings housing [[Ministry of Defence (Denmark)|the Ministry of Defence]], royal palaces (like [[Amalienborg Palace]]) and parts of [[Christiansborg Palace]]. On some occasions, MP personnel can provide support to the civilian police for certain tasks, but will only have slightly more legal authority than civilians, similar to the police home guard.\n\n==Police Home Guard==\n[[File:Politi-hjemmev\u00e6rnet (MC betjent).jpg|thumb|right|Police Home Guard [[Police motorcycle|motorcycle]] operator.]]\n\nThe Danish police can call upon assistance from a section of the [[Danish Home Guard|Danish home guard]]: [[Politihjemmev\u00e6rnet]] the ''police home guard''. The police home guard consists of 47 companies, each led by professional police officers.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe volunteers are mainly used for traffic control at [[festival]]s, [[Missing person|searches for victims]] and guarding community installations and are never used in tasks involving direct confrontation with civilians ([[riot control]] or planned [[arrest]]s). These companies are part of the Army Home Guard.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vistillerop.dk/vores-organisation/haerhjemmevaernet/ |title=H\u00e6rhjemmev\u00e6rnet |trans-title=The Home Guard |website=Vistillerop.dk |language=da |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThey wear branch-common daily battle dress uniforms, green berets and bright yellow vests with the text \"POLITI HJEMMEV\u00c6RNET\" (POLICE HOME GUARD). \n\nMembers of the police home guard have slightly more legal authority than regular citizens when the service they provide calls for it, but they are always under the supervision of the civilian police.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Crime in Denmark]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Police of Denmark}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.politi.dk }}\n\n{{Europe topic|Law enforcement in}}\n{{Americas topic|Law enforcement in}}\n{{Border guards}}\n{{Police}}\n{{Customs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Police Of Denmark}}\n[[Category:Law enforcement in Denmark| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Police agency}}\n{{Infobox law enforcement agency\n| agencyname      = State Police\n| nativename      = Politiet\n| nativenamea     =\n| nativenamer     =\n| commonname      = \n| abbreviation    = \n| patch           =\n| patchcaption    =\n| logo            =Logo de la Police Danoise (Politi).svg \n| logocaption     =\n| badge           =\n| badgecaption    =\n| flag            =\n| flagcaption     =\n| imagesize       =\n| motto           = \n| mottotranslated = Insight, vision and foresight <ref>{{cite web |title=About Police (danish: Om Politiforbundet) |url=https://politiforbundet.dk/om-politiforbundet |publisher=Politiforbundet}}</ref>\n| mission         =\n| formedyear      = 1919\n| formedmonthday  = \n| preceding1      =\n| dissolved       =\n| superseding     =\n| employees       = \n| volunteers      =\n| budget          =\n| nongovernment   =\n| country         = \n| countryabbr     =\n| national        = Yes\n| map             =\n| mapcaption      =\n| sizearea        =\n| sizepopulation  =\n| legaljuris      =\n| governingbody   = Rigspolitiet\n| governingbodyscnd =\n| constitution1   =\n| police          = Yes\n| local           = Yes\n| overviewtype    =\n| overviewbody    =\n| headquarters    = [[Copenhagen]]\n| hqlocmap        =\n| hqlocleft       =\n| hqloctop        =\n| hqlocmappoptitle =\n| sworntype       =\n| sworn           = \n| unsworntype     = Civilian\n| unsworn         = 14 000\n| electeetype     =\n| minister1name   =\n| minister1pfo    =\n| chief1name      =\n| chief1position  =\n| parentagency    =\n| child1agency    = \n| child2agency    = \n| child3agency    = \n| child4agency    = \n| unittype        =\n| unitname        =\n| officetype      =\n| officename      =\n| provideragency  =\n| uniformedas     =\n| stationtype     =\n| stations        =\n| airbases        =\n| lockuptype      =\n| lockups         =\n| vehicle1type    =\n| vehicles1       =\n| boat1type       =\n| boats1          =\n| aircraft1type   =\n| aircraft1       =\n| animal1type     =\n| animals1        =\n| person1name     =\n| person1reason   =\n| person1type     =\n| programme1      =\n| activity1name   =\n| activitytype    =\n| anniversary1    =\n| award1          =\n| website         = [https://www.politi.dk/da/servicemenu/forside/ www.politi.dk]\n| footnotes       =\n| reference       =\n}}\n\n[[Image:MHE - Politibetjente.jpg|thumb|right|Police officers in daily utility uniform]]\n[[Image:Politi arbejde.jpg|thumb|right|Parked police vehicle]]\n[[Image:Eskorte.jpg|thumb|right|Police motorcycles escorting an [[ambulance]]]]\n[[Image:Hestepolitiet.jpg|thumb|right|Mounted police officers]]\n[[Image:MHE_-_Afsp\u00e6rring.jpg|thumb|right|Police line made by [[caution tape]]]]\n[[Image:DK-POL-VW-LT35.jpg|thumb|right|2nd gen. LT35 operated by the Danish police]]\n\nThe '''[[police]] of Denmark''' ({{lang-da|Politiet}}, {{lang-fo|L\u00f8greglan}}, {{lang-kl|Politiit}})) is the interior part of the Danish security forces (the [[Danish Defence|Danish military]] being the exterior) in the Kingdom ([[The unity of the Realm]]: Denmark (proper), Greenland, Faroe Islands). The police are empowered to enforce the law and to effect public and social order, as well as being responsible for [[border control]].<ref>{{cite book |chapterurl=https://ec.europa.eu/home-affairs/sites/homeaffairs/files/e-library/documents/policies/borders-and-visas/schengen/docs/handbook-annex_01.pdf |chapter=Annex 1: List of national services responsible for border control |title=Practical Handbook for Border Guards (Schengen Handbook) |date=6 November 2006 |publisher=[[European Commission]] |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organization==\nThe police of Denmark consists of 12 districts each managed by a director and two minor districts in [[Greenland]] and the [[Faroe Islands]], run by a local chief of police.\nThe district of [[Copenhagen]] is somewhat differently organized due to its size and tasks.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nBesides the regular districts other organizations exist that work outside the general police:\n* [[Rigspolitiet]] - a nationwide police force with specialized tasks such as ''Budgets and Accounts'', ''Building Surveying Department'' and the ''Data Investigating Department''\n* [[Politiets Efterretningstjeneste]] - the national security intelligence agency of Denmark\n* [[Politiets Aktionsstyrke]] - the special forces unit of the Danish police\n\n==Equipment==\n===Uniform===\nThe common uniform is a light blue shirt with the police insignia on the sleeve. Usually a tie is also worn. Rank-insignia is worn on the shoulders. The trousers are dark blue with reflective patches. Black shoes are also included in the standard uniform. Special tactical suits are made of flame-resistant materials and are worn in situations requiring such equipment. The tactical suit also includes a protective helmet.{{citation needed|date=October 2014}} \n\n===Vehicles===\nFor daily duties, the patrol-vehicles are white and dog-patrols are mostly dark blue. They have a blue strobe-light or flashing light and the word \"POLITI\" painted on the side in clear reflective paint. The most commonly used patrol vehicles are [[Ford Mondeo]], [[Volkswagen Passat]] and [[Opel Vectra]], with 2.0 to 2.2 litre engines. In 2009, the 3.6 litre [[\u0160koda Superb]] was added to the fleet. Unmarked cars are usually fitted with engines with a size of around 1.6 to 2.2 litres. In addition a large number of small unmarked cars are used like [[Peugeot 307]], [[Opel Astra]], [[Ford Focus (international)|Ford Focus]] and Toyota Yaris - with engine size of around 1.2 to 1.6 litre. The [[Peugeot 607]] is used by a security attachment for cabinet members and the royal court. The [[Toyota Landcruiser]] and VW Touareg are used for special tasks. Small detachments typically use [[Volkswagen Transporter|VW Transporters]], while [[Volkswagen LT|VW LTs]] and [[Ford Transit]] mini-buses are used in larger operations, which require a lot of manpower (demonstrations, football matches and larger civil unrests). In extreme events, a variation of the [[Mercedes-Benz Vario|MB Vario]] is used. It is generally known as the ''Dutchman's vehicle'' (in Danish ''Holl\u00e6ndervogn''). This name derives from the fact that these vehicles are kitted out in the Netherlands as [[Armoured personnel carrier|light APC's]] with reinforced windows, wheels and metal parts and [[Fireproofing|fire-resistant]] coating. They are used both as light APCs in event of demonstrations or public disturbances, and as general transportation of large numbers of detainees.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}} Other vehicles in use are the [[Mercedes-Benz Vito]] (used by both Central Patrol Leaders, a kind of on-street watch commanders) and [[Nissan Patrol]]s used by the mounted police squads with a horse carrier attached.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe traffic police also use unmarked vans for automatic traffic control. These are primarily VW Transporters, Mercedes Benz Vitos, [[Toyota Hiace]]s, but others are used as well.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.10-20.dk/fotovogn.htm |title=Fotovogne i Danmark |trans-title=Photo vehicles in Denmark |website=10-20.dk |language=da  |accessdate=7 November 2018 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071020021815/http://www.10-20.dk/fotovogn.htm |archivedate=20 October 2007}}</ref>\n\nSome rural police officers use civilian vehicles with a dismountable magnetic roof beacon.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nFor traffic regulation and VIP and ambulance escorts [[motorcycle]]s are also used, primarily [[Yamaha FJR1300]]A, [[Honda ST1300]]a,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politi.dk/da/aktuelt/nyheder/2005/motorcykler_220905.htm |title=Politiet f\u00e5r nye motorcykler |trans-title=Police get new motorcycles |date=22 September 2005 |website=Politi.dk |language=da |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref> [[BMW K1200R]]S and [[BMW K1200GT]] (over time replacing older [[BMW motorcycles#K Series|BMW K1100LT]] and [[BMW motorcycles#R Series|BMW R1100RT]]).\n\n===Weapons===\nThe standard service handgun is the [[Heckler & Koch USP|H&K USP Compact]] 9mm [[pistol]]. For special tasks the [[Heckler & Koch MP5|H&K MP5]] [[sub-machine gun]] is used. Officers are also equipped with batons and pepper spray cans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.politi.dk/NR/rdonlyres/20DE43AF-33F4-48C5-A710-6A58457E35D2/0/Engelskresum%C3%A9afendeligrapport.pdf |title=The use of police firearms in Denmark |first=Frode Z. |last=Olsen |date=2008 |website=Politi.dk |accessdate=28 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Law about police enforcement==\nThe operation of [[Denmark|Danish]] [[police]] is regulated in the ''Act on Police Enforcement'' (da: ''Lov om politiets virksomhed''), commonly known as ''The Police Act'' (da: ''politiloven'') of 20 August 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.retsinformation.dk/forms/R0710.aspx?id=143225 |title=Lov om politiets virksomhed |trans-title=Law on Police Activity |language=da |website=Retsinformation.dk |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nIts first section states that:\n\n\"The police must work to ensure security, safety, peace and order in society. The police must promote this purpose through prevention, assistance and enforcement.\"\n\nThe second section states that other areas of police jurisdiction include:\n\n# preventing criminal actions, disturbances of the public peace and order and danger to individual citizens and public safety\n# stopping criminal actions and investigating and prosecuting criminal actions\n# supporting citizens in dangerous situations\n# carrying out checking and inspecting under current rules and regulations\n# supporting other agencies under current rules and regulations\n# performing other tasks under current rules and regulations, as well as handling other tasks which are naturally associated with police duties.\n\nLastly, the third section states:\n\"The police may in other situations than those mentioned in statutory law only interfere with citizens under this Act.\"<ref group=note>Though this may seem obvious, it is a precaution that clearly states that the police may under no circumstances act towards the citizens in ways not stated by law (da: ''hjemlet''). This ensures that the police cannot make their own interpretations of laws or regulations.</ref>\n\n==Ranks and insignia==\nIn Denmark, the local prosecution service is part of the police. Since 2014, only Chief Prosecutors wear uniforms; other prosecutors, such as senior prosecutors, prosecutors, associate prosecutors, and advocates, do not.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"F1F1F1\"\n! align=\"left\" width=\"50\" | '''Rank'''\n! align=\"left\" width=\"260\" | Rank titles<ref name=\"Gradstegn2014\">{{cite web |url=https://politi.dk/-/media/mediefiler/dokumenter/landsdaekkende/om-politiet/hr/distinktioner-i-politiet.pdf?la=da&hash=8986DE4231A0AD29201BE5D764512DB2D6B32A45 |title=Distinktioner I Politiet |trans-title=Danish Police rank insignia |date=July 2017 |website=Politi.dk |language=da |access-date=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" |Rank insignia<ref name=\"Gradstegn2014\"/>\n! align=\"left\" width=\"100\" | Personnel category\n! align=\"left\" width=\"260\" | English equivalent\n|-\n| 1. || [[Rigspolitiet|Rigspolitichef]] || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Rigspolitichef.svg|34px]]  ||Senior manager|| [[Police commissioner]]\n|-\n| 2. || Politidirekt\u00f8r<br/>Direktionsmedlem i Rigspolitiet<br/>Politimester i [[Politiets Efterretningstjeneste|PET]]<br/>Politimester i Gr\u00f8nland<br/>Politimester p\u00e5 F\u00e6r\u00f8erne || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Politidirekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]] || Senior manager|| [[Chief constable]]\n|-\n|  rowspan=\"3\"| 3. || Stabschef<br/>Afdelingschef i Rigs-<br/>politiet || align=\"center\" rowspan=\"3\"| [[File:Dansk Chefpolitiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]]  || Senior manager|| [[Assistant Chief Constable]]\n|-\n|  Chefanklager   || Lawyer || [[Crown Prosecutor|Chief Crown Prosecutor]]\n|-\n|  Chefpolitiinspekt\u00f8r    || Police || [[Chief Superintendent]]  \n|-\n| 4. || Vicepolitimester i Gr\u00f8nland<br/>Vicepolitimester p\u00e5 F\u00e6r\u00f8erne<br/>Vicepolitimester i Rigspolitiet<br/>Politiinspekt\u00f8r || align=\"center\"| [[File:Dansk Politiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]]  ||  Police || [[Superintendent (police)|Superintendent]]\n|-\n| 5. || Vicepolitiinspekt\u00f8r || align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Vicepolitiinspekt\u00f8r.svg|34px]] || Police || [[Police Inspector]] \n|-\n| 6. || Politikommiss\u00e6r ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politikommiss\u00e6r.svg|34px]] || Police ||  [[Police Sergeant]] \n|-\n| 7. || Politiassistent  ||  align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politiassistent 2.svg|34px]] ||Police||  Police Constable with 12 years service\n|-\n| 8. || Politiassistent ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politiassistent 1.svg|34px]] || Police ||Police Constable with 7 years service\n|-\n|9. || Politibetjent ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politibetjent.svg|34px]] || Police || [[Police Constable]] \n|-\n| 10. || Politikadet ||align=\"center\"|[[File:Dansk Politikadet.svg|34px]] || Police || Police Cadet\n|}\n\n==Military police==\n\n[[File:Danish military police Mercedes.JPG|thumb|right|Danish military police]]\n\nThe [[Military Police#Denmark|military police (MP) in Denmark]] are police units within the armed forces branches. Each branch has its own MP corps, although they often work together and wear similar insignias.\n\nMP personnel typically wear either specific display dress uniforms with white MP shoulder markings or the branch-common daily [[Battle Dress Uniform|battle dress uniforms]] with a red [[beret]].\n\nMP personnel generally do not have any legal jurisdiction over civilians in non-military locations, but only over military personnel and over everyone on military installations (also publicly accessible places such as the [[Holmen Naval Base]] in [[Copenhagen]]), in the buildings housing [[Ministry of Defence (Denmark)|the Ministry of Defence]], royal palaces (like [[Amalienborg Palace]]) and parts of [[Christiansborg Palace]]. On some occasions, MP personnel can provide support to the civilian police for certain tasks, but will only have slightly more legal authority than civilians, similar to the police home guard.\n\n==Police Home Guard==\n[[File:Politi-hjemmev\u00e6rnet (MC betjent).jpg|thumb|right|Police Home Guard [[Police motorcycle|motorcycle]] operator.]]\n\nThe Danish police can call upon assistance from a section of the [[Danish Home Guard|Danish home guard]]: [[Politihjemmev\u00e6rnet]] the ''police home guard''. The police home guard consists of 47 companies, each led by professional police officers.{{Citation needed|date=February 2015}}\n\nThe volunteers are mainly used for traffic control at [[festival]]s, [[Missing person|searches for victims]] and guarding community installations and are never used in tasks involving direct confrontation with civilians ([[riot control]] or planned [[arrest]]s). These companies are part of the Army Home Guard.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.vistillerop.dk/vores-organisation/haerhjemmevaernet/ |title=H\u00e6rhjemmev\u00e6rnet |trans-title=The Home Guard |website=Vistillerop.dk |language=da |accessdate=7 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThey wear branch-common daily battle dress uniforms, green berets and bright yellow vests with the text \"POLITI HJEMMEV\u00c6RNET\" (POLICE HOME GUARD). \n\nMembers of the police home guard have slightly more legal authority than regular citizens when the service they provide calls for it, but they are always under the supervision of the civilian police.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Crime in Denmark]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Police of Denmark}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.politi.dk }}\n\n{{Europe topic|Law enforcement in}}\n{{Border guards}}\n{{Police}}\n{{Customs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Police Of Denmark}}\n[[Category:Law enforcement in Denmark| ]]\n", "name_user": "BALMAINM", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Police_of_Denmark"}
{"title_page": "Qualcomm", "text_new": "{{short description|American global semiconductor company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Qualcomm Incorporated\n| logo             =Qualcomm-Logo.svg\n|image=[[Image:Qualcomm Headquarters La Jolla.jpg|250px]]\n| image_caption = Qualcomm Research Center in San Diego, California.\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = NASDAQ: QCOM<br />[[S&P 500|S&P 500 Component]]\n| foundation       = [[San Diego]], [[California]], [[United States of America|USA]] (1985)\n| founder          = [[Irwin M. Jacobs|Irwin Jacobs]]\n| location_city    = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| location_country = United States\n| area =\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = Steven Mollenkopf, CEO<br>Cristiano Amon, President<br>Mark D. McLaughlin, Chairman\n| industry         = {{nowrap|[[Telecommunications equipment]]<br />[[Semiconductor]]s}}\n| products         =Intellectual property and semiconductors\n| num_employees = ~37,000 (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| revenue           = $24.3 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\">{{cite web | title=FORM 10-K: For the fiscal year ended September 29, 2019 | website=Qualcomm.com | date=September 29, 2019 | url=https://investor.qualcomm.com/sec-filings/all-sec-filings/content/0001728949-19-000072/qcom10-k2019.htm | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income  = US $7.7 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| net_income        = US $4.4 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| assets            =  US $33 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| equity            = US $4.9 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| homepage = https://www.qualcomm.com }}<b>Qualcomm</b> is a public multinational corporation headquartered in [[San Diego, California]]. It creates [[intellectual property]], semiconductors, software, and services related to wireless technology. It owns patents critical to the [[CDMA2000]], [[TD-SCDMA]] and [[WCDMA]] mobile communications standards.\n \nQualcomm was established in 1985 by Irwin Jacobs and six other co-founders. Its early research into [[CDMA]] wireless cell phone technology was funded by selling satellite communications systems for commercial trucks. After a heated debate in the wireless industry, the 3G standard was adopted with Qualcomm's CDMA patents incorporated.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\"/> Afterwards there was a series of legal disputes about pricing for licensing patents required by the standard.\n \nOver the years, Qualcomm has expanded into selling semiconductor products in a predominantly [[Fabless manufacturing|fabless manufacturing]] model. It also developed semiconductor components or software for vehicles, watches, laptops, wi-fi, smartphones, and other devices.\n \n==Corporate history==\n===Early history===\nQualcomm was created on July 1, 1985<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Founder Set to Retire|first=Shara|last=Tibken|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=December 21, 2011|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052970204879004577111313063790248|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> by seven former [[Linkabit]] employees led by Irwin Jacobs.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> The company was named Qualcomm for \u201cQUALity COMMunications.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Dialed 26,078% Gain as it Transformed Mobile|first=Brian|last=Deagon|date=May 25, 2014|url=http://news.investors.com/business-the-new-america/042514-698579-qualcomm-qcom-set-cdma-cellphone-standard.htm|accessdate=July 26, 2014|newspaper=Investor\u2019s Business Daily}}</ref> It started as a contract research and development center<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\">{{cite book|author=Dan Steinbock|title=Wireless Horizon: Strategy and Competition in the Worldwide Mobile Marketplace|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=HugmyrqibtwC&amp;pg=PA305|year=2003|publisher=AMACOM Div American Mgmt Assn|isbn=978-0-8144-0714-1|pages=305}}</ref> largely for government and defense projects.<ref name=\"Mock2005\">{{cite book|author=Dave Mock|title=The Qualcomm Equation: How a Fledgling Telecom Company Forged a New Path to Big Profits and Market Dominance|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JcH4C2eAsJEC&amp;pg=PA33|date=January 1, 2005|publisher=AMACOM: American Management Association|isbn=978-0-8144-2858-0|pages=33}}</ref><ref name=\"six\"/>\n \nQualcomm merged with [[Omninet]] in 1988 and raised $3.5 million in funding in order to produce the Omnitracs satellite communications system for trucking companies.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm grew from eight employees in 1986 to 620 employees in 1991, due to demand for Omnitracs.<ref name=\"nytnyt\">{{cite news|title=Satellite System Helps Trucks Stay in Touch|first=Agis|last=Salpukas|date=June 5, 1991|accessdate=July 16, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/05/business/business-technology-satellite-system-helps-trucks-stay-in-touch.html|newspaper=The New York Times}}</reF> By 1989, Qualcomm had $32 million in revenues, 50 percent of which was from an Omnitracs contract with [[Schneider National]].<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><Ref name=\"two\">{{cite news|title=Big Boost for Qualcomm|date=November 23, 1988|first=Chris|last=Kraul|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-23/business/fi-275_1_qualcomm-system|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Omnitracs profits helped fund Qualcomm's research and development into [[code-division multiple access]] (CDMA) technologies for cell phone networks.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><ref name=\"tribunel\"/>\n \n===1990-2015===\nQualcomm was operating at a loss in the 1990s due to its investment in CDMA research.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><ref name=\"tribunel\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm completes sale of Omnitracs|first=Mike|last=Freeman|date=November 26, 2014|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/Nov/26/Qualcomm-Omnitracs-Vista-Equity-partners/|accessdate=July 17, 2014|newspaper=The San Diego Tribune}}</ref> To obtain funding, the company filed an [[initial public offering]] in September 1991<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Goes Public With Stock|date=September 17, 1991|first=Greg|last=Johnson|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-09-17/business/fi-2845_1_qualcomm-treasurer-dick-grannis|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> raising $68 million.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> An additional $486 million was raised in 1995 through the sale of 11.5 million more shares. The second funding round was done to raise money for the mass manufacturing of CDMA-based phones, base-stations, and equipment, after most US-based cellular networks announced they would adopt the CDMA standard.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> The company had $383 million in annual revenue in 1995<ref name=\"bwbw\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/1995-09-03/qualcomm-unproven-but-dazzling|newspaper=BusinessWeek|title=Qualcomm: Unproven, But Dazzling|date=September 3, 1995|first=Larry|last=Armstrong|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}</reF> and $814 million by 1996.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \nIn 1998, Qualcomm was restructured, leading to a 700-employee layoff. Its cell-phone manufacturing business was also spun-off in order to focus on its higher-margin patents business.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|310-311}} The following year, Qualcomm was the fastest growing stock on the market with a 2,621 percent growth over one year.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Hits The Big Time Pushing a little-known digital cellular technology from surf's-up San Diego, this $4-billion-a-year hotshot wants to be THE NEXT INTEL|newspaper=Fortune Magazine|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2000/05/15/279766/index.htm|first=Eric|last=Nee|date=May 15, 2000|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"sandiegomag\">{{cite news|title=A Qualcomm Quarter-Century|first=Joseph|last=Perkins|date=September 3, 2010|newspaper=San Diego Magazine|url=http://www.sandiegomagazine.com/San-Diego-Magazine/September-2010/A-Qualcomm-Quarter-Century/}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|publisher=CNET|date=January 7, 2000|title=Taking stock of 1999|first1=Sandeep|last1=Junnarkar|first2=Scott|last2=Ard|url=http://news.cnet.com/Taking-stock-of-1999/2100-1017_3-235357.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF> By 2000, Qualcomm had grown to 6,300 employees, $3.2 billion in revenues, and $670 million in profit. 39 percent of its sales were from CDMA technology, followed by licensing (22%), wireless (22%), and other products (17%).<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> Around this time, Qualcomm established offices in Europe, Asia Pacific, and Latin America.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|316}} By 2001, 65 percent of Qualcomm's revenues originated from outside the United States with 35 percent coming from South Korea.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|19}}\n \nIn 2005, [[Paul E. Jacobs]], son of Qualcomm founder Dr. Irwin Jacobs, was appointed as Qualcomm's new CEO.<ref name=\"nytsy\">{{cite news|title=At Qualcomm, Rise of Founder\u2019s Son Defies Hazards of Succession|first=Malia|last=Wollan |newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/13/technology/13qualcomm.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=0&amp;gwt=pay}}</reF> Whereas Irwin Jacobs focused on CDMA patents, Paul Jacobs refocused much of Qualcomm's new research and development on projects related to the [[internet of things]].<ref name=\"nytsy\"/> Qualcomm announced Steven Mollenkopf would succeed Paul Jacobs as CEO in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm names Mollenkopf president, COO|newspaper=EE Times|date=October 4, 2011|url= http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1260357|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|first=Brian|last=Chen|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 8, 2014|date=December 13, 2013|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/technology/qualcomm-names-a-new-chief-executive.html?_r=0|title=Qualcomm Picks Insider as New Chief Executive}}</ref> Mollenkopf said he would expand Qualcomm's focus to wireless technology for cars, wearable devices, and other new markets.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alistair|last=Barr| title=CES 2014: Qualcomm CEO sees growth in wearables, autos | website=USA TODAY | date=January 6, 2014 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/01/06/qualcomm-ceo-mollenkopf/4341927/ | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Rubin 2014\">{{cite web | last=Rubin | first=Ben Fox | title=Qualcomm wants to move out of your pocket into your car, house and wearable | website=CNET | date=November 19, 2014 | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-wants-to-move-out-of-your-pocket-into-your-cars-house-and-wearable/ |accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n===NXP and Broadcom===\nQualcomm announced its intent to acquire NXP Semiconductors for $47 billion in October 2016.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016\">{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Pressman| title=Here's Why the Qualcomm-NXP Deal Makes Sense | website=Fortune | date=October 27, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/10/27/qualcomm-nxp-deal/ | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The deal was approved by U.S. antitrust regulators in April 2017<ref name=\"Fortune 2017\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm's $47 Billion Acquisition Clears Key Hurdle | website=Fortune | date=April 4, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/04/04/qualcomm-nxp-acquisition-antitrust/ | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> with some standard-essential patents excluded to get the deal approved by antitrust regulators.<ref>{{cite web | last=Chee | first=Foo Yun | title=Qualcomm offers to buy NXP minus some patents to allay EU concerns:... | website=U.S. | date=October 10, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nxp-semicondtrs-m-a-qualcomm-eu/qualcomm-offers-to-buy-nxp-minus-some-patents-to-allay-eu-concerns-sources-idUSKBN1CF20D | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Drozdiak 2018\">{{cite web | last=Drozdiak | first=Natalia | title=Qualcomm Set to Win European Backing for $39 Billion NXP Buy | website=WSJ | date=January 11, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-set-to-win-european-backing-for-39-billion-nxp-buy-1515673776 |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n \nAs the NXP acquisition was ongoing, Broadcom made a $103 billion offer to acquire Qualcomm,<ref>{{cite web | title=Broadcom Offers $105 Billion for Qualcomm in Landmark Deal|first=Ian|last=King | website=Bloomberg | date=November 6, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-06/broadcom-offers-130-billion-for-qualcomm-in-landmark-tech-deal | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mukherjee 2017\">{{cite web | last=Mukherjee | first=Supantha | title=Broadcom bids $103 billion for Qualcomm, open to going hostile | website=U.S. | date=November 6, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/broadcom-offers-to-buy-mobile-chipmaker-qualcomm-for-103-billion-idUSKBN1D61EO | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> and Qualcomm rejected the offer.<ref name=\"Mukherjee 20172\">{{cite web | last=Mukherjee | first=Supantha | title=Qualcomm rejects Broadcom's $103-billion takeover bid | website=U.S. | date=November 13, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/qualcomm-rejects-broadcoms-103-billion-takeover-proposal-idUSKBN1DD1NU | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> Broadcom attempted a hostile takeover,<ref>{{cite web | first=Aishwarya|last=Venugopal, | title=Broadcom is laying the foundation for a hostile takeover of Qualcomm | website=Business Insider | date=December 4, 2017 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/qualcomm-broadcom-laying-the-foundation-for-a-hostile-takeover-2017-12 |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> and raised its offer, eventually to $121 billion.<ref name=\"dkahfad\">{{cite web | title=Broadcom Raises Qualcomm Hostile Bid to About $121 Billion| website=Bloomberg|first=Ian|last=King | date=February 5, 2018 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-05/broadcom-is-said-planning-to-boost-qualcomm-bid-to-120-billion | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> The potential Broadcom acquisition was investigated by the U.S. [[Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States|Committee on Foreign Investment]]<ref>{{cite web | title=US national security regulator delays Qualcomm vote | website=Financial Times | date=March 5, 2018 | url=https://www.ft.com/content/fb3e6312-2055-11e8-a895-1ba1f72c2c11 | accessdate=August 16, 2018|first1=Arash|last1=Massoudi|first2=Rochelle|last2=Toplensky |first3=James|last3=Fontanella-Khan}}</ref> and blocked by an executive order from U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], citing national security concerns.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Blocks Broadcom Takeover of Qualcomm on Security Risks|website=Bloomberg|date=March 12, 2018|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-12/trump-issues-order-to-block-broadcom-s-takeover-of-qualcomm-jeoszwnt|accessdate=August 16, 2018|first=David|last=McLaughlin}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm's NXP acquisition then became a part of the [[2018 China\u2013United States trade war]].<ref name=\"ouafhouh\">{{cite web | title=Trump Throws a Wrench Into Qualcomm's NXP Deal | website=Bloomberg | date=June 15, 2018 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-06-15/trump-throws-a-wrench-into-qualcomm-s-nxp-deal | accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Alex|last=Webb}}</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] blocked China-based [[ZTE Corporation]] from buying American-made components, such as those from Qualcomm.<ref name=\"ouafhouh\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm May Be Collateral Damage in a U.S.-China Trade War |first1=Ana |last1=Swanson|first2=Alexandra|last2=Stevenson| website=The New York Times | date=April 18, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/us/politics/qualcomm-us-china-trade-war.html | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref> The ZTE restriction was lifted after the two countries reached an agreement,<ref name=\"Financial Times 2017\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm, NXP jolted higher after US-ZTE deal | website=Financial Times | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://www.ft.com/content/c162a48c-6a56-11e8-8cf3-0c230fa67aec | accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Pan|last= Yuk}}</ref> but then Trump raised tariffs against Chinese goods.<ref name=\"ouafhouh\"/> Qualcomm extended a tender offer to NXP at least 29 times pending Chinese approval,<ref name=\"Reuters 2018\">{{cite web | first=Sonam|last=Rai| title=Qualcomm extends NXP tender offer yet again | website=Business Insider | date=June 29, 2018 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/r-qualcomm-extends-nxp-tender-offer-yet-again-2018-6 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref> before abandoning the deal in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web | first=Don|last=Clark|title=Qualcomm Scraps $44 Billion NXP Deal After China Inaction | website=The New York Times | date=July 25, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/technology/qualcomm-nxp-china-deadline.html | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Brown | first=Eliot | last2=Davis | first2=Bob | title=Qualcomm Abandons NXP Deal Amid U.S.-China Tensions | website=WSJ | date=July 25, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-plans-to-abandon-nxp-deal-1532549728 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Wireless CDMA==\n===2G===\n====Early history====\nIn mid-1985, Qualcomm was hired by [[Hughes Aircraft]] to provide research and testing for a satellite network proposal to the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC).<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|38}} The following year, Qualcomm filed its first CDMA patent (No. 4,901,307).<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> This patent established Qualcomm's overall approach to CDMA<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> and later became one of the most frequently cited technical documents in history.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\">{{cite book|first1=Mark|last1=Blaxill|first2=Ralph|last2= Eckardt|title=The Invisible Edge: Taking Your Strategy to the Next Level Using Intellectual Property|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JO6kA0hebJIC&pg=PA86|year=2009|publisher=Portfolio|isbn=978-1-59184-237-8}}</ref>{{RP|84}} The project with the FCC was scrapped in 1988, when the FCC told all twelve vendors that submitted proposals to form a joint venture to create a single proposal.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|38}}\n \nQualcomm further developed the CDMA techniques for commercial use and submitted them to the [[Cellular Telephone Industries Association]] (CTIA) in 1989 as an alternative to the [[time division multiple access]] (TDMA) standard for second-generation cell-phone networks.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|49}} A few months later, CTIA officially rejected Qualcomm's CDMA standard<ref name=\"LeiSlocum2013\">{{cite book|author1=David Lei|author2=John W. Slocum|title=Demystifying Your Business Strategy|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LaJFAAAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA101|date=August 29, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-26802-1|pages=101}}</ref> in favor of the more established TDMA standard developed by [[Ericsson]].<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><Ref name=\"bw3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/1997-06-01/qualcomm-not-exactly-an-overnight-success|newspaper=BusinessWeek|title=Qualcomm: Not Exactly An Overnight Success|date=June 1, 1997|accessdate=July 16, 2014|first=Peter|last=Elstrom}}</reF>\n \nAt the time, CDMA wasn't considered viable in high-volume commercial applications due to the near-far field effect, whereby phones closer to a cell tower with a stronger signal drown out callers that are further away and have a weaker signal.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|54-55,62-65}}<ref name=\"wsjalpha\"/> Qualcomm filed three additional patents in 1989. They were for: a power management system that adjusts the signal strength of each call to adjust for the near-far field effect; a \"soft handoff\" methodology for transferring callers from one cell-tower to the next; and a variable rate encoder, which reduces bandwidth usage when a caller isn't speaking.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|54-55,62-65}}<ref name=\"wsjalpha\"/>\n \n====Holy wars of wireless====\nAfter the FCC said carriers were allowed to implement standards not approved by the CTIA, Qualcomm began pitching its CDMA technology directly to carriers.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> This started what is often referred to as \"the Holy Wars of Wireless,\" an often heated debate about whether TDMA or CDMA was better suited for 2G networks.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|117-120}} Qualcomm-supported CDMA standards eventually unseated TDMA as the more popular 2G standard in North America, due to its network capacity.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \nQualcomm conducted CDMA test demonstrations in 1989<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/> in San Diego and in 1990 in New York City.<Ref name=\"thanks\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\"/> In 1990, Nynex Mobile Communications and Ameritech Mobile Communications were the first carriers to implement CDMA networks instead of TDMA.<Ref name=\"thanks\">{{cite news|date=August 20, 1990|title=Bolting from the cellular herd|newspaper=BusinessWeek|last1=Armstrong |first1= Larry|\nlast2=Therrien |first2= Lois|last3=Coy |first3= Peter}}</ref> [[Motorola]], a prior TDMA advocate, conducted CDMA test implementations in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Motorola Shift On Technology|date=November 20, 1990|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=July 17, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/20/business/motorola-shift-on-technology.html}}</ref><ref name=\"wsjalpha\">{{cite news|title=Jacobs's Patter: An Inventor's Promise Has Companies Taking Big Cellular Gamble --- Qualcomm Boss's Innovation In Digital-Phone System Is Problematic -- and Late --- Are Claims Hope or Hype?|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|first=Quentin|last=Hardy|date=September 6, 1996}}</reF> This was followed by a $2 million trial network in San Diego for Airtouch Communications.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\">{{cite book|author=Hsiao-Hwa Chen|title=The Next Generation CDMA Technologies|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eMfG0kuaL-kC&pg=PA178|date=August 20, 2007|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-02295-5}}</ref>{{RP|177}} In November 1991, 14 carriers and manufacturers conducted large-scale CDMA field tests.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"international\">{{cite book|author=Gale Group|title=International Directory of Company Histories|DUPLICATE-url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kd-6AAAAIAAJ|date=December 2, 2002|publisher=St. James Press|isbn=978-1-55862-476-4|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/qualcomm-incorporated-history/}}</ref>\n \nResults from the test implementations convinced CTIA to re-open discussions regarding CDMA and the 2G standard.<ref name=\"PhD2010\">{{cite book|author=William A. Cohen, PhD|title=Heroic Leadership: Leading with Integrity and Honor|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CevTu1VbrgEC&pg=PT60|date=May 24, 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-40501-7|page=60}}</ref> CTIA changed its position and supported CDMA in 1993,<Ref name=\"bw3\"/> adopting Qualcomm's CDMA as the IS-95A standard, also known as cdmaOne.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\">{{cite book|author1=Wolter Lemstra|author2=Vic Hayes|author3=John Groenewegen|title=The Innovation Journey of Wi-Fi: The Road to Global Success|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-OMoL5Irm08C&pg=PA29|date=November 18, 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-49257-7|pages=29}}</ref> This prompted widespread criticism in forums, trade press, and conventions from businesses that had already invested heavily in the TDMA standard and from TDMA's developer, Ericsson.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"PhD2010\"/> \n \nThe first commercial-scale CDMA cellular network was created in Hong Kong in 1995.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\"/> On July 21, 1995, [[Primeco]], which represented a consortium of [[Cox Communications]], [[Comcast]], [[Sprint Corporation|Sprint]] and others, announced it was going to implement CDMA-based services<Ref name=\"bw3\"/> on networks in 15 states.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\"/> By this time, 11 out of 14 of the world's largest networks supported CDMA.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><Ref name=\"economist\">{{cite news|title=Shorts circuited: cellular phones. (US cellular telephone industry backs Qualcomm's code division multiple access technology)|newspaper=The Economist (US)|date=July 29, 1995|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-17388504.html|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}</ref> By 1997 CDMA had 57 percent of the US market, whereas 14 percent of the market was on TDMA.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \n====International====\nIn 1991, Qualcomm and the [[Electronics and Telecommunications Research Institute]] (ETRI) agreed to jointly develop CDMA technologies for the Korean telecommunications infrastructure.<ref name=\"Reddick2012\">{{cite book|author=Christopher G. Reddick|title=Cases on Public Information Management and E-Government Adoption|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=r-VVYRvSafYC|year=2012|publisher=IGI Global Snippet|isbn=978-1-4666-0982-2|page=225}}</ref><ref name=\"Pacific2004\">{{cite book|author=United Nations. Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific|title=Good Practices in Information and Communication Technology Policies in Asia and the Pacific|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=N4AQ453g_voC&pg=PA64|year=2004|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-120412-4|pages=64}}</ref> A CDMA standard was adopted as the national wireless standard in Korea in May 1993<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> with commercial CDMA networks being launched in 1996.<ref name=\"Pacific2004\"/><ref name=\"Reddick2012\"/> CDMA networks were also launched in Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, India, and Venezuela.<ref name=\"DrakeWilson2008\">{{cite book|first1=William|last1=Drake|first2=Ernest|last2=Wilson|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vw2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-30931-8|pages=167}}</ref><ref name=\"HarperBuress2008\">{{cite book|first1=Alvin|last1=Harper|first2=Raymond|last2=Buress|title=Mobile Telephones: Networks, Applications, and Performance|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tG3wJZtq8PgC&pg=PA48|year=2008|publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=978-1-60456-436-5|pages=48}}</ref> Qualcomm entered the Russian and Latin American markets in 2005.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> By 2007, Qualcomm's technology was in cell phone networks in more than 105 countries.<ref name=\"DrakeWilson2008\"/> Qualcomm also formed licensing agreements with [[Nokia]] in Europe, [[Nortel]] in Canada, and with [[Matsushita]] and [[Mitsubishi]] in Japan.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>\n \nQualcomm entered the Chinese market through a partnership with [[China Unicom]] in 2000,<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> which launched the first CDMA-based network in China in 2003.<ref name=\"HarperBuress2008\"/> China became a major market for Qualcomm's semiconductor products, representing more than fifty percent of its revenues,<ref name=\"reutreur\">{{cite news|title=China regulator determines Qualcomm has monopoly: state-run newspaper|first=Paul|last=Carsten|first2=Michael|last2=Martina|date=July 24, 2014|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/24/us-qualcomm-china-idUSKBN0FT0AU20140724|accessdate=August 7, 2014|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> but also the source of many legal disputes regarding Qualcomm's intellectual property.<ref name=\"wsjsj\"/> By 2007, $500 million of Qualcomm's annual revenues were coming from Korean manufacturers.<ref name=\"OhLarson2011\">{{cite book|first1=Myung|last1=Oh|first2=James|last2=Larson|title=Digital Development in Korea: Building an Information Society|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OZpdqhsPHnQC&pg=PA97|date=March 14, 2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-81313-9|pages=97}}</ref>\n \n====Manufacturing====\nInitially, Qualcomm's manufacturing operations were limited to a small ASIC design and manufacturing team to support the Omnitracs system.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm was forced to expand into manufacturing in the 1990s in order to produce the hardware carriers needed to implement CDMA networks that used Qualcomm's intellectual property.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm's first large manufacturing project was in May 1993, in a deal to provide 36,000 CDMA phones to [[US West]].<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\"/>\n \nFor a time, Qualcomm experienced delays and other manufacturing problems, because it was in-experienced with mass manufacturing.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> In 1994, Qualcomm partnered with [[Northern Telecom]] and formed a joint partnership with [[Sony]], in order to leverage their manufacturing expertise.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/> [[Nokia]], [[Samsung]] and [[Motorola]] introduced their own CDMA phones in 1997.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\">{{cite book|author=Guy Klemens|title=The Cellphone: The History and Technology of the Gadget That Changed the World|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3WNnM7iZF_QC&pg=PA131|date=September 9, 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5996-4|pages=131\u2013132}}</ref> Qualcomm's manufacturing business was losing money due to large capital equipment costs and declining prices caused by competition.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/><ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/><ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Also, in March 1997, after Qualcomm introduced its Q phone, [[Motorola]] initiated a lawsuit (settled out of court in 2000) for allegedly copying the design of its Startac phone.<ref name=\"Inc.1997\">{{cite book|first=Marc|last=Ferranti|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MToEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44|date=March 24, 1997|newspaper=InfoWorld|page=44|accessdate=August 9, 2014|title=Motorola claims patent infringement by Qualcomm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Motorola claims patent infringement by Qualcomm|newspaper=Infoworld|date=March 24, 1997|first=Marc|last=Ferranti}}</reF>\n \nIn December 1999, Qualcomm sold its manufacturing interests to Kyocera Corporation, a Japanese CDMA manufacturer and Qualcomm licensee.<ref name=\u201cpike\">{{cite news\n|title=Qualcomm sells CDMA phone division to Kyocera\n|first=Loring\n|last=Wirbel\n|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times\n|date=December 22, 1999\n|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1230103\n|accessdate=July 23, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=Qualcomm, Kyocera strike deal for handset business\n|first=\n|last=\n|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times\n|date=December 22, 1999\n|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1124095\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> Qualcomm's infrastructure division was sold to competitor Ericsson in 1999 as part of an out-of-court agreement for a CDMA patent dispute that started in 1996.<reF name=\"thirteen\">{{Cite news|last=Alleven|first=Monica|title=Ericsson Tangles With Qualcomm|newspaper=Wireless Week|date=November 29, 1999|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/2587634/ericsson-tangles-qualcomm|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wireless giants get connected|publisher=The Associated Press|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&amp;dat=19990326&amp;id=NVBYAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=DY4DAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=4436,2341517|date=March 26, 1999|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> The sale of the infrastructure division marked the beginning of an increase in Qualcomm's stock price and stronger financial performance, but many of the 1,200 employees involved were discontent with working for a competitor and losing their stock options.<reF name=\"thirteen\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Alleven|first=Monica|title=Qualcomm, Unhappy Employees Try Mediation|newspaper=Wireless Week|date=May 8, 2000|accessdate=June 6, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/3106407/qualcomm-unhappy-employees-try-mediation}}</ref> This led to a protracted legal dispute regarding employee stock options, resulting in $74 million in settlements by 2005.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>\n \n===3G===\n3G standards were expected to force prior TDMA carriers onto CDMA, in order to meet 3G bandwidth goals.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\">{{cite book|author1=William J. Drake|author2=Ernest J. Wilson (III.)|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5A2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA166|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-04251-2|pages=166}}</ref><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> The two largest GSM manufacturers, Nokia and Ericsson, advocated for a greater role for GSM,<ref name=\"TaplinWakui2006\">{{cite book|author1=Ruth Taplin|author2=Masako Wakui|title=Japanese Telecommunications: Market and Policy in Transition|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C6Z-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|date=February 1, 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-20815-9|pages=124}}</ref> in order to negotiate lower royalty prices from Qualcomm.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> In 1998, the [[European Telecommunications Standards Institute]] (ETSI) voted in support of the WCDMA standard, which relied less on Qualcomm's CDMA patents.<ref name=\"Association2010\">{{cite book|author=Information Resources Management Association|title=Networking and Telecommunications: Concepts, Methodologies, Tools, and Applications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=DYWB5nMjB38C&pg=PA240|date=January 2010|publisher=Idea Group Inc (IGI)|isbn=978-1-60566-987-8|pages=240}}</ref> Qualcomm responded by refusing to license its intellectual property for the standard.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/>\n \nThe [[Telecommunications Industry Association]] (TIA) and the Third Generation Partnership Program 2, advocated for a competing CDMA-2000 standard developed primarily by Qualcomm.<ref name=\"ChenGuizani2006\">{{cite book|author1=Hsiao-Hwa Chen|author2=Mohsen Guizani|title=Next Generation Wireless Systems and Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MVEaQ7TRBTMC&pg=PA122|date=May 1, 2006|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-02435-5|pages=122}}</ref><ref name=\"Unhelkar2006\">{{cite book|author=Bhuvan Unhelkar|title=Handbook of Research in Mobile Business: Technical, Methodological and Social Perspectives|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IvHcyXDzu4oC&pg=PA150|date=January 1, 2006|publisher=Idea Group Inc (IGI)|isbn=978-1-59140-818-5|pages=150}}</ref> American and European politicians advocated for the CDMA-2000 and WCDMA standards respectively.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> The ITU said it would exclude Qualcomm's CDMA technology from the 3G standards entirely if a patent dispute over the technology with Ericsson was not resolved.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Lennon2007\"/> The two reached an agreement out-of-court in 1999, one month before a deadline set by the ITU. Both companies agreed to cross-license their technology to each other<ref name=\"Lennon2007\">{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Lennon|title=Drafting Technology Patent License Agreements|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=i3MLYUjRWisC&pg=SA1-PA31|year=2007|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-6748-1|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>{{RP|30}} and to work together on 3G standards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ericsson/Qualcomm bitter feud ends|newspaper=Telephony|date=March 29, 1999|accessdate=June 6, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/2183790/ericsson-qualcomm-bitter-feud-ends|last=Gohring|first=Nancy}}</ref>\n \nA compromise was eventually reached whereby the ITU would initially endorse three standards: CDMA2000 1X, WCDMA and TD-SCDMA.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\">{{cite book|author1=William J. Drake|author2=Ernest J. Wilson (III.)|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5A2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA166|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-04251-2|pages=166}}</ref> Qualcomm agreed to license its CDMA patents for variants such as WCDMA.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> There were 240 million CDMA 3G subscribers by 2004 and 143 carriers in 67 countries by 2005.<ref name=\"Chen2007\"/> Qualcomm claimed to own 38 percent of WCDMA's essential patents, whereas European GSM interests sponsored a research paper allegigng Qualcomm only owned 19 percent.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/>\n \nQualcomm consolidated its interests in telecommunications carriers, such as [[Cricket Communications]] and [[Pegaso]] into a holding company, [[Leap Wireless]], in 1998.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Calls Off a Spinoff and Realigns Management|first=Chris|last=Gaither|date=July 25, 2001|newspaper=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/25/business/technology-qualcomm-calls-off-a-spinoff-and-realigns-management.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> Leap was spun-off later that year<Ref name=\"jkopys\"/> and sold to [[AT&T]] in 2014.<Ref name=\"jkopys\">{{cite news|title=Leap Wireless Reports $640.8M Loss for 2013 as Sale to AT&T Looms|first=Mike|last=Allen|date=March 9, 2014|url=http://sdbj.com/news/2014/mar/09/leap-wireless-reports-6408m-loss-2013-sale-t-looms/|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF>\n \n===4G===\nQualcomm initially advocated for the CDMA-based [[Ultra Mobile Broadband]] (UMB) standard for fourth generation wireless networks.<ref name=\"Unhelkar2009\">{{cite book|author=Bhuvan Unhelkar|title=Mobile Enterprise Transition and Management|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OPXZFkBzvd8C&pg=PA132|date=June 25, 2009|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-7828-2|pages=132}}</ref> UMB wasn't backwards compatible with prior CDMA networks and didn't operate as well in narrow bandwidths as the LTE (long-term evolution) standard. No cellular networks adopted UMB.<ref name=\"Cox2012\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Cox|title=An Introduction to LTE: LTE, LTE-Advanced, SAE and 4G Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=q04NlHWgnfYC&pg=PA16|date=February 28, 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-94281-8|pages=16}}</ref> Qualcomm halted development of UMB in 2005 and decided to support the LTE standard,<ref name=\"Korhonen2014\">{{cite book|author=Juha Korhonen|title=Introduction to 4G Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=lutPAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26|date=March 1, 2014|publisher=Artech House|isbn=978-1-60807-699-4|pages=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm halts UMB project, sees no major job cuts|first=Sinead|last=Carew|date=November 13, 2008|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/11/13/us-qualcomm-umb-idUSTRE4AC7M720081113|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> even though it didn't rely as heavily on Qualcomm patents.<ref>{{cite news|title=What's next for Qualcomm?|first=Jessi|last=Hempel|date=June 24, 2009|url=http://cnnfn.cnn.com/2009/06/23/technology/qualcomm_wireless_chips_new_gadgets.fortune/index.htm?postversion=2009062406|newspaper=Fortune Magazine|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Then, Qualcomm purchased LTE-related patents through acquisitions.<ref name=\"Coll2013\">{{cite book|author=Eric Coll|title=Telecom, Datacom and Networking for Non-Engineers: Reference Book - CTNS Study Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jZPTNW--k40C&pg=PA115|date=September 9, 2013|publisher=Teracom Training Institute|isbn=978-1-894887-05-2|pages=115}}</ref> By 2012, Qualcomm held 81 seminal patents used in 4G LTE standards, or 12.46 percent.<ref name=\"Reed 2012\">{{cite web | last=Reed | first=Brad | title=Watch out Apple: Samsung, Qualcomm positioned to dominate LTE patent wars | website=Network World | date=April 26, 2012 | url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2188067/wireless/watch-out-apple--samsung--qualcomm-positioned-to-dominate-lte-patent-wars.html | accessdate=October 29, 2015}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm also became more focused on using its intellectual property to manufacture semiconductors in a [[fabless manufacturing]] model.<ref>{{cite news|DUPLICATE-title=Can Samsung Get Qualcomm in LTE Market?|title=Casualty is not Qualcomm but Broadcom|first=Junko|last=Yoshida|date=July 11, 2014|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1323072|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> A VLSI Technology Organization division was founded in 2004, followed by a DFX group in 2006, which did more of the manufacturing design in-house.<ref name=\"eetimesss\">{{cite news|title=Fabless Qualcomm zooms to next node|first=Mark|last=LaPedus|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=November 27, 2006|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1164472|accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm announced it was developing the [[Scorpion (CPU)|Scorpion]] [[central processing unit]] (CPU) for mobile devices in November 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Snapdragon seeds Qualcomm's future|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=June 4, 2007|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1247637|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</reF><ref name=\"djabnf\">{{cite news|title=Analysis: Qualcomm's 1 GHz ARM \"Snapdragon\"|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1275485|publisher=Electronic Engineering Times|accessdate=October 2, 2014|author=BDTI|date=December 5, 2007}}</reF> This was followed by the first shipments of the [[Snapdragon (system on chip)|Snapdragon]] system-on-chip product, which includes a CPU, GPS, graphics processing unit, camera support and other software and semiconductors,<Ref name=\"extreme\">{{cite news|title=How Qualcomm's Snapdragon ARM chips are unique|first=Ryan|last=Whitwam|date=August 26, 2011|url=http://www.extremetech.com/mobile/94064-how-qualcomms-snapdragon-arm-chips-are-unique|publisher=ExtremeTech|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref> in November 2007.<ref name=\"cnet\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/toshiba-handheld-hits-1ghz-with-snapdragon/|accessdate=October 2, 2014|publisher=CNET|date=February 3, 2009|first=Brooke|last=Crothers|title=Toshiba handheld hits 1GHz with 'Snapdragon'}}</ref> The [[Gobi]] family of modems for portable devices was released in 2008.<ref name=\"giz announcement\">{{ cite news  | url = http://gizmodo.com/#!314704/qualcomm-gobi-3g-chip-goes-both-ways-ev+do-or-hsdpa\n | title = Qualcomm Gobi 3G Chip Goes Both Ways: EV-DO or HSDPA\n | accessdate =February 2, 2011\n | publisher = gizmodo.com\n|first=Matt\n|last= Buchanan }}\n</ref><ref name=\"engadget announcement\">{{ cite web  | url = http://www.engadget.com/2007/10/24/qualcomms-dual-3g-gobi-chip-handles-ev-do-and-hspa/\n | title = Qualcomm's dual-3G Gobi chip handles EV-DO and HSPA -- Engadget\n | accessdate = February 11, 2011\n | publisher = engadget.com\n|date=October 24, 2007\n|first=Darren\n|last=Murph}}\n</ref> Gobi modems were embedded in many laptop brands<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's new Gobi: A WiMax and Wi-Fi killer?|first=Matt|last=Hamblen|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=August 18, 2014|url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9073838/Qualcomm_s_new_Gobi_A_WiMax_and_Wi_Fi_killer_|newspaper=Computerworld}}</ref><Ref>{{cite news|title=Panasonic taps Qualcomm Gobi for broadband data|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=September 11, 2008|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1169259|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref> and Snapdragon system on chips were embedded into most Android devices.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm to buy Atheros for $3.2 billion|date=January 6, 2011|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/05/AR2011010506338.html|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm won a government auction in India in 2010 for $1 billion in spectrum and licenses from which to offer broadband services. It formed four joint ventures with Indian holding companies for this purpose. A 49 percent stake in the holding companies was acquired by [[Bharti Enterprises|Bharti]] in May 2012 and the remaining was acquired in October 2012<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Exits India Broadband Venture|last=Krishna|first=Jai|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=October 18, 2013|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304864504579143020414211610|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> by AT&T.<ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T closes on Leap acquisition, with conditions|first=Dan|last=Meyer|date=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.rcrwireless.com/20140314/carriers/att-closes-on-leap-acquisition-with-conditions|publisher=RCR Wireless|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</reF>\n \n===5G===\nAccording to <i>Fortune Magazine</i>, Qualcomm has been developing technologies for future 5G standards in three areas: radios that would use bandwidth from any network it has access to, creating larger ranges of spectrum by combining smaller pieces, and a set of services for [[internet of things]] applications.<ref name=\"Higginbotham 2015\">{{cite news| last=Higginbotham | first=Stacey | title=Qualcomm readies itself for 5G with these 3 tech breakthroughs | newspaper=Fortune | date=October 14, 2015 | url=http://fortune.com/2015/10/14/qualcomm-5g/ | accessdate=October 18, 2015}}</ref> Qualcomm's first 5G modem chip was announced in October 2016<ref name=\"Captain 2016\">{{cite web | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=The Wild Technology That Will Make 5G Wireless Work | website=Fast Company | date=October 18, 2016 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3064144/the-wild-technology-that-will-make-5g-wireless-work | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> and a prototype was demonstrated in October 2017.<ref name=\"BBC News 2017\">{{cite web | title=5G high-speed data 'milestone' claimed | website=BBC News | date=October 17, 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41652967 | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm's first 5G antennas were announced in July 2018.<ref name=\"Smith 2018\">{{cite web | last=Smith | first=Ryan | title=Qualcomm Announces Their First 5G mmWave Antenna Module: QTM052, Coming This Year | website=AnandTech | date=2018-07-23 | url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/13106/qualcomm-announces-their-first-5g-mmwave-antenna-module-qtm052-coming-this-year | accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref> As of 2018, Qualcomm has partnerships with 19 mobile device manufacturers and 18 carriers to commercialize 5G technology.<ref name=\"Horwitz 2018\">{{cite web | last=Horwitz | first=Jeremy | title=Qualcomm signs 19 phone makers and 18 carriers for global 5G launches in 2019 | website=VentureBeat | date=February 8, 2018 | url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/08/qualcomm-signs-19-phone-makers-and-18-carriers-for-global-5g-launches-in-2019/ | accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> By late 2019, several phone were being sold with Qualcomm's 5G technology incorporated.<ref name=\"Nellis 2019\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=Qualcomm-Samsung axis brings 5G to the masses as Huawei struggles | website=U.S. | date=September 6, 2019 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-5g-idUSKCN1VR1HT | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n \n==Software and other technology==\n===Early software===\nQualcomm acquired an email application called [[Eudora (email client)|Eudora]] in 1991.<ref name=\"merc\">{{cite news|newspaper=San Jose Mercury News|title=Technology Testdrive Column|date=February 27, 2000 | last=Langberg|first= Mike}}</ref> By 1996, Eudora was installed on 63 percent of PCs.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Utilities get with the e-mail program\n|first=Peter\n|last=Grad\n|newspaper=The Record\n|date=November 25, 1996\n|url=\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> [[Microsoft Outlook]] eclipsed Eudora, since it was provided for free by default on Windows-based machines.<ref name=\"aplip\">{{cite news\n|title=Good-Bye Eudora\n|first=\n|last=\n|publisher=Associated Press\n|date=October 21, 2006\n|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=20061021&id=-HFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mgQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3308,1348487\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> By 2003 Qualcomm's Eudora was the most popular alternative to Microsoft Outlook, but still had only a five percent share of the market.<ref name=\"alt\">{{cite news\n|title=Alternativees can liberate you form Microsoft e-mail software\n|first=\n|last=\n|newspaper=Dallas Morning News\n|date=September 1, 2003\n|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=20030901&id=xrRQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YV4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2307,428729\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> Software development for Eudora was retired in 2006.<ref name=\"aplip\"/>\n \nIn 2001, Qualcomm introduced [[Binary Runtime Environment for Wireless|Brew]], a smartphone app development service<ref name=\"whatisbrew\">{{cite news|title=BREW (Binary Runtime Environment for Wireless)|first=Margaret|last=Rouse|url=http://searchmobilecomputing.techtarget.com/definition/BREW|publisher=TechTarget}}</ref><ref name=\"Etoh2005\"/><ref name=\"daghniouhd\">{{cite news|title=A fresh outlook on 3G|last1=Carroll|first1=Kelly|newspaper=Telephony|date=April 16, 2001|url=http://connectedplanetonline.com/mag/telecom_fresh_outlook/|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> with APIs to access contacts, billing, app-stores, or multimedia on the phone.<ref name=\"Etoh2005\">{{cite book|author=Minoru Etoh|title=Next Generation Mobile Systems: 3G & Beyond|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3R-Hc106lb8C&pg=PA199|date=August 5, 2005|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-09152-4|pages=199}}</ref> South Korean carrier KTFreeTel was the first to adopt the Brew system in November 2001, followed by Verizon in March 2002<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Unveils its new BREW|first=Brad|last=Graves|date=March 18, 2002|url=http://san-diego-business-journal.vlex.com/vid/qualcomm-brew-verizon-nationwide-rollout-54435867|accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref> for its \"Get it Now\" program. There were 2.5 million Brew users by the end of 2002 and 73 million in 2003.<ref name=\"Chen2007\"/>\n \n===Other technology===\nIn 2004, Qualcomm created a [[MediaFLO]] subsidiary to bring its FLO (forward link only) specification to market. Qualcomm built an $800 million MediaFLO network of cell towers to supplement carrier networks with one that is designed for multimedia.<ref name=\"yugdtsuobdajf\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Re-Imagines Mobile Media|first=Kevin|last=Fitchard|url=http://connectedplanetonline.com/mag/telecom_qualcomm_reimagines_mobile/|newspaper=Connected Planet|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=November 8, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Invests In TV Broadcasts Over Cellphones|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=November 2, 2004|accessdate=August 10, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB109935045322361616}}</reF> In comparison to cellular towers that provide two-way communications with each cell phone individually, MediaFLO towers would broadcast multimedia content to mobile phones in a one-way broadcast.<ref name=\"dajobiurebv\">{{cite news|title=Go with the FLO?|date=February 27, 2007|url=http://www.wirelessweek.com/news/2007/02/go-w-ith-flo|first=Karen|last=Brown|accessdate=August 10, 2014|newspaper=Wireless Week}}</ref><ref name=\"apdia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10286552/ns/technology_and_science-wireless/t/verizon-offer-broadcast-tv-over-cell-phones/#.U-fTQ4BdWxE|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=August 10, 2014|date=December 1, 2005|title=Verizon to offer broadcast TV over cell phones}}</reF> Qualcomm also sold FLO-based semiconductors and licenses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitchard|first=Kevin|title=TV wars go wireless|newspaper=Telephony|date=September 26, 2005|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/15075230/qualcomm-eyes-programming-phones|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|first=Brad|last=Graves|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=November 2004|title=Qualcomm Eyes Programming For Phones}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm created the FLO Forum standards group with 15 industry participants in July 2005.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=September 12, 2005|title=Mobile-TV on-ramp under construction -- But lack of chip sets, profusion of net options could bring delays|first=Rick|last=Merritt|url=http://business.highbeam.com/3094/article-1G1-136081199/mobiletv-ramp-under-construction-but-lack-chip-sets|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</reF> Verizon was the first carrier to partner with MediaFlo in December 2005<ref name=\"apdia\"/> for its Verizon Wireless' V Cast TV,<Ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.cnet.com/Verizon-offers-live-TV-on-cell-phones/2100-1039_3-6147908.html|publisher=CNET|accessdate=August 10, 2014|date=January 7, 2007|title=Verizon offers live TV on cell phones|first=Marguerite|last=Reardon }}</ref> which was followed by the AT&T Mobile TV service a couple months later.<ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T's MediaFLO TV coming in May|first=Stephen|last=Lawson|publisher=IDG|date=Mar 28, 2008|accessdate=August 10, 2014|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2285013/network-security/at-t-s-mediaflo-tv-coming-in-may.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T airs TV service on new phones|first=Peter|last=Svensson|publisher=Associated Press|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/story?id=4773117|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> The MediaFlo service was launched on Super Bowl Sunday in 2007.<ref name=\"unique13\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Suspends Flo Mobile TV Sales|first=Priya|last=Ganapati|publisher=WIRED|date=October 5, 2010|url=http://www.wired.com/2010/10/qualcomm-cancels-flo-tv/|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Despite the interest the service got among carriers, it was unpopular among consumers.<ref name=\"unique13\"/><ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><Ref name=\"uniquename\"/> The service required users to pay for a subscription and have phones that were equipped with special semiconductors.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\">{{cite news|title=Why Qualcomm thinks LTE-broadcast will work where FLO TV failed|first=Kevin|last=Kitchard|date=April 9, 2014|publisher=Giga Om|url=http://gigaom.com/2013/04/09/why-qualcomm-thinks-lte-broadcast-will-work-where-flo-tv-failed/|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF><Ref name=\"uniquename\"/> The service was discontinued in 2011 and its spectrum was sold to AT&T for $1.93 billion.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><Ref name=\"uniquename\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Wants To Dump \"MediaFLO\" Mobile TV Business No One Watches|first=Dan|last=Frommer|date=July 22, 2010|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/qualcomm-wants-to-dump-its-mediaflo-mobile-tv-business-2010-7#ixzz39wzl7jAE|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm rebooted the effort in 2013 with LTE Broadcast, which uses pre-existing cell towers to broadcast select content locally on a dedicated spectrum, such as during major sporting events.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=LTE broadcast may help Qualcomm salvage Flo TV|newspaper=PC World|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2030367/lte-broadcast-may-help-qualcomm-salvage-flo-tv.html|first=Stephen|last=Lawson|accessdate=August 12, 2014|date=March 19, 2013}}</reF>\n \nBased on technology acquired from Iridigm in 2004 for $170 million,<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2007/06/01/100050991/ |title=Product design, nature's way |last=Watters |first=Ethan |work=CNNMoney |publisher=Cable News Network |date=June 12, 2007}}</ref> Qualcomm began commercializing [[Interferometric modulator display|Mirasol]] displays in 2007, which was expanded into eight products in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Screens Pack Visual Punch With Scant Power|first=Brad|last=Graves|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=June 9, 2008}}</reF> Mirasol uses natural light shining on a screen to provide lighting for the display, rather a backlight, in order to reduce power consumption.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Bright Low-Power Screen|first=Cliff|last=Edwards|date=April 28, 2010|newspaper=Businessweek|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2010-04-28/qualcomms-bright-low-power-screen|accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref> The amount of space between the surface of the display and a mirror within a 10 micron-wide \"interferometric modulator\" determines the color of the reflected light.<ref>{{cite news|title=E-Reader Display Shows Vibrant Color Video|first=Tom|last=Simonite|date=November 15, 2011|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/news/426120/e-reader-display-shows-vibrant-color-video/|accessdate=October 24, 2014|newspaper=Technology Review}}</ref> Mirasol was eventually closed down after an attempt to revive it in 2013 in Toq watches.<ref name=\"Captain 2017\">{{cite web | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=The Everything Chip: Qualcomm\u2019s Plan To Power Drones, VR, Cars, PCs, And More | website=Fast Company | date=January 10, 2017 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3066849/qualcomm-drones-vr-cars-satellites | accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn June 2011, Qualcomm introduced [[AllJoyn]], a wireless standard for communicating between devices like cell phones, televisions, air-conditioners, and refrigerators.<ref name=\"alljoynnww\">{{cite news|newspaper=Network World|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2456421/internet-of-things/a-guide-to-the-confusing-internet-of-things-standards-world.html|title=A guide to the confusing Internet of Things standards world|first=Colin|last=Neagle}}</ref><Ref name=\"oneilyady\">{{cite news|title=At CES, the Internet of Everything will Speak Alljoyn|first=Leah|last=Hunter|newspaper=Fast Company|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3024203/innovation-agents/at-ces-the-internet-of-everything-will-be-powered-by-alljoyn|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"FitzekKatz2013\">{{cite book|author1=Frank H. P. Fitzek|author2=Marcos D. Katz|title=Mobile Clouds: Exploiting Distributed Resources in Wireless, Mobile and Social Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jmlXAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT211|date=December 11, 2013|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-80140-6|pages=211}}</ref> The Alljoyn technology was donated to the [[Linux Foundation]] in December 2013. Qualcomm and the Linux Foundation then formed the Allseen Alliance to administer the standard<ref name=\"alljoynnww\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Brad|last=Graves|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=January 6, 2014|title=Internet of Things Set to Bring Lots of Connections, Opportunity}}</ref> and Qualcomm developed products that used the AllJoyn standard<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's smartwatch is Toq of the town|first=John|last=Shinal|newspaper=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/MONEY/usaedition/2013-09-05-Qualcomm-is-seeding-market-for-wearable-devices_ST_U.htm|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm\u2019s Toq Smartwatch Needs More Time|date=December 26, 2013|url=http://allthingsd.com/20131226/qualcomms-toq-smartwatch-needs-more-time/|publisher=AllThingsD|accessdate=August 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Timex launches smartwatch with Qualcomm technology|first=Noel|last=Randewich|date=August 5, 2014|publisher=Reuters|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/06/us-timex-qualcomm-idUSKBN0G600520140806|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In December 2011, Qualcomm formed a healthcare subsidiary called Qualcomm Life. Simultaneously, the subsidiary released a cloud-based service for managing clinical data called 2net and the Qualcomm Life Fund, which invests in wireless healthcare technology companies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Subsidiary Focuses on Mobile Medical Data|url=http://www.informationweek.com/mobile/qualcomm-subsidiary-focuses-on-mobile-medical-data/d/d-id/1101744?|newspaper=InformationWeek|accessdate=October 24, 2014|date=December 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Launches Mobile Health Company, New Cloud Medical Data Platform|first=Brian|last=Horowitz|url=http://www.eweek.com/c/a/Health-Care-IT/Qualcomm-Launches-Mobile-Health-Company-New-Cloud-Medical-Data-Platform-435345/|newspaper=eWeek}}</ref> The subsidiary doubled its employee-count by acquiring HealthyCircles Inc., a healthcare IT company, the following May.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Acquires medical Software Maker|first=Meghana|last=Keshavan|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=March 11, 2013}}</ref> Qualcomm life was later sold to a private equity firm, Francisco Partners, in 2019.<ref name=\"MobiHealthNews 2019\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Life acquired by PE firm Francisco Partners, will spin off under new name | website=MobiHealthNews | date=February 11, 2019 | url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/qualcomm-life-acquired-pe-firm-francisco-partners-will-spin-under-new-name | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n \n===Recent developments===\nIn 2016, Qualcomm developed its first beta processor chip for servers and PCs called \u201cServer Development Platform\u201d and sent samples for testing.<ref name=\"dalihgeahrocin\">{{cite news | first=Aaron|last=Tilley|title=Qualcomm Launches The First 10nm Server Chip | newspaper=Forbes | date=December 7, 2016 | url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2016/12/07/qualcomm-launches-the-first-10nm-server-chip/#50f9ae034b62 | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In January 2017, a second generation data center and PC server chip called Centriq 2400 was released.<ref name=\"dalihgeahrocin\"/> <i>PC Magazine</i> said the release was \"historic\" for Qualcomm, because it was a new market segment for the company.<ref name=\"Shah 2016\">{{cite web | last=Shah | first=Agam | title=Sleeping giant Qualcomm awakens with aim to crush Intel at its own game | website=PCWorld | date=December 12, 2016 | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/3149749/components-processors/sleeping-giant-qualcomm-awakens-with-aim-to-crush-intel-at-its-own-game.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also created a Qualcomm Datacenter Technologies subsidiary to focus on the PCs and servers market.<ref name=\"eWeek.com 2016\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Names Upcoming Server Family Centriq | website=eWeek.com | date=August 19, 2016 | url=http://www.eweek.com/servers/qualcomm-names-upcoming-server-family-centriq.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Qualcomm introduced embedded technology for 3D cameras intended for augmented reality apps.<ref name=\"Captain 2017b\">{{cite news | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=Qualcomm\u2019s New Camera Will Give Smartphones 3D Vision | newspaper=Fast Company | date=August 15, 2017 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40451913/qualcomms-new-camera-will-give-smartphones-3d-vision | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm is also developing and demonstrating laptop processors and other parts, as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Takes Another Shot at Ending Intel PC Stranglehold | website=Bloomberg|first=Ian|last=King | date=December 5, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-05/qualcomm-takes-another-shot-at-breaking-intel-pc-stranglehold | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2000, Qualcomm formed a joint venture with [[Ford Motor Company|FORD]] called Wingcast, which created [[telematics]] equipment for cars, but was unsuccessful and closed down two years later.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Ford, Qualcomm form auto-telecom venture|publisher=The Associated Press|first=Justin|last=Hyde|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&amp;dat=20000801&amp;id=4oUNAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=aW8DAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=5050,221397|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Lewis|date=June 4, 2002|title=Ford Grounds Its Wingcast Venture|url=http://www.forbes.com/2002/06/04/0604telematics.html|accessdate=October 24, 2014|newspaper=Forbes}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Charny |date=June 4, 2002|url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/qualcomm-grounds-wingcast-venture/123199|title=Qualcomm grounds Wingcast venture|publisher=ZDNet|accessdate=October 24, 2014 }}</reF> Qualcomm acquired the wireless electric car charging company, HaloIPT, in November 2011<Ref>{{cite news|title=University sells off wireless technology|first=Catherine|last=Harris|newspaper=The Press|date=November 10, 2011|page=A.14}}</ref> and later sold the company to WiTricity in February 2019.<ref name=\"Sawers 2019\">{{cite web | last=Sawers | first=Paul | title=WiTricity acquires Qualcomm Halo to accelerate wireless charging for electric vehicles | website=VentureBeat | date=February 11, 2019 | url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/02/11/witricity-acquires-qualcomm-halo-to-accelerate-wireless-charging-for-electric-vehicles/ | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Qualcomm also started introducing Snapdragon system-on-chips<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm brings its Snapdragon chip to the car|first=James|last=Niccolai|publisher=IDG News Service|date=January 6, 2014|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1320552&page_number=1|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</ref> and Gobi modems<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm launches 64-bit chips for high-end phones at MWC 2014|first=Shara|last=Tibken|date=February 23, 2014|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-launches-64-bit-chips-for-high-end-phones-at-mwc-2014/|publisher=CNET|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</reF> and other software or semiconductor products for self-driving cars and modern in-car computers.<ref name=\"Velazco 2017\">{{cite web | last=Velazco | first=Chris | title=Qualcomm wants to make smarter cars by sharing sensor data | website=Engadget | date=January 3, 2017 | url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/03/qualcomm-wants-to-make-smarter-cars-by-sharing-sensor-data/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Condon 2017\">{{cite web | last=Condon | first=Stephanie | title=New Qualcomm auto chipset advances vehicle-to-everything communications | website=ZDNet | date=August 31, 2017 | url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/new-qualcomm-auto-chipset-advances-vehicle-to-everything-communications/ | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Patents and patent disputes==\nAs of 2017, Qualcomm owns more than 130,000 current or pending patents.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\">{{cite web | last=Chafkin | first=Max | last2=King | first2=Ian | title=Apple and Qualcomm\u2019s Billion-Dollar War Over an $18 Part | website=Bloomberg.com | date=October 4, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-04/apple-and-qualcomm-s-billion-dollar-war-over-an-18-part | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> By the early 2000s, Qualcomm had more than 1,000 patents.<ref name=\"eight\">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&amp;dat=20000916&amp;id=TrkeAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=8s8EAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=6534,472942|title=Qualcomm streamlines for wireless battle|first=Michael|last=White|date=September 16, 2000|accessdate=June 5, 2014|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&amp;dat=20000726&amp;id=jbM0AAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=OiEGAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=3257,3098830|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 26, 2000|accessdate=June 3, 2014|title=Qualcomm spinning off businesses}}</ref> As the sole early investor in CDMA research and development, Qualcomm's patent portfolio contains much of the intellectual property that is essential to CDMA technologies.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/>\n \nSince many of Qualcomm's patents are part of an industry standard, the company has agreed to license those patents under \u201cfair, reasonable, and non-discriminatory\u201d terms.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> Qualcomm's royalties come out to about 5% or $30 per mobile device.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\"/> According to Fortune Magazine, this is about 5-10 times more than what is typically charged by other patent-holders.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> Qualcomm says its patents are more expensive because they are more important and its pricing is within the range of common licensing practices.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> However, competitors, clients, and regulators often allege Qualcomm charges unreasonable rates or engages in unfair competition for mandatory patents.<ref name=\"Delta2009\">{{cite book|first=George|last=Delta|title=Law of the Internet|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0eMafpE7A0YC&pg=RA1-SA7-PA23|year=2009|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-7559-2|pages=1|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \n===Broadcom===\nIn 2005, Broadcom and Qualcomm were unable to reach an agreement on cross-licensing their intellectual property,<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm punished with phone import ban|first=Kathryn|last=Balint|date=June 8, 2007|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070608/news_1n8qualcomm.html|newspaper=Union-Tribune San Diego|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> and Broadcom sued Qualcomm alleging it was breach ten Broadcom patents.<ref name=\"wsjwsjwsjjj\">{{cite news|title=Broadcom Levels Suit on Qualcomm|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB111651086084838082|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=May 20, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Mei2012\">{{cite book|first=Lei|last=Mei|title=Conducting Business in China: An Intellectual Property Perspective|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IelMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA161|date=November 8, 2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-976022-0|pages=161}}</ref> Broadcom asked the International Trade Commission to prohibit importing the affected technology.<ref name=\"wsjwsjwsjjj\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom seeks injunction in intellectual property war|newspaper=Financial Times|date=May 20, 2005|first=Simon|last=London|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/5b00902c-c8cb-11d9-87c9-00000e2511c8.html#axzz39iO1EwRz|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> A separate lawsuit alleged Qualcomm was threatening to withhold UMTS patent licenses against manufacturers that bought their semiconductors from competitors, in violation of the standards agreement.<ref name=\"Stern2005\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Suit by Broadcom Says Qualcomm Seeks a Monopoly|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 6, 2005|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB112056555346377303|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Stern2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Stern|first1=R.H.|title=Standardization skullduggery update: UMTS standard|journal=IEEE Micro|volume=25|issue=4|year=2005|pages=73\u201376|issn=0272-1732|doi=10.1109/MM.2005.76}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rival Names Qualcomm in Antitrust Suit|publisher=Bloomberg|date=July 6, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/06/technology/06broadcom.html?_r=0|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm alleged Broadcom was using litigation as a negotiation tactic and that it would respond with its own lawsuits.<ref name=\"Stern2005\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Simons|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom Fight Stands to Be Costly|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=July 18, 2005|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/17871652/qualcomm-broadcom-fight-stands-be-costly}}</ref> Qualcomm sued Broadcom, alleging it was using seven Qualcomm patents without permission.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm sues Broadcom over patents|first=Grant|last=Gross|publisher=IDG News Service|date=July 11, 2005|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2322556/network-security/qualcomm-sues-broadcom-over-patents.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> By late 2006, more than 20 lawsuits had been filed between the two parties and both sides claimed to be winning.<ref name=\"bwuyda\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom Face Off|first1=Ron|last1=Grover|first2=Olga|last2=Kharif|date=October 3, 2006|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2006-10-03/qualcomm-broadcom-face-off|newspaper=BusinessWeek|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2006, a New Jersey court judge ruled that Qualcomm's patent monopoly was an inherit aspect of creating industry standards and that Qualcomm's pricing practices were lawful.<ref name=\"bwuyda\"/><ref name=\"Stern2006\">{{cite journal|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=1709817&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fiel5%2F40%2F36071%2F01709817.pdf%3Farnumber%3D1709817|accessdate=August 9, 2014|last1=Stern|first1=R.|title=New Jersey federal court holds Qualcomm's unFRANDly acts no antitrust violation|journal=IEEE Micro|volume=26|issue=5|year=2006|pages=9\u201385|issn=0272-1732|doi=10.1109/MM.2006.97|date=September-October 2006}}</ref> In May 2007, a jury ordered Qualcomm to pay Broadcom $19.6 million for infringing on three Broadcom patents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom Wins Verdict Against Rival Qualcomm|first1=Roger|last1=Cheng|first2=Don|last2=Clark|date=May 30, 2007|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118046894245217541|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> In June 2007, the ITC ruled that Qualcomm had infringed on at least one Broadcom patent and banned corresponding imports.<ref name=\"Mei2012\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom versus Qualcomm: Patents and the International Trade Commission|first=Jay|last=Sandvos|date=July 18, 2007|url=http://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4315644/Broadcom-versus-Qualcomm-Patents-and-the-International-Trade-Commission|newspaper=Electronic Design News|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm and Broadcom reached a settlement in April 2009, resulting in a cross-licensing agreement, a dismissal of all litigation and Qualcomm paying $891 million over four years.<ref name=\"julione\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom reach $891 million settlement|publisher=CNET|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-broadcom-reach-891-million-settlement/|first=Brooke|last=Crothers|date=April 26, 2009|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n \nDuring the litigation, Qualcomm claimed it had never participated in the JVT standards-setting process.<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book|title=Antitrust and Associations Handbook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=azpqjkiybX0C&pg=PA153|year=2009|publisher=American Bar Association|isbn=978-1-60442-392-1}}</ref>{{RP|153}} However, an engineer's testimony led to discovery of 21 JVT-related email Qualcomm lawyers had withheld from the court and 200,000 pages of JVT-related documents.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\"/> Qualcomm's lawyers said the evidence was overlooked by accident, whereas the judge said it was gross misconduct.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm battles in federal court|date=October 13, 2007|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=20071013&id=f2o1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=xNAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1893,4820957|accessdate=June 5, 2014|newspaper=Herald Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|title=Broadcom Lands Blows to Rival|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118648775574690358?mg=reno64-wsj&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB118648775574690358.html|first=Don|last=Clark|date=August 8, 2007|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</reF> Qualcomm was fined $8.5 million for legal misconduct.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Court Rules For Former Qualcomm Lawyers, Blasts Qualcomm Employees|first=Dona|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303411604575168631785800738|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=April 7, 2010}}</ref> On appeal, the court held that Qualcomm could only enforce the related patents against non-JVT members, based on the agreements signed to participate in JVT.<ref name=\"handbook\"/><ref name=\"BlockEpstein1995\">{{cite book|author1=Dennis J. Block|author2=Michael A. Epstein|title=The Corporate Counsellor's Deskbook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=myNUO_May5kC&pg=SA13-PA141|date=December 1995|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-0381-6}}</ref>{{RP|7}}\n \n===Nokia and Project Stockholm===\nSix large telecommunications companies<ref name=\"randommm\">{{cite news|title=E.U. Drops Antitrust Case Against Qualcomm|date=November 25, 2009|url=http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/11/25/eu-drops-antitrust-case-against-qualcomm/|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> led by Nokia<ref name=\"goodsource\">{{cite news|title=Why Qualcomm Folded to Nokia|first=Jennifer|last=Schenker|date=July 24, 2008|newspaper=BusinessWeek|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2008-07-24/why-qualcomm-folded-to-nokiabusinessweek-business-news-stock-market-and-financial-advice|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</reF> filed a complaint against Qualcomm with the [[European Commission]]'s antitrust division<ref name=\"goodsource\"/> in October 2005.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Business Model Attacked|first=Elliot|last=Spagat|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 26, 2007|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/26/AR2007012600826_pf.html|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</reF> They alleged Qualcomm was abusing its market position to charge unreasonable rates for its patents.<ref name=\"DodgsonGann2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mark Dodgson|author2=David M. Gann|author3=Nelson Phillips|title=The Oxford Handbook of Innovation Management|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=s0dYAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA571|date=November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-969494-5|pages=571}}</ref><ref name=\"Lundqvist2014\"/> Qualcomm alleged the six companies were colluding together under the code name Project Stockholm in a legal strategy to negotiate lower rates.<reF>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm says competitors conspiring in patent dispute|first=Jonathan|last=Sidener|date=March 21, 2008|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20080321/news_1b21conspire.html|newspaper=Union Tribune San Diego}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=January 24, 2007|title=Qualcomm warns of escalating costs|first=Chris|last=Nuttall|newspaper=The Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/806e3634-abff-11db-a0ed-0000779e2340.html#axzz39iO1EwRz|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"battle\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Legal Battles Hold Big Implications for Cellphones|first=Don|last=Clark|date=September 7, 2006|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB115759241325855938}}</ref> These events led to a protracted legal dispute.<ref name=\"randommm\"/>\n \nQualcomm filed a series of patent-infringement lawsuits against Nokia in Europe, Asia, the United States, and with the ITC.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Files Lawsuits Against Nokia|first=Bruce|last=Meyerson|publisher=The Associated Press|date=November 7, 2005|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/07/AR2005110700505.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><Ref name=\"timeline\"/> The parties initiated more than one dozen lawsuits against one another.<Ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news|title=TIMELINE: Qualcomm vs Nokia patents battle|publisher=Reuters|date=February 25, 2008|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/02/25/us-nokia-qualcomm-idUSL257876620080225|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> Several companies filed antitrust complaints against Qualcomm with the Korean [[Fair Trade Commission (South Korea)|Fair Trade Commission]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom and TI take action on Qualcomm|first=Song|last=Jung-a|date=July 3, 2006|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/80f8b628-0aac-11db-b595-0000779e2340.html#axzz39uAwmWk9|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> who initiated an investigation into Qualcomm's practices in December 2006.<Ref name=\"ten\">{{cite news|date=January 5, 2007|title=South Korea's fair trade regulators steps up Qualcomm probe|accessdate=June 5, 2014|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&amp;dat=20070105&amp;id=fsQ0AAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=fiEGAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=2776,337753|publisher=The Associated Press}}</ref> The dispute between Qualcomm and Nokia escalated, when their licensing agreement ended in April 2007.<ref name=\"nokia\">{{cite news\n|title=In settlement, Nokia will pay royalties to Qualcomm\n|first=Matt\n|last=Richtel\n|newspaper=The New York Times\n|date=July 24, 2008\n|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/24/technology/24qualcomm.html?_r=0\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref>\n \nIn February 2008, the two parties agreed to halt any new litigation until an initial ruling is made on the first lawsuit in Delaware.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\">{{cite book|author1=Constance E. Bagley|author2=Diane Savage|title=Managers and the Legal Environment: Strategies for the 21st Century|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I2ezeH8IpSgC&pg=PA386|date=February 5, 2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=0-324-58204-8|pages=386}}</ref><Ref name=\"timeline\"/> Nokia won three consecutive court rulings with the German Federal Patent Court, the High Court in the United Kingdom, and the International Trade Commission respectively. Each found that Nokia was not infringing on Qualcomm's patents.<ref name=\"goodsource\"/><ref name=\"Lundqvist2014\">{{cite book|author=Bj\u00f6rn Lundqvist|title=Standardization under EU Competition Rules and US Antitrust Laws: The Rise and Limits of Self-Regulation|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PySeAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA64|date=May 30, 2014|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|isbn=978-1-78195-486-7|pages=64}}</ref><Ref>{{cite news|title=Nokia: German court rules Qualcomm patent invalid|date=July 23, 2008|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2008/07/23/idINL2310194220080723|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> In July 2008, Nokia and Qualcomm reached an out-of-court settlement that ended the dispute and created a 15-year cross-licensing agreement.<ref name=\"goodsource\"/>\n \n===Recent disputes===\n \nParkerVision filed a lawsuit against Qualcomm in July 2011 alleging that it infringed on seven ParkerVision patents related to converting electromagnetic radio signals to lower frequencies.<ref name=\"parker\">{{cite news|first=Brad|last=Graves|title=Qualcomm Likely to Appeal $173M Verdict|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/91945397/qualcomm-likely-appeal-173m-verdict}}</ref> A $173 million jury verdict against Qualcomm was overturned by a judge.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Wins Ruling Tossing ParkerVision $173M Verdict|first=Susan|last=Decker|date=June 23, 2014|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-06-23/qualcomm-wins-ruling-tossing-parkervision-173m-verdict.html}}</reF>\n \nIn November 2013, the China National Development and Reform Commission initiated an anti-trust investigation into Qualcomm's licensing division.<ref name=\"reutreur\"/><ref name=\"wsjsj\"/> The [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] also started an investigation into whether Qualcomm breached antibribery laws through its activities in China.<ref name=\"wsjsj\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Profit Rises; Company Notes 'Challenges' in China|first1=Don|last1=Clark|first2=Josh|last2=Beckerman|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-profit-rises-company-notes-challenges-in-china-1406147672|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</reF><Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm not talking about bribery probe|first=Mike|last=Freeman|date=February 5, 2012|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/03f68896-77a3-11de-9713-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2xMChLKki|accessdate=August 9, 2014|newspaper=Union-Tribune San Diego}}</reF> The Chinese regulator raided Qualcomm's Chinese offices in August 2013.<ReF name=\"reutersssst\">{{cite news|title=China accuses Qualcomm of overcharging, abusing dominance|first1=Kevin|last1=Yao|first2=Matthew|last2=Miller|date=February 19, 2014|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/19/us-china-ndrc-idUSBREA1I0A820140219|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The dispute was settled in 2015 for $975 million.<ref name=\"Clark 2015\">{{cite web | last=Clark | first=Don | title=Qualcomm to Pay $975 Million Antitrust Fine to China | website=WSJ | date=February 8, 2015 | url=http://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-settles-china-probe-1423518143 | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In late 2016 The Korea Fair Trade Commission alleged Qualcomm abused a \"dominant market position\" to charge cell phone manufacturers excessive royalties for patents and limit sales to companies selling competing semiconductor products.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016hsj\">{{cite news | title=Why South Korea Just Hit Qualcomm with a Record $854 Million Fine | newspaper=Fortune | date=December 27, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/12/27/qualcomm-korea-antitrust/ | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The regulator gave Qualcomm a fine of $854 million, which the company said it will appeal.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016hsj\"/>\n \nIn April 2017, Qualcomm paid a $814.9 million settlement with [[Blackberry]] as a refund for prepaid licensing fees.<ref name=\"Cao 2017\">{{cite web | last=Cao | first=Jing | title=BlackBerry Jumps as $814.9 Million Qualcomm Refund Bolsters Cash | website=Bloomberg.com | date=April 12, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-12/blackberry-wins-814-9-million-from-qualcomm-in-royalty-dispute | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, Taiwan's Fair Trade Commission fined Qualcomm another $773 million.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Fined Record $773 Million in Taiwan Antitrust Probe| website=Bloomberg | date=October 11, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/qualcomm-fined-773-million-in-taiwan-for-antitrust-violations | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> However, in late 2018 Qualcomm paid a settlement to Taiwan for $93 million in fines and a promise to spend $700 million in the local Taiwan economy.<ref name=\"Mickle 2018\">{{cite web | last=Mickle | first=Tripp | title=Qualcomm, Taiwan Reach Settlement in Patent-Licensing Dispute | website=WSJ | date=August 10, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-taiwan-reach-settlement-in-patent-licensing-dispute-1533872303 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee 2018\">{{cite web | last=Lee | first=Yimou | title=Qualcomm settles anti-trust case with Taiwan regulator for $93 million | website=U.S. | date=August 10, 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-qualcomm-taiwan/qualcomm-settles-with-taiwan-antitrust-regulator-for-t2-73-billion-idUSKBN1KV07Z | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n===Apple===\nIn January 2017, the Federal Trade Commission initiated an investigation into allegations that Qualcomm charged excessive royalties for patents that are \"essential to industry standards.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm shares plunge amid US antitrust case|url=http://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/17/qualcomm-shares-plunge-after-report-said-it-will-face-us-antitrust-case.html|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=CNBC|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> That same year, Apple initiated a $1 billion lawsuit against Qualcomm in the U.S. alleging Qualcomm overcharged for semiconductors and failed to pay $1 billion in rebates.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apple files $1 billion lawsuit against chip supplier Qualcomm|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-lawsuit-qualcomm-idUSKBN1542SG|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Balakrishnan|first1=Anita|title=Qualcomm blasts 'baseless' $1 billion Apple royalties lawsuit|url=http://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/20/apple-sues-qualcomm-for-1-billion.html|accessdate=January 21, 2017|work=CNBC|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Apple also filed lawsuits in China<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\">{{cite web | last=Pressman | first=Aaron | title=Qualcomm Slams Apple Over Lawsuits | website=Fortune | date=January 26, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/01/26/qualcomm-apple-patent-fight-analysts/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"adfljajdcpajdpfijaoiwec\">{{cite web | title=Apple Is Expanding its War with Qualcomm | website=Fortune | date=March 3, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/03/03/apple-qualcomm-legal-battle/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n \nApple alleged Qualcomm was engaging in unfair competition by selling industry-standard patents at a discount rate in exchange for an exclusivity agreement for its semiconductor products.<ref name=\"King McLaughlin Rosenblatt 2017\">{{cite web | last=King | first=Ian | last2=McLaughlin | first2=David | last3=Rosenblatt | first3=Joel | title=Qualcomm Accused of Forcing Deal on Apple to Thwart Rivals | website=Bloomberg.com | date=January 17, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-17/qualcomm-forced-apple-to-exclusively-use-modem-chips-ftc-says | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> An FTC report reached similar conclusions.<ref name=\"King McLaughlin Rosenblatt 2017\"/> Qualcomm filed counter-claims alleging Apple made false and misleading statements to induce regulators to sue Qualcomm.<ref name=\"Forbespatents\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Is Suing iPhone Manufacturers In Backlash Against Apple | website=Forbes | date=May 17, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2017/05/17/qualcomm-suing-apple-contract-manufacturers/#e0eea6a183a7 | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also sued Apple's suppliers for allegedly not paying Qualcomm's patent royalties, after Apple stopped reimbursing them for patent fees.<ref name=\"Forbespatents\"/><ref name=\"Fortune 2017Apple\">{{cite web | title=Apple Stops Paying Qualcomm Royalties | website=Fortune | date=April 28, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/04/28/apple-iphone-royalties-qualcomm/ | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm petitioned the International Trade Commission to prohibit imports of iPhones, on the premise that they contain stolen Qualcomm patents after Apple's suppliers stopped paying.<ref name=\"King Decker 2017\">{{cite web | last=King | first=Ian | last2=Decker | first2=Susan | title=Qualcomm Said to Seek U.S. Import Ban for iPhones | website=Bloomberg.com | date=May 3, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-03/qualcomm-said-to-seek-u-s-import-ban-for-iphones | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn August, the International Trade Commission responded to Qualcomm's complaints by starting an investigation of Apple's use of Qualcomm patents without royalties.<ref name=\"Heavey Nellis 2017\">{{cite web | last=Heavey | first=Susan | last2=Nellis | first2=Stephen | title=U.S. to review Qualcomm's complaints about Apple iPhone patents | website=U.S. | date=August 8, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-qualcomm/u-s-to-review-qualcomms-complaints-about-apple-iphone-patents-idUSKBN1AO23R | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also filed suit against Apple in China for alleged patent infringement in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Seeks China iPhone Ban, Expanding Apple Legal Fight | website=Bloomberg | date=October 13, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-13/qualcomm-seeks-china-iphone-ban-escalating-apple-legal-fight | accessdate=August 12, 2018|first=Ian|last=King}}</ref> The following month, Apple counter-sued, alleging Qualcomm was using patented Apple technology in its Android components.<ref name=\"Nellis 2017\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=Apple accuses Qualcomm of patent infringement in countersuit | website=U.S. | date=November 29, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-qualcomm/apple-accuses-qualcomm-patent-infringement-in-countersuit-idUSKBN1DT1UU | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn December 2018 Chinese<ref name=\"Nellis 2018\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=China court bans sales of older iPhone models in Apple-Qualcomm global battle | website=U.S. | date=December 11, 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-apple-idUSKBN1O91LD | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> and Germany<ref name=\"Feiner 2018\">{{cite web | last=Feiner | first=Lauren | title=Apple will stop selling some iPhone models in its stores in Germany following ruling in Qualcomm patent case | website=CNBC | date=December 20, 2018 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/20/qualcomm-reportedly-wins-injunction-against-apple-in-munich.html | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> courts held that Apple infringed on Qualcomm patents and banned sales of certain iPhones. Some patents were held to be invalid,<ref name=\"Bloomberg 2019\">{{cite web | title=Apple Dodges One Import Ban in Qualcomm Fight, Faces Another| website=Bloomberg | date=March 26, 2019 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-26/apple-infringes-qualcomm-patent-judge-recommends-iphone-ban | accessdate=December 18, 2019|first1=Susan|last1=Decker|first2=Ian|last2=King|first3=Mark|last3=Gurman}}</ref> while others were infringed by Apple.<ref name=\"Nieva 2019\">{{cite web | last=Nieva | first=Richard | title=Apple dealt legal blow as jury awards Qualcomm $31 million | website=CNET | date=March 15, 2019 | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-qualcomm-patent-infringement-verdict/ | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn April 2019, Apple and Qualcomm reached an agreement to cease all litigation and sign a six-year licensing agreement.<ref name=\"daoijdaiew\">{{cite web | title=Apple and Qualcomm Settle All Disputes Worldwide | website=The New York Times | date=April 16, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/technology/apple-qualcomm-settle.html | first1=Don|last1=Clark|first2=Daisuke|last2=Wakabayashi|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The settlement included a one-time payment from Apple of about $4.5 to $4.7 billion.<ref name=\"daiuowbavinadsewmgn\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Pegs Payment From Apple at $4.5 Billion to $4.7 Billion | website=The New York Times | date=April 1, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/technology/qualcomm-apple-payment.html | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Terms of the six-year licensing agreement were not disclosed, but the licensing fees were expected to increase revenues by $2 per-share.<ref name=\"daoijdaiew\"/><ref name=\"daiuowbavinadsewmgn\"/>\n \nIn January 2018, the European Competition Commission fined Qualcomm $1.2 billion for an arrangement to use Qualcomm chips exclusively in Apple\u2019s mobile products.<ref name=\"Olson 2018\">{{cite web | last=Olson | first=Parmy | title=Qualcomm Hit With $1.2 Billion EU Antitrust Fine | website=Forbes | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/parmyolson/2018/01/24/qualcomm-1-2-billion-eu-antitrust-fine/ | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"danonqveroidnsiun\">{{cite web | title=E.U. Fines Qualcomm $1.2 Billion Over Apple Deal |first=Chad|last=Bray| website=The New York Times | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/24/business/eu-qualcomm-fine-antitrust.html | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Drozdiak Greenwald 2018\">{{cite web | last=Drozdiak | first=Natalia | last2=Greenwald | first2=Ted | title=Qualcomm Is Slapped With $1.23 Billion EU Fine for Illegal Payments to Apple | website=WSJ | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-fine-qualcomm-over-exclusivity-payments-to-apple-1516783685 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm is appealing the decision.<ref name=\"Olson 2018\"/><ref name=\"danonqveroidnsiun\"/><ref name=\"Drozdiak Greenwald 2018\"/>\n \n==Operations and market-share==\nQualcomm develops software, semiconductor designs, patented intellectual property, development tools and services, but does not manufacture physical products like phones or infrastructure equipment.<ref name=\"Kodama2012\">{{cite book|first=Mitsuru|last=Kodama|title=Interactive Business Communities: Accelerating Corporate Innovation through Boundary Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iYu-lGHtkK4C&pg=PA94|date=August 28, 2012|publisher=Gower Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-5950-7|pages=94}}</ref> The company's revenues are derived from licensing fees for use of its intellectual property, sales of semiconductor products that are based on its designs, and from other wireless hardware, software or services.<reF name=\"primary\">{{cite|date=November 6, 2013|title=Form 10-K Annual Report|accessdate=July 26, 2014|publisher=Qualcomm|url=http://investor.qualcomm.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1234452-13-483}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm divides its business into three categories:<ref name=\"primary2\">{{cite web | title=About Qualcomm | website=QUALCOMM Incorporated | date=August 23, 2019 | url=https://investor.qualcomm.com/about-qualcomm/overview |accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* QCT (Qualcomm CDMA Technologies): CDMA wireless products; 60 percent of revenue\n* QTL (Qualcomm Technology Licensing): Licensing; 19% of revenue\n* QSI (Qualcomm strategic initiatives): Investing in other tech companies; 1% of revenue\n \nQualcomm is a predominantly fabless provider of semiconductor products for wireless communications and data transfer in portable devices.<ref name=\"newceo\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm calling on a new CEO amid intensifying competition|first=Stuart|last=Pfeifer|date=February 16, 2014|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-stock-spotlight-qualcomm-20140217-story.html#axzz2tmGtq2XB|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> According to the analyst firm Strategy Analytics, Qualcomm has a 39 percent market-share for smartphone application processors and a 50 percent market-share of baseband processors.<ref name=\"FierceWireless 2016\">{{cite web | title=Report: Qualcomm led smartphone application processor market in 1H 2016 | website=FierceWireless | date=October 12, 2016 | url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/report-qualcomm-led-smartphone-application-processor-market-1h-2016 |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Its share of the market for application processors on tablets is 18 percent.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Manners|date=October 18, 2016|title=Apps processor market grows 3% while tablet AP market sinks 34%|url=http://www.electronicsweekly.com/news/business/487606-2016-10/|newspaper=Electronics Weekly}}</ref> According to analyst firm ABI Research, Qualcomm has a 65 percent market-share in LTE baseband.<ref name=\"Mott 2017\">{{cite web | last=Mott | first=Nathaniel | title=FTC: Qualcomm Has Unfair Monopoly In Smartphone Market | website=Tom's Hardware | date=January 18, 2017 | url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/ftc-qualcomm-baseband-processors-monopoly,33443.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also provides licenses to use its patents, many of which are critical to the CDMA2000, TD-SCDMA and WCDMA wireless standards.<ref name=\"Asif2011\">{{cite book|first=Saad|last=Asif|title=Next Generation Mobile Communications Ecosystem: Technology Management for Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=zgqQ4MX3uIUC&pg=PT378|date=February 25, 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-99581-4|pages=378|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The company is estimated to earn $20 for every smartphone sold.<ref name=\"Cannady2013\">{{cite book|first=Cynthia|last=Cannady|title=Technology Licensing and Development Agreements|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3NFMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA67|date=April 4, 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-538513-7|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>{{RP|64}}\n \nQualcomm is the largest public company in San Diego.<ref>{{cite news|first=Allen|last=Mike|title=San Diego's Largest Public Company Remains a Work in Progress|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=June 20, 2011|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/61993682/san-diegos-largest-public-company-remains-work-progress|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"six\">{{cite|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/v55-1/pdf/v55-1west.pdf|publisher=The Journal of San Diego History|title=Before Qualcomm: Linkabit and the Origins of San Diego\u2019s Telecom Industry|first=Joel|last=West|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> It has a philanthropic arm called The Qualcomm Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|title=X Prize finalists design Trekkie-inspired health tools|first=Michelle|last=Healy|newspaper=USA Today|date=August 27, 2014|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/08/27/qualcomm-tricorder-xprize/14586959/|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Mike|title=Stadium perks `Q' up for Qualcomm|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=March 31, 1997}}</reF> A January 2013 lawsuit resulted in Qualcomm voluntarily adopting a policy of disclosing its political contributions. According to <i>The New York Times</i>, Qualcomm's new disclosure policy was praised by transparency advocates.<ref name=\"randomname\">{{cite news|title=State Comptroller Sues Qualcomm for Data About Its Political Contributions|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=January 3, 2013|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/04/nyregion/new-york-comptroller-sues-qualcomm-for-data-on-political-giving.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Aw%2C%7B%222%22%3A%22RI%3A13%22%7D|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Reveals Its Donations to Tax-Exempt Groups|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=February 22, 2013|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/22/qualcomm-agrees-to-reveal-donations-to-tax-exempt-groups/?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Aw%2C%7B%222%22%3A%22RI%3A13%22%7D|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \n==See also==\n* [[Qualcomm Snapdragon]]\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n \n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.qualcomm.com/ Official website]\n{{Finance links\n| name = QUALCOMM, Inc.\n| symbol = QCOM\n| sec_cik = 804328\n| yahoo = QCOM\n| google = QCOM\n}}\n\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n{{NASDAQ-100}}\n{{Major networking hardware companies}}\n{{Major semiconductor companies}}\n{{Electronics industry in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Qualcomm| ]]\n[[Category:1985 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Display technology companies]]\n[[Category:Electronics companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Fabless semiconductor companies]]\n[[Category:Graphics hardware companies]]\n[[Category:HSA Foundation]]\n[[Category:Information technology companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Networking hardware companies]]\n[[Category:Semiconductor companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in San Diego]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1985]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Telecommunications equipment vendors]]\n[[Category:1991 initial public offerings]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American global semiconductor company}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name             = Qualcomm Incorporated\n| logo             =Qualcomm-Logo.svg\n|image=[[Image:Qualcomm Headquarters La Jolla.jpg|250px]]\n| image_caption = Qualcomm Research Center in San Diego, California.\n| type             = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as        = NASDAQ: QCOM<br />[[S&P 500|S&P 500 Component]]\n| foundation       = [[San Diego]], [[California]], [[United States of America|USA]] (1985)\n| founder          = [[Irwin M. Jacobs|Irwin Jacobs]]\n| location_city    = [[San Diego]], [[California]]\n| location_country = United States\n| area =\n| area_served      = Worldwide\n| key_people       = Steven Mollenkopf, CEO<br>Cristiano Amon, President<br>Mark D. McLaughlin, Chairman\n| industry         = {{nowrap|[[Telecommunications equipment]]<br />[[Semiconductor]]s}}\n| products         =Intellectual property and semiconductors\n| num_employees = ~37,000 (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| revenue           = $24.3 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\">{{cite web | title=FORM 10-K: For the fiscal year ended September 29, 2019 | website=Qualcomm.com | date=September 29, 2019 | url=https://investor.qualcomm.com/sec-filings/all-sec-filings/content/0001728949-19-000072/qcom10-k2019.htm | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n| operating_income  = US $7.7 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| net_income        = US $4.4 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| assets            =  US $33 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| equity            = US $4.9 billion (2019)<ref name=\"10k\"/>\n| homepage = https://www.qualcomm.com }}<b>Qualcomm</b> is a public multinational corporation headquartered in [[San Diego, California]]. It creates [[intellectual property]], semiconductors, software, and services related to wireless technology. It owns patents critical to the [[CDMA2000]], [[TD-SCDMA]] and [[WCDMA]] mobile communications standards.\n \nQualcomm was established in 1985 by Irwin Jacobs and six other co-founders. Its early research into [[CDMA]] wireless cell phone technology was funded by selling satellite communications systems for commercial trucks. After a heated debate in the wireless industry, the 3G standard was adopted with Qualcomm's CDMA patents incorporated.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\"/> Afterwards there was a series of legal disputes about pricing for licensing patents required by the standard.\n \nOver the years, Qualcomm has expanded into selling semiconductor products in a predominantly [[Fabless manufacturing|fabless manufacturing]] model. It also developed semiconductor components or software for vehicles, watches, laptops, wi-fi, smartphones, and other devices.\n \n==Corporate history==\n===Early history===\nQualcomm was created on July 1, 1985<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Founder Set to Retire|first=Shara|last=Tibken|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=December 21, 2011|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052970204879004577111313063790248|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> by seven former [[Linkabit]] employees led by Irwin Jacobs.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> The company was named Qualcomm for \u201cQUALity COMMunications.\u201d<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Dialed 26,078% Gain as it Transformed Mobile|first=Brian|last=Deagon|date=May 25, 2014|url=http://news.investors.com/business-the-new-america/042514-698579-qualcomm-qcom-set-cdma-cellphone-standard.htm|accessdate=July 26, 2014|newspaper=Investor\u2019s Business Daily}}</ref> It started as a contract research and development center<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\">{{cite book|author=Dan Steinbock|title=Wireless Horizon: Strategy and Competition in the Worldwide Mobile Marketplace|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=HugmyrqibtwC&amp;pg=PA305|year=2003|publisher=AMACOM Div American Mgmt Assn|isbn=978-0-8144-0714-1|pages=305}}</ref> largely for government and defense projects.<ref name=\"Mock2005\">{{cite book|author=Dave Mock|title=The Qualcomm Equation: How a Fledgling Telecom Company Forged a New Path to Big Profits and Market Dominance|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JcH4C2eAsJEC&amp;pg=PA33|date=January 1, 2005|publisher=AMACOM: American Management Association|isbn=978-0-8144-2858-0|pages=33}}</ref><ref name=\"six\"/>\n \nQualcomm merged with [[Omninet]] in 1988 and raised $3.5 million in funding in order to produce the Omnitracs satellite communications system for trucking companies.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm grew from eight employees in 1986 to 620 employees in 1991, due to demand for Omnitracs.<ref name=\"nytnyt\">{{cite news|title=Satellite System Helps Trucks Stay in Touch|first=Agis|last=Salpukas|date=June 5, 1991|accessdate=July 16, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1991/06/05/business/business-technology-satellite-system-helps-trucks-stay-in-touch.html|newspaper=The New York Times}}</reF> By 1989, Qualcomm had $32 million in revenues, 50 percent of which was from an Omnitracs contract with [[Schneider National]].<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><Ref name=\"two\">{{cite news|title=Big Boost for Qualcomm|date=November 23, 1988|first=Chris|last=Kraul|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-11-23/business/fi-275_1_qualcomm-system|accessdate=June 3, 2014}}</ref> Omnitracs profits helped fund Qualcomm's research and development into [[code-division multiple access]] (CDMA) technologies for cell phone networks.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><ref name=\"tribunel\"/>\n \n===1990-2015===\nQualcomm was operating at a loss in the 1990s due to its investment in CDMA research.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><ref name=\"tribunel\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm completes sale of Omnitracs|first=Mike|last=Freeman|date=November 26, 2014|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/news/2013/Nov/26/Qualcomm-Omnitracs-Vista-Equity-partners/|accessdate=July 17, 2014|newspaper=The San Diego Tribune}}</ref> To obtain funding, the company filed an [[initial public offering]] in September 1991<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Goes Public With Stock|date=September 17, 1991|first=Greg|last=Johnson|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-09-17/business/fi-2845_1_qualcomm-treasurer-dick-grannis|accessdate=July 17, 2014}}</ref> raising $68 million.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> An additional $486 million was raised in 1995 through the sale of 11.5 million more shares. The second funding round was done to raise money for the mass manufacturing of CDMA-based phones, base-stations, and equipment, after most US-based cellular networks announced they would adopt the CDMA standard.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> The company had $383 million in annual revenue in 1995<ref name=\"bwbw\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/1995-09-03/qualcomm-unproven-but-dazzling|newspaper=BusinessWeek|title=Qualcomm: Unproven, But Dazzling|date=September 3, 1995|first=Larry|last=Armstrong|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}</reF> and $814 million by 1996.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \nIn 1998, Qualcomm was restructured, leading to a 700-employee layoff. Its cell-phone manufacturing business was also spun-off in order to focus on its higher-margin patents business.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|310-311}} The following year, Qualcomm was the fastest growing stock on the market with a 2,621 percent growth over one year.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Hits The Big Time Pushing a little-known digital cellular technology from surf's-up San Diego, this $4-billion-a-year hotshot wants to be THE NEXT INTEL|newspaper=Fortune Magazine|url=https://archive.fortune.com/magazines/fortune/fortune_archive/2000/05/15/279766/index.htm|first=Eric|last=Nee|date=May 15, 2000|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"sandiegomag\">{{cite news|title=A Qualcomm Quarter-Century|first=Joseph|last=Perkins|date=September 3, 2010|newspaper=San Diego Magazine|url=http://www.sandiegomagazine.com/San-Diego-Magazine/September-2010/A-Qualcomm-Quarter-Century/}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|publisher=CNET|date=January 7, 2000|title=Taking stock of 1999|first1=Sandeep|last1=Junnarkar|first2=Scott|last2=Ard|url=http://news.cnet.com/Taking-stock-of-1999/2100-1017_3-235357.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF> By 2000, Qualcomm had grown to 6,300 employees, $3.2 billion in revenues, and $670 million in profit. 39 percent of its sales were from CDMA technology, followed by licensing (22%), wireless (22%), and other products (17%).<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> Around this time, Qualcomm established offices in Europe, Asia Pacific, and Latin America.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|316}} By 2001, 65 percent of Qualcomm's revenues originated from outside the United States with 35 percent coming from South Korea.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>{{RP|19}}\n \nIn 2005, [[Paul E. Jacobs]], son of Qualcomm founder Dr. Irwin Jacobs, was appointed as Qualcomm's new CEO.<ref name=\"nytsy\">{{cite news|title=At Qualcomm, Rise of Founder\u2019s Son Defies Hazards of Succession|first=Malia|last=Wollan |newspaper=The New York Times|date=June 12, 2011|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2011/06/13/technology/13qualcomm.html?pagewanted=all&amp;_r=0&amp;gwt=pay}}</reF> Whereas Irwin Jacobs focused on CDMA patents, Paul Jacobs refocused much of Qualcomm's new research and development on projects related to the [[internet of things]].<ref name=\"nytsy\"/> Qualcomm announced Steven Mollenkopf would succeed Paul Jacobs as CEO in December 2013.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm names Mollenkopf president, COO|newspaper=EE Times|date=October 4, 2011|url= http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1260357|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|first=Brian|last=Chen|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 8, 2014|date=December 13, 2013|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/12/14/technology/qualcomm-names-a-new-chief-executive.html?_r=0|title=Qualcomm Picks Insider as New Chief Executive}}</ref> Mollenkopf said he would expand Qualcomm's focus to wireless technology for cars, wearable devices, and other new markets.<ref>{{cite web |first=Alistair|last=Barr| title=CES 2014: Qualcomm CEO sees growth in wearables, autos | website=USA TODAY | date=January 6, 2014 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/2014/01/06/qualcomm-ceo-mollenkopf/4341927/ | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Rubin 2014\">{{cite web | last=Rubin | first=Ben Fox | title=Qualcomm wants to move out of your pocket into your car, house and wearable | website=CNET | date=November 19, 2014 | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-wants-to-move-out-of-your-pocket-into-your-cars-house-and-wearable/ |accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n===NXP and Broadcom===\nQualcomm announced its intent to acquire NXP Semiconductors for $47 billion in October 2016.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016\">{{cite web |first=Aaron |last=Pressman| title=Here's Why the Qualcomm-NXP Deal Makes Sense | website=Fortune | date=October 27, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/10/27/qualcomm-nxp-deal/ | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The deal was approved by U.S. antitrust regulators in April 2017<ref name=\"Fortune 2017\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm's $47 Billion Acquisition Clears Key Hurdle | website=Fortune | date=April 4, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/04/04/qualcomm-nxp-acquisition-antitrust/ | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> with some standard-essential patents excluded to get the deal approved by antitrust regulators.<ref>{{cite web | last=Chee | first=Foo Yun | title=Qualcomm offers to buy NXP minus some patents to allay EU concerns:... | website=U.S. | date=October 10, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-nxp-semicondtrs-m-a-qualcomm-eu/qualcomm-offers-to-buy-nxp-minus-some-patents-to-allay-eu-concerns-sources-idUSKBN1CF20D | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Drozdiak 2018\">{{cite web | last=Drozdiak | first=Natalia | title=Qualcomm Set to Win European Backing for $39 Billion NXP Buy | website=WSJ | date=January 11, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-set-to-win-european-backing-for-39-billion-nxp-buy-1515673776 |accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n \nAs the NXP acquisition was ongoing, Broadcom made a $103 billion offer to acquire Qualcomm,<ref>{{cite web | title=Broadcom Offers $105 Billion for Qualcomm in Landmark Deal|first=Ian|last=King | website=Bloomberg | date=November 6, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-11-06/broadcom-offers-130-billion-for-qualcomm-in-landmark-tech-deal | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Mukherjee 2017\">{{cite web | last=Mukherjee | first=Supantha | title=Broadcom bids $103 billion for Qualcomm, open to going hostile | website=U.S. | date=November 6, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/broadcom-offers-to-buy-mobile-chipmaker-qualcomm-for-103-billion-idUSKBN1D61EO | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> and Qualcomm rejected the offer.<ref name=\"Mukherjee 20172\">{{cite web | last=Mukherjee | first=Supantha | title=Qualcomm rejects Broadcom's $103-billion takeover bid | website=U.S. | date=November 13, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-m-a-broadcom/qualcomm-rejects-broadcoms-103-billion-takeover-proposal-idUSKBN1DD1NU | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> Broadcom attempted a hostile takeover,<ref>{{cite web | first=Aishwarya|last=Venugopal, | title=Broadcom is laying the foundation for a hostile takeover of Qualcomm | website=Business Insider | date=December 4, 2017 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/qualcomm-broadcom-laying-the-foundation-for-a-hostile-takeover-2017-12 |accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> and raised its offer, eventually to $121 billion.<ref name=\"dkahfad\">{{cite web | title=Broadcom Raises Qualcomm Hostile Bid to About $121 Billion| website=Bloomberg|first=Ian|last=King | date=February 5, 2018 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-02-05/broadcom-is-said-planning-to-boost-qualcomm-bid-to-120-billion | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> The potential Broadcom acquisition was investigated by the U.S. [[Committee on Foreign Investment in the United States|Committee on Foreign Investment]]<ref>{{cite web | title=US national security regulator delays Qualcomm vote | website=Financial Times | date=March 5, 2018 | url=https://www.ft.com/content/fb3e6312-2055-11e8-a895-1ba1f72c2c11 | accessdate=August 16, 2018|first1=Arash|last1=Massoudi|first2=Rochelle|last2=Toplensky |first3=James|last3=Fontanella-Khan}}</ref> and blocked by an executive order from U.S. President [[Donald Trump]], citing national security concerns.<ref>{{cite web|title=Trump Blocks Broadcom Takeover of Qualcomm on Security Risks|website=Bloomberg|date=March 12, 2018|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-03-12/trump-issues-order-to-block-broadcom-s-takeover-of-qualcomm-jeoszwnt|accessdate=August 16, 2018|first=David|last=McLaughlin}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm's NXP acquisition then became a part of the [[2018 China\u2013United States trade war]].<ref name=\"ouafhouh\">{{cite web | title=Trump Throws a Wrench Into Qualcomm's NXP Deal | website=Bloomberg | date=June 15, 2018 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/view/articles/2018-06-15/trump-throws-a-wrench-into-qualcomm-s-nxp-deal | accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Alex|last=Webb}}</ref> U.S. President [[Donald Trump]] blocked China-based [[ZTE Corporation]] from buying American-made components, such as those from Qualcomm.<ref name=\"ouafhouh\"/><ref name=\"The New York Times 2018\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm May Be Collateral Damage in a U.S.-China Trade War |first1=Ana |last1=Swanson|first2=Alexandra|last2=Stevenson| website=The New York Times | date=April 18, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/04/18/us/politics/qualcomm-us-china-trade-war.html | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref> The ZTE restriction was lifted after the two countries reached an agreement,<ref name=\"Financial Times 2017\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm, NXP jolted higher after US-ZTE deal | website=Financial Times | date=June 7, 2018 | url=https://www.ft.com/content/c162a48c-6a56-11e8-8cf3-0c230fa67aec | accessdate=August 17, 2018|first=Pan|last= Yuk}}</ref> but then Trump raised tariffs against Chinese goods.<ref name=\"ouafhouh\"/> Qualcomm extended a tender offer to NXP at least 29 times pending Chinese approval,<ref name=\"Reuters 2018\">{{cite web | first=Sonam|last=Rai| title=Qualcomm extends NXP tender offer yet again | website=Business Insider | date=June 29, 2018 | url=https://www.businessinsider.com/r-qualcomm-extends-nxp-tender-offer-yet-again-2018-6 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref> before abandoning the deal in July 2018.<ref>{{cite web | first=Don|last=Clark|title=Qualcomm Scraps $44 Billion NXP Deal After China Inaction | website=The New York Times | date=July 25, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/25/technology/qualcomm-nxp-china-deadline.html | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Brown | first=Eliot | last2=Davis | first2=Bob | title=Qualcomm Abandons NXP Deal Amid U.S.-China Tensions | website=WSJ | date=July 25, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-plans-to-abandon-nxp-deal-1532549728 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Wireless CDMA==\n===2G===\n====Early history====\nIn mid-1985, Qualcomm was hired by [[Hughes Aircraft]] to provide research and testing for a satellite network proposal to the [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC).<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|38}} The following year, Qualcomm filed its first CDMA patent (No. 4,901,307).<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> This patent established Qualcomm's overall approach to CDMA<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> and later became one of the most frequently cited technical documents in history.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\">{{cite book|first1=Mark|last1=Blaxill|first2=Ralph|last2= Eckardt|title=The Invisible Edge: Taking Your Strategy to the Next Level Using Intellectual Property|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=JO6kA0hebJIC&pg=PA86|year=2009|publisher=Portfolio|isbn=978-1-59184-237-8}}</ref>{{RP|84}} The project with the FCC was scrapped in 1988, when the FCC told all twelve vendors that submitted proposals to form a joint venture to create a single proposal.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|38}}\n \nQualcomm further developed the CDMA techniques for commercial use and submitted them to the [[Cellular Telephone Industries Association]] (CTIA) in 1989 as an alternative to the [[time division multiple access]] (TDMA) standard for second-generation cell-phone networks.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|49}} A few months later, CTIA officially rejected Qualcomm's CDMA standard<ref name=\"LeiSlocum2013\">{{cite book|author1=David Lei|author2=John W. Slocum|title=Demystifying Your Business Strategy|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=LaJFAAAAQBAJ&amp;pg=PA101|date=August 29, 2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-136-26802-1|pages=101}}</ref> in favor of the more established TDMA standard developed by [[Ericsson]].<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/><Ref name=\"bw3\">{{cite news|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/1997-06-01/qualcomm-not-exactly-an-overnight-success|newspaper=BusinessWeek|title=Qualcomm: Not Exactly An Overnight Success|date=June 1, 1997|accessdate=July 16, 2014|first=Peter|last=Elstrom}}</reF>\n \nAt the time, CDMA wasn't considered viable in high-volume commercial applications due to the near-far field effect, whereby phones closer to a cell tower with a stronger signal drown out callers that are further away and have a weaker signal.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|54-55,62-65}}<ref name=\"wsjalpha\"/> Qualcomm filed three additional patents in 1989. They were for: a power management system that adjusts the signal strength of each call to adjust for the near-far field effect; a \"soft handoff\" methodology for transferring callers from one cell-tower to the next; and a variable rate encoder, which reduces bandwidth usage when a caller isn't speaking.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|54-55,62-65}}<ref name=\"wsjalpha\"/>\n \n====Holy wars of wireless====\nAfter the FCC said carriers were allowed to implement standards not approved by the CTIA, Qualcomm began pitching its CDMA technology directly to carriers.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> This started what is often referred to as \"the Holy Wars of Wireless,\" an often heated debate about whether TDMA or CDMA was better suited for 2G networks.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>{{RP|117-120}} Qualcomm-supported CDMA standards eventually unseated TDMA as the more popular 2G standard in North America, due to its network capacity.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \nQualcomm conducted CDMA test demonstrations in 1989<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/> in San Diego and in 1990 in New York City.<Ref name=\"thanks\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\"/> In 1990, Nynex Mobile Communications and Ameritech Mobile Communications were the first carriers to implement CDMA networks instead of TDMA.<Ref name=\"thanks\">{{cite news|date=August 20, 1990|title=Bolting from the cellular herd|newspaper=BusinessWeek|last1=Armstrong |first1= Larry|\nlast2=Therrien |first2= Lois|last3=Coy |first3= Peter}}</ref> [[Motorola]], a prior TDMA advocate, conducted CDMA test implementations in [[Hong Kong]] and [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Motorola Shift On Technology|date=November 20, 1990|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=July 17, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/1990/11/20/business/motorola-shift-on-technology.html}}</ref><ref name=\"wsjalpha\">{{cite news|title=Jacobs's Patter: An Inventor's Promise Has Companies Taking Big Cellular Gamble --- Qualcomm Boss's Innovation In Digital-Phone System Is Problematic -- and Late --- Are Claims Hope or Hype?|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|first=Quentin|last=Hardy|date=September 6, 1996}}</reF> This was followed by a $2 million trial network in San Diego for Airtouch Communications.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\">{{cite book|author=Hsiao-Hwa Chen|title=The Next Generation CDMA Technologies|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=eMfG0kuaL-kC&pg=PA178|date=August 20, 2007|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-02295-5}}</ref>{{RP|177}} In November 1991, 14 carriers and manufacturers conducted large-scale CDMA field tests.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"international\">{{cite book|author=Gale Group|title=International Directory of Company Histories|DUPLICATE-url=http://books.google.com/books?id=kd-6AAAAIAAJ|date=December 2, 2002|publisher=St. James Press|isbn=978-1-55862-476-4|url=http://www.fundinguniverse.com/company-histories/qualcomm-incorporated-history/}}</ref>\n \nResults from the test implementations convinced CTIA to re-open discussions regarding CDMA and the 2G standard.<ref name=\"PhD2010\">{{cite book|author=William A. Cohen, PhD|title=Heroic Leadership: Leading with Integrity and Honor|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CevTu1VbrgEC&pg=PT60|date=May 24, 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-40501-7|page=60}}</ref> CTIA changed its position and supported CDMA in 1993,<Ref name=\"bw3\"/> adopting Qualcomm's CDMA as the IS-95A standard, also known as cdmaOne.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\">{{cite book|author1=Wolter Lemstra|author2=Vic Hayes|author3=John Groenewegen|title=The Innovation Journey of Wi-Fi: The Road to Global Success|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=-OMoL5Irm08C&pg=PA29|date=November 18, 2010|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-139-49257-7|pages=29}}</ref> This prompted widespread criticism in forums, trade press, and conventions from businesses that had already invested heavily in the TDMA standard and from TDMA's developer, Ericsson.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><ref name=\"PhD2010\"/> \n \nThe first commercial-scale CDMA cellular network was created in Hong Kong in 1995.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\"/> On July 21, 1995, [[Primeco]], which represented a consortium of [[Cox Communications]], [[Comcast]], [[Sprint]] and others, announced it was going to implement CDMA-based services<Ref name=\"bw3\"/> on networks in 15 states.<ref name=\"LemstraHayes2010\"/> By this time, 11 out of 14 of the world's largest networks supported CDMA.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/><Ref name=\"economist\">{{cite news|title=Shorts circuited: cellular phones. (US cellular telephone industry backs Qualcomm's code division multiple access technology)|newspaper=The Economist (US)|date=July 29, 1995|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-17388504.html|accessdate=July 16, 2014}}</ref> By 1997 CDMA had 57 percent of the US market, whereas 14 percent of the market was on TDMA.<Ref name=\"bw3\"/>\n \n====International====\nIn 1991, Qualcomm and the [[Electronics and Telecommunications Research Institute]] (ETRI) agreed to jointly develop CDMA technologies for the Korean telecommunications infrastructure.<ref name=\"Reddick2012\">{{cite book|author=Christopher G. Reddick|title=Cases on Public Information Management and E-Government Adoption|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=r-VVYRvSafYC|year=2012|publisher=IGI Global Snippet|isbn=978-1-4666-0982-2|page=225}}</ref><ref name=\"Pacific2004\">{{cite book|author=United Nations. Economic and Social Commission for Asia and the Pacific|title=Good Practices in Information and Communication Technology Policies in Asia and the Pacific|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=N4AQ453g_voC&pg=PA64|year=2004|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-120412-4|pages=64}}</ref> A CDMA standard was adopted as the national wireless standard in Korea in May 1993<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> with commercial CDMA networks being launched in 1996.<ref name=\"Pacific2004\"/><ref name=\"Reddick2012\"/> CDMA networks were also launched in Argentina, Brazil, Mexico, India, and Venezuela.<ref name=\"DrakeWilson2008\">{{cite book|first1=William|last1=Drake|first2=Ernest|last2=Wilson|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=vw2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA167|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-30931-8|pages=167}}</ref><ref name=\"HarperBuress2008\">{{cite book|first1=Alvin|last1=Harper|first2=Raymond|last2=Buress|title=Mobile Telephones: Networks, Applications, and Performance|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=tG3wJZtq8PgC&pg=PA48|year=2008|publisher=Nova Publishers|isbn=978-1-60456-436-5|pages=48}}</ref> Qualcomm entered the Russian and Latin American markets in 2005.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> By 2007, Qualcomm's technology was in cell phone networks in more than 105 countries.<ref name=\"DrakeWilson2008\"/> Qualcomm also formed licensing agreements with [[Nokia]] in Europe, [[Nortel]] in Canada, and with [[Matsushita]] and [[Mitsubishi]] in Japan.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/>\n \nQualcomm entered the Chinese market through a partnership with [[China Unicom]] in 2000,<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> which launched the first CDMA-based network in China in 2003.<ref name=\"HarperBuress2008\"/> China became a major market for Qualcomm's semiconductor products, representing more than fifty percent of its revenues,<ref name=\"reutreur\">{{cite news|title=China regulator determines Qualcomm has monopoly: state-run newspaper|first=Paul|last=Carsten|first2=Michael|last2=Martina|date=July 24, 2014|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/07/24/us-qualcomm-china-idUSKBN0FT0AU20140724|accessdate=August 7, 2014|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> but also the source of many legal disputes regarding Qualcomm's intellectual property.<ref name=\"wsjsj\"/> By 2007, $500 million of Qualcomm's annual revenues were coming from Korean manufacturers.<ref name=\"OhLarson2011\">{{cite book|first1=Myung|last1=Oh|first2=James|last2=Larson|title=Digital Development in Korea: Building an Information Society|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OZpdqhsPHnQC&pg=PA97|date=March 14, 2011|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-136-81313-9|pages=97}}</ref>\n \n====Manufacturing====\nInitially, Qualcomm's manufacturing operations were limited to a small ASIC design and manufacturing team to support the Omnitracs system.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm was forced to expand into manufacturing in the 1990s in order to produce the hardware carriers needed to implement CDMA networks that used Qualcomm's intellectual property.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Qualcomm's first large manufacturing project was in May 1993, in a deal to provide 36,000 CDMA phones to [[US West]].<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Chen2007\"/>\n \nFor a time, Qualcomm experienced delays and other manufacturing problems, because it was in-experienced with mass manufacturing.<ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> In 1994, Qualcomm partnered with [[Northern Telecom]] and formed a joint partnership with [[Sony]], in order to leverage their manufacturing expertise.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/> [[Nokia]], [[Samsung]] and [[Motorola]] introduced their own CDMA phones in 1997.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\">{{cite book|author=Guy Klemens|title=The Cellphone: The History and Technology of the Gadget That Changed the World|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3WNnM7iZF_QC&pg=PA131|date=September 9, 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5996-4|pages=131\u2013132}}</ref> Qualcomm's manufacturing business was losing money due to large capital equipment costs and declining prices caused by competition.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/><ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/><ref name=\"Mock2005\"/> Also, in March 1997, after Qualcomm introduced its Q phone, [[Motorola]] initiated a lawsuit (settled out of court in 2000) for allegedly copying the design of its Startac phone.<ref name=\"Inc.1997\">{{cite book|first=Marc|last=Ferranti|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MToEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA44|date=March 24, 1997|newspaper=InfoWorld|page=44|accessdate=August 9, 2014|title=Motorola claims patent infringement by Qualcomm}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Motorola claims patent infringement by Qualcomm|newspaper=Infoworld|date=March 24, 1997|first=Marc|last=Ferranti}}</reF>\n \nIn December 1999, Qualcomm sold its manufacturing interests to Kyocera Corporation, a Japanese CDMA manufacturer and Qualcomm licensee.<ref name=\u201cpike\">{{cite news\n|title=Qualcomm sells CDMA phone division to Kyocera\n|first=Loring\n|last=Wirbel\n|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times\n|date=December 22, 1999\n|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1230103\n|accessdate=July 23, 2017\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n|title=Qualcomm, Kyocera strike deal for handset business\n|first=\n|last=\n|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times\n|date=December 22, 1999\n|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1124095\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> Qualcomm's infrastructure division was sold to competitor Ericsson in 1999 as part of an out-of-court agreement for a CDMA patent dispute that started in 1996.<reF name=\"thirteen\">{{Cite news|last=Alleven|first=Monica|title=Ericsson Tangles With Qualcomm|newspaper=Wireless Week|date=November 29, 1999|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/2587634/ericsson-tangles-qualcomm|accessdate=June 6, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Wireless giants get connected|publisher=The Associated Press|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&amp;dat=19990326&amp;id=NVBYAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=DY4DAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=4436,2341517|date=March 26, 1999|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> The sale of the infrastructure division marked the beginning of an increase in Qualcomm's stock price and stronger financial performance, but many of the 1,200 employees involved were discontent with working for a competitor and losing their stock options.<reF name=\"thirteen\"/><ref>{{cite news|last=Alleven|first=Monica|title=Qualcomm, Unhappy Employees Try Mediation|newspaper=Wireless Week|date=May 8, 2000|accessdate=June 6, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/3106407/qualcomm-unhappy-employees-try-mediation}}</ref> This led to a protracted legal dispute regarding employee stock options, resulting in $74 million in settlements by 2005.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/>\n \n===3G===\n3G standards were expected to force prior TDMA carriers onto CDMA, in order to meet 3G bandwidth goals.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\">{{cite book|author1=William J. Drake|author2=Ernest J. Wilson (III.)|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5A2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA166|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-04251-2|pages=166}}</ref><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> The two largest GSM manufacturers, Nokia and Ericsson, advocated for a greater role for GSM,<ref name=\"TaplinWakui2006\">{{cite book|author1=Ruth Taplin|author2=Masako Wakui|title=Japanese Telecommunications: Market and Policy in Transition|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=C6Z-AgAAQBAJ&pg=PA124|date=February 1, 2006|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-20815-9|pages=124}}</ref> in order to negotiate lower royalty prices from Qualcomm.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> In 1998, the [[European Telecommunications Standards Institute]] (ETSI) voted in support of the WCDMA standard, which relied less on Qualcomm's CDMA patents.<ref name=\"Association2010\">{{cite book|author=Information Resources Management Association|title=Networking and Telecommunications: Concepts, Methodologies, Tools, and Applications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=DYWB5nMjB38C&pg=PA240|date=January 2010|publisher=Idea Group Inc (IGI)|isbn=978-1-60566-987-8|pages=240}}</ref> Qualcomm responded by refusing to license its intellectual property for the standard.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/>\n \nThe [[Telecommunications Industry Association]] (TIA) and the Third Generation Partnership Program 2, advocated for a competing CDMA-2000 standard developed primarily by Qualcomm.<ref name=\"ChenGuizani2006\">{{cite book|author1=Hsiao-Hwa Chen|author2=Mohsen Guizani|title=Next Generation Wireless Systems and Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=MVEaQ7TRBTMC&pg=PA122|date=May 1, 2006|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-02435-5|pages=122}}</ref><ref name=\"Unhelkar2006\">{{cite book|author=Bhuvan Unhelkar|title=Handbook of Research in Mobile Business: Technical, Methodological and Social Perspectives|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IvHcyXDzu4oC&pg=PA150|date=January 1, 2006|publisher=Idea Group Inc (IGI)|isbn=978-1-59140-818-5|pages=150}}</ref> American and European politicians advocated for the CDMA-2000 and WCDMA standards respectively.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> The ITU said it would exclude Qualcomm's CDMA technology from the 3G standards entirely if a patent dispute over the technology with Ericsson was not resolved.<ref name=\"Mock2005\"/><ref name=\"Lennon2007\"/> The two reached an agreement out-of-court in 1999, one month before a deadline set by the ITU. Both companies agreed to cross-license their technology to each other<ref name=\"Lennon2007\">{{cite book|first=Michael|last=Lennon|title=Drafting Technology Patent License Agreements|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=i3MLYUjRWisC&pg=SA1-PA31|year=2007|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-6748-1|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>{{RP|30}} and to work together on 3G standards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ericsson/Qualcomm bitter feud ends|newspaper=Telephony|date=March 29, 1999|accessdate=June 6, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/2183790/ericsson-qualcomm-bitter-feud-ends|last=Gohring|first=Nancy}}</ref>\n \nA compromise was eventually reached whereby the ITU would initially endorse three standards: CDMA2000 1X, WCDMA and TD-SCDMA.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\">{{cite book|author1=William J. Drake|author2=Ernest J. Wilson (III.)|title=Governing Global Electronic Networks: International Perspectives on Policy and Power|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=5A2mAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA166|date=December 5, 2008|publisher=MIT Press|isbn=978-0-262-04251-2|pages=166}}</ref> Qualcomm agreed to license its CDMA patents for variants such as WCDMA.<ref name=\"Drake(III.)2008\"/> There were 240 million CDMA 3G subscribers by 2004 and 143 carriers in 67 countries by 2005.<ref name=\"Chen2007\"/> Qualcomm claimed to own 38 percent of WCDMA's essential patents, whereas European GSM interests sponsored a research paper allegigng Qualcomm only owned 19 percent.<ref name=\"BlaxillEckardt2009\"/>\n \nQualcomm consolidated its interests in telecommunications carriers, such as [[Cricket Communications]] and [[Pegaso]] into a holding company, [[Leap Wireless]], in 1998.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Calls Off a Spinoff and Realigns Management|first=Chris|last=Gaither|date=July 25, 2001|newspaper=The New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2001/07/25/business/technology-qualcomm-calls-off-a-spinoff-and-realigns-management.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Steinbock2003\"/> Leap was spun-off later that year<Ref name=\"jkopys\"/> and sold to [[AT&T]] in 2014.<Ref name=\"jkopys\">{{cite news|title=Leap Wireless Reports $640.8M Loss for 2013 as Sale to AT&T Looms|first=Mike|last=Allen|date=March 9, 2014|url=http://sdbj.com/news/2014/mar/09/leap-wireless-reports-6408m-loss-2013-sale-t-looms/|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF>\n \n===4G===\nQualcomm initially advocated for the CDMA-based [[Ultra Mobile Broadband]] (UMB) standard for fourth generation wireless networks.<ref name=\"Unhelkar2009\">{{cite book|author=Bhuvan Unhelkar|title=Mobile Enterprise Transition and Management|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=OPXZFkBzvd8C&pg=PA132|date=June 25, 2009|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4200-7828-2|pages=132}}</ref> UMB wasn't backwards compatible with prior CDMA networks and didn't operate as well in narrow bandwidths as the LTE (long-term evolution) standard. No cellular networks adopted UMB.<ref name=\"Cox2012\">{{cite book|author=Christopher Cox|title=An Introduction to LTE: LTE, LTE-Advanced, SAE and 4G Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=q04NlHWgnfYC&pg=PA16|date=February 28, 2012|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-94281-8|pages=16}}</ref> Qualcomm halted development of UMB in 2005 and decided to support the LTE standard,<ref name=\"Korhonen2014\">{{cite book|author=Juha Korhonen|title=Introduction to 4G Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=lutPAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA26|date=March 1, 2014|publisher=Artech House|isbn=978-1-60807-699-4|pages=26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm halts UMB project, sees no major job cuts|first=Sinead|last=Carew|date=November 13, 2008|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/11/13/us-qualcomm-umb-idUSTRE4AC7M720081113|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> even though it didn't rely as heavily on Qualcomm patents.<ref>{{cite news|title=What's next for Qualcomm?|first=Jessi|last=Hempel|date=June 24, 2009|url=http://cnnfn.cnn.com/2009/06/23/technology/qualcomm_wireless_chips_new_gadgets.fortune/index.htm?postversion=2009062406|newspaper=Fortune Magazine|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> Then, Qualcomm purchased LTE-related patents through acquisitions.<ref name=\"Coll2013\">{{cite book|author=Eric Coll|title=Telecom, Datacom and Networking for Non-Engineers: Reference Book - CTNS Study Guide|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jZPTNW--k40C&pg=PA115|date=September 9, 2013|publisher=Teracom Training Institute|isbn=978-1-894887-05-2|pages=115}}</ref> By 2012, Qualcomm held 81 seminal patents used in 4G LTE standards, or 12.46 percent.<ref name=\"Reed 2012\">{{cite web | last=Reed | first=Brad | title=Watch out Apple: Samsung, Qualcomm positioned to dominate LTE patent wars | website=Network World | date=April 26, 2012 | url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2188067/wireless/watch-out-apple--samsung--qualcomm-positioned-to-dominate-lte-patent-wars.html | accessdate=October 29, 2015}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm also became more focused on using its intellectual property to manufacture semiconductors in a [[fabless manufacturing]] model.<ref>{{cite news|DUPLICATE-title=Can Samsung Get Qualcomm in LTE Market?|title=Casualty is not Qualcomm but Broadcom|first=Junko|last=Yoshida|date=July 11, 2014|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1323072|accessdate=August 20, 2014}}</ref> A VLSI Technology Organization division was founded in 2004, followed by a DFX group in 2006, which did more of the manufacturing design in-house.<ref name=\"eetimesss\">{{cite news|title=Fabless Qualcomm zooms to next node|first=Mark|last=LaPedus|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=November 27, 2006|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1164472|accessdate=July 28, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm announced it was developing the [[Scorpion (CPU)|Scorpion]] [[central processing unit]] (CPU) for mobile devices in November 2005.<ref>{{cite news|title=Snapdragon seeds Qualcomm's future|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=June 4, 2007|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1247637|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</reF><ref name=\"djabnf\">{{cite news|title=Analysis: Qualcomm's 1 GHz ARM \"Snapdragon\"|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1275485|publisher=Electronic Engineering Times|accessdate=October 2, 2014|author=BDTI|date=December 5, 2007}}</reF> This was followed by the first shipments of the [[Snapdragon (system on chip)|Snapdragon]] system-on-chip product, which includes a CPU, GPS, graphics processing unit, camera support and other software and semiconductors,<Ref name=\"extreme\">{{cite news|title=How Qualcomm's Snapdragon ARM chips are unique|first=Ryan|last=Whitwam|date=August 26, 2011|url=http://www.extremetech.com/mobile/94064-how-qualcomms-snapdragon-arm-chips-are-unique|publisher=ExtremeTech|accessdate=October 4, 2014}}</ref> in November 2007.<ref name=\"cnet\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/toshiba-handheld-hits-1ghz-with-snapdragon/|accessdate=October 2, 2014|publisher=CNET|date=February 3, 2009|first=Brooke|last=Crothers|title=Toshiba handheld hits 1GHz with 'Snapdragon'}}</ref> The [[Gobi]] family of modems for portable devices was released in 2008.<ref name=\"giz announcement\">{{ cite news  | url = http://gizmodo.com/#!314704/qualcomm-gobi-3g-chip-goes-both-ways-ev+do-or-hsdpa\n | title = Qualcomm Gobi 3G Chip Goes Both Ways: EV-DO or HSDPA\n | accessdate =February 2, 2011\n | publisher = gizmodo.com\n|first=Matt\n|last= Buchanan }}\n</ref><ref name=\"engadget announcement\">{{ cite web  | url = http://www.engadget.com/2007/10/24/qualcomms-dual-3g-gobi-chip-handles-ev-do-and-hspa/\n | title = Qualcomm's dual-3G Gobi chip handles EV-DO and HSPA -- Engadget\n | accessdate = February 11, 2011\n | publisher = engadget.com\n|date=October 24, 2007\n|first=Darren\n|last=Murph}}\n</ref> Gobi modems were embedded in many laptop brands<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's new Gobi: A WiMax and Wi-Fi killer?|first=Matt|last=Hamblen|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=August 18, 2014|url=http://www.computerworld.com/s/article/9073838/Qualcomm_s_new_Gobi_A_WiMax_and_Wi_Fi_killer_|newspaper=Computerworld}}</ref><Ref>{{cite news|title=Panasonic taps Qualcomm Gobi for broadband data|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=September 11, 2008|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1169259|accessdate=August 18, 2014}}</ref> and Snapdragon system on chips were embedded into most Android devices.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm to buy Atheros for $3.2 billion|date=January 6, 2011|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2011/01/05/AR2011010506338.html|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=October 2, 2014}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm won a government auction in India in 2010 for $1 billion in spectrum and licenses from which to offer broadband services. It formed four joint ventures with Indian holding companies for this purpose. A 49 percent stake in the holding companies was acquired by [[Bharti]] in May 2012 and the remaining was acquired in October 2012<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Exits India Broadband Venture|last=Krishna|first=Jai|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|date=October 18, 2013|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702304864504579143020414211610|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> by AT&T.<ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T closes on Leap acquisition, with conditions|first=Dan|last=Meyer|date=March 14, 2014|url=http://www.rcrwireless.com/20140314/carriers/att-closes-on-leap-acquisition-with-conditions|publisher=RCR Wireless|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</reF>\n \n===5G===\nAccording to <i>Fortune Magazine</i>, Qualcomm has been developing technologies for future 5G standards in three areas: radios that would use bandwidth from any network it has access to, creating larger ranges of spectrum by combining smaller pieces, and a set of services for [[internet of things]] applications.<ref name=\"Higginbotham 2015\">{{cite news| last=Higginbotham | first=Stacey | title=Qualcomm readies itself for 5G with these 3 tech breakthroughs | newspaper=Fortune | date=October 14, 2015 | url=http://fortune.com/2015/10/14/qualcomm-5g/ | accessdate=October 18, 2015}}</ref> Qualcomm's first 5G modem chip was announced in October 2016<ref name=\"Captain 2016\">{{cite web | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=The Wild Technology That Will Make 5G Wireless Work | website=Fast Company | date=October 18, 2016 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3064144/the-wild-technology-that-will-make-5g-wireless-work | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> and a prototype was demonstrated in October 2017.<ref name=\"BBC News 2017\">{{cite web | title=5G high-speed data 'milestone' claimed | website=BBC News | date=October 17, 2017 | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-41652967 | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm's first 5G antennas were announced in July 2018.<ref name=\"Smith 2018\">{{cite web | last=Smith | first=Ryan | title=Qualcomm Announces Their First 5G mmWave Antenna Module: QTM052, Coming This Year | website=AnandTech | date=2018-07-23 | url=https://www.anandtech.com/show/13106/qualcomm-announces-their-first-5g-mmwave-antenna-module-qtm052-coming-this-year | accessdate=2018-09-02}}</ref> As of 2018, Qualcomm has partnerships with 19 mobile device manufacturers and 18 carriers to commercialize 5G technology.<ref name=\"Horwitz 2018\">{{cite web | last=Horwitz | first=Jeremy | title=Qualcomm signs 19 phone makers and 18 carriers for global 5G launches in 2019 | website=VentureBeat | date=February 8, 2018 | url=https://venturebeat.com/2018/02/08/qualcomm-signs-19-phone-makers-and-18-carriers-for-global-5g-launches-in-2019/ | accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> By late 2019, several phone were being sold with Qualcomm's 5G technology incorporated.<ref name=\"Nellis 2019\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=Qualcomm-Samsung axis brings 5G to the masses as Huawei struggles | website=U.S. | date=September 6, 2019 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-5g-idUSKCN1VR1HT | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n \n==Software and other technology==\n===Early software===\nQualcomm acquired an email application called [[Eudora (email client)|Eudora]] in 1991.<ref name=\"merc\">{{cite news|newspaper=San Jose Mercury News|title=Technology Testdrive Column|date=February 27, 2000 | last=Langberg|first= Mike}}</ref> By 1996, Eudora was installed on 63 percent of PCs.<ref>{{cite news\n|title=Utilities get with the e-mail program\n|first=Peter\n|last=Grad\n|newspaper=The Record\n|date=November 25, 1996\n|url=\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> [[Microsoft Outlook]] eclipsed Eudora, since it was provided for free by default on Windows-based machines.<ref name=\"aplip\">{{cite news\n|title=Good-Bye Eudora\n|first=\n|last=\n|publisher=Associated Press\n|date=October 21, 2006\n|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1350&dat=20061021&id=-HFPAAAAIBAJ&sjid=mgQEAAAAIBAJ&pg=3308,1348487\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> By 2003 Qualcomm's Eudora was the most popular alternative to Microsoft Outlook, but still had only a five percent share of the market.<ref name=\"alt\">{{cite news\n|title=Alternativees can liberate you form Microsoft e-mail software\n|first=\n|last=\n|newspaper=Dallas Morning News\n|date=September 1, 2003\n|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=888&dat=20030901&id=xrRQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YV4DAAAAIBAJ&pg=2307,428729\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref> Software development for Eudora was retired in 2006.<ref name=\"aplip\"/>\n \nIn 2001, Qualcomm introduced [[Binary Runtime Environment for Wireless|Brew]], a smartphone app development service<ref name=\"whatisbrew\">{{cite news|title=BREW (Binary Runtime Environment for Wireless)|first=Margaret|last=Rouse|url=http://searchmobilecomputing.techtarget.com/definition/BREW|publisher=TechTarget}}</ref><ref name=\"Etoh2005\"/><ref name=\"daghniouhd\">{{cite news|title=A fresh outlook on 3G|last1=Carroll|first1=Kelly|newspaper=Telephony|date=April 16, 2001|url=http://connectedplanetonline.com/mag/telecom_fresh_outlook/|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> with APIs to access contacts, billing, app-stores, or multimedia on the phone.<ref name=\"Etoh2005\">{{cite book|author=Minoru Etoh|title=Next Generation Mobile Systems: 3G & Beyond|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3R-Hc106lb8C&pg=PA199|date=August 5, 2005|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-09152-4|pages=199}}</ref> South Korean carrier KTFreeTel was the first to adopt the Brew system in November 2001, followed by Verizon in March 2002<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Unveils its new BREW|first=Brad|last=Graves|date=March 18, 2002|url=http://san-diego-business-journal.vlex.com/vid/qualcomm-brew-verizon-nationwide-rollout-54435867|accessdate=August 12, 2014}}</ref> for its \"Get it Now\" program. There were 2.5 million Brew users by the end of 2002 and 73 million in 2003.<ref name=\"Chen2007\"/>\n \n===Other technology===\nIn 2004, Qualcomm created a [[MediaFLO]] subsidiary to bring its FLO (forward link only) specification to market. Qualcomm built an $800 million MediaFLO network of cell towers to supplement carrier networks with one that is designed for multimedia.<ref name=\"yugdtsuobdajf\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Re-Imagines Mobile Media|first=Kevin|last=Fitchard|url=http://connectedplanetonline.com/mag/telecom_qualcomm_reimagines_mobile/|newspaper=Connected Planet|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=November 8, 2004}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Invests In TV Broadcasts Over Cellphones|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=November 2, 2004|accessdate=August 10, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB109935045322361616}}</reF> In comparison to cellular towers that provide two-way communications with each cell phone individually, MediaFLO towers would broadcast multimedia content to mobile phones in a one-way broadcast.<ref name=\"dajobiurebv\">{{cite news|title=Go with the FLO?|date=February 27, 2007|url=http://www.wirelessweek.com/news/2007/02/go-w-ith-flo|first=Karen|last=Brown|accessdate=August 10, 2014|newspaper=Wireless Week}}</ref><ref name=\"apdia\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/10286552/ns/technology_and_science-wireless/t/verizon-offer-broadcast-tv-over-cell-phones/#.U-fTQ4BdWxE|publisher=Associated Press|accessdate=August 10, 2014|date=December 1, 2005|title=Verizon to offer broadcast TV over cell phones}}</reF> Qualcomm also sold FLO-based semiconductors and licenses.<ref>{{cite news|last=Fitchard|first=Kevin|title=TV wars go wireless|newspaper=Telephony|date=September 26, 2005|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/15075230/qualcomm-eyes-programming-phones|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|first=Brad|last=Graves|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=November 2004|title=Qualcomm Eyes Programming For Phones}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm created the FLO Forum standards group with 15 industry participants in July 2005.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Electronic Engineering Times|date=September 12, 2005|title=Mobile-TV on-ramp under construction -- But lack of chip sets, profusion of net options could bring delays|first=Rick|last=Merritt|url=http://business.highbeam.com/3094/article-1G1-136081199/mobiletv-ramp-under-construction-but-lack-chip-sets|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</reF> Verizon was the first carrier to partner with MediaFlo in December 2005<ref name=\"apdia\"/> for its Verizon Wireless' V Cast TV,<Ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.cnet.com/Verizon-offers-live-TV-on-cell-phones/2100-1039_3-6147908.html|publisher=CNET|accessdate=August 10, 2014|date=January 7, 2007|title=Verizon offers live TV on cell phones|first=Marguerite|last=Reardon }}</ref> which was followed by the AT&T Mobile TV service a couple months later.<ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T's MediaFLO TV coming in May|first=Stephen|last=Lawson|publisher=IDG|date=Mar 28, 2008|accessdate=August 10, 2014|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2285013/network-security/at-t-s-mediaflo-tv-coming-in-may.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=AT&T airs TV service on new phones|first=Peter|last=Svensson|publisher=Associated Press|url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/story?id=4773117|accessdate=August 10, 2014}}</ref> The MediaFlo service was launched on Super Bowl Sunday in 2007.<ref name=\"unique13\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Suspends Flo Mobile TV Sales|first=Priya|last=Ganapati|publisher=WIRED|date=October 5, 2010|url=http://www.wired.com/2010/10/qualcomm-cancels-flo-tv/|accessdate=August 19, 2014}}</ref> Despite the interest the service got among carriers, it was unpopular among consumers.<ref name=\"unique13\"/><ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><Ref name=\"uniquename\"/> The service required users to pay for a subscription and have phones that were equipped with special semiconductors.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\">{{cite news|title=Why Qualcomm thinks LTE-broadcast will work where FLO TV failed|first=Kevin|last=Kitchard|date=April 9, 2014|publisher=Giga Om|url=http://gigaom.com/2013/04/09/why-qualcomm-thinks-lte-broadcast-will-work-where-flo-tv-failed/|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</reF><Ref name=\"uniquename\"/> The service was discontinued in 2011 and its spectrum was sold to AT&T for $1.93 billion.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><Ref name=\"uniquename\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Wants To Dump \"MediaFLO\" Mobile TV Business No One Watches|first=Dan|last=Frommer|date=July 22, 2010|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/qualcomm-wants-to-dump-its-mediaflo-mobile-tv-business-2010-7#ixzz39wzl7jAE|publisher=Business Insider|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm rebooted the effort in 2013 with LTE Broadcast, which uses pre-existing cell towers to broadcast select content locally on a dedicated spectrum, such as during major sporting events.<ReF name=\"gigaomyud\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=LTE broadcast may help Qualcomm salvage Flo TV|newspaper=PC World|url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/2030367/lte-broadcast-may-help-qualcomm-salvage-flo-tv.html|first=Stephen|last=Lawson|accessdate=August 12, 2014|date=March 19, 2013}}</reF>\n \nBased on technology acquired from Iridigm in 2004 for $170 million,<ref name=\"cnn\">{{cite web |url=http://money.cnn.com/magazines/business2/business2_archive/2007/06/01/100050991/ |title=Product design, nature's way |last=Watters |first=Ethan |work=CNNMoney |publisher=Cable News Network |date=June 12, 2007}}</ref> Qualcomm began commercializing [[Mirasol]] displays in 2007, which was expanded into eight products in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Screens Pack Visual Punch With Scant Power|first=Brad|last=Graves|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=June 9, 2008}}</reF> Mirasol uses natural light shining on a screen to provide lighting for the display, rather a backlight, in order to reduce power consumption.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Bright Low-Power Screen|first=Cliff|last=Edwards|date=April 28, 2010|newspaper=Businessweek|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2010-04-28/qualcomms-bright-low-power-screen|accessdate=October 24, 2014}}</ref> The amount of space between the surface of the display and a mirror within a 10 micron-wide \"interferometric modulator\" determines the color of the reflected light.<ref>{{cite news|title=E-Reader Display Shows Vibrant Color Video|first=Tom|last=Simonite|date=November 15, 2011|url=http://www.technologyreview.com/news/426120/e-reader-display-shows-vibrant-color-video/|accessdate=October 24, 2014|newspaper=Technology Review}}</ref> Mirasol was eventually closed down after an attempt to revive it in 2013 in Toq watches.<ref name=\"Captain 2017\">{{cite web | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=The Everything Chip: Qualcomm\u2019s Plan To Power Drones, VR, Cars, PCs, And More | website=Fast Company | date=January 10, 2017 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/3066849/qualcomm-drones-vr-cars-satellites | accessdate=January 21, 2020}}</ref>\n \nIn June 2011, Qualcomm introduced [[AllJoyn]], a wireless standard for communicating between devices like cell phones, televisions, air-conditioners, and refrigerators.<ref name=\"alljoynnww\">{{cite news|newspaper=Network World|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2456421/internet-of-things/a-guide-to-the-confusing-internet-of-things-standards-world.html|title=A guide to the confusing Internet of Things standards world|first=Colin|last=Neagle}}</ref><Ref name=\"oneilyady\">{{cite news|title=At CES, the Internet of Everything will Speak Alljoyn|first=Leah|last=Hunter|newspaper=Fast Company|url=http://www.fastcompany.com/3024203/innovation-agents/at-ces-the-internet-of-everything-will-be-powered-by-alljoyn|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"FitzekKatz2013\">{{cite book|author1=Frank H. P. Fitzek|author2=Marcos D. Katz|title=Mobile Clouds: Exploiting Distributed Resources in Wireless, Mobile and Social Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=jmlXAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT211|date=December 11, 2013|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-118-80140-6|pages=211}}</ref> The Alljoyn technology was donated to the [[Linux Foundation]] in December 2013. Qualcomm and the Linux Foundation then formed the Allseen Alliance to administer the standard<ref name=\"alljoynnww\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Brad|last=Graves|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=January 6, 2014|title=Internet of Things Set to Bring Lots of Connections, Opportunity}}</ref> and Qualcomm developed products that used the AllJoyn standard<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's smartwatch is Toq of the town|first=John|last=Shinal|newspaper=USA Today|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/MONEY/usaedition/2013-09-05-Qualcomm-is-seeding-market-for-wearable-devices_ST_U.htm|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm\u2019s Toq Smartwatch Needs More Time|date=December 26, 2013|url=http://allthingsd.com/20131226/qualcomms-toq-smartwatch-needs-more-time/|publisher=AllThingsD|accessdate=August 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Timex launches smartwatch with Qualcomm technology|first=Noel|last=Randewich|date=August 5, 2014|publisher=Reuters|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/08/06/us-timex-qualcomm-idUSKBN0G600520140806|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> In December 2011, Qualcomm formed a healthcare subsidiary called Qualcomm Life. Simultaneously, the subsidiary released a cloud-based service for managing clinical data called 2net and the Qualcomm Life Fund, which invests in wireless healthcare technology companies.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Subsidiary Focuses on Mobile Medical Data|url=http://www.informationweek.com/mobile/qualcomm-subsidiary-focuses-on-mobile-medical-data/d/d-id/1101744?|newspaper=InformationWeek|accessdate=October 24, 2014|date=December 8, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Launches Mobile Health Company, New Cloud Medical Data Platform|first=Brian|last=Horowitz|url=http://www.eweek.com/c/a/Health-Care-IT/Qualcomm-Launches-Mobile-Health-Company-New-Cloud-Medical-Data-Platform-435345/|newspaper=eWeek}}</ref> The subsidiary doubled its employee-count by acquiring HealthyCircles Inc., a healthcare IT company, the following May.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Acquires medical Software Maker|first=Meghana|last=Keshavan|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=March 11, 2013}}</ref> Qualcomm life was later sold to a private equity firm, Francisco Partners, in 2019.<ref name=\"MobiHealthNews 2019\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Life acquired by PE firm Francisco Partners, will spin off under new name | website=MobiHealthNews | date=February 11, 2019 | url=https://www.mobihealthnews.com/content/qualcomm-life-acquired-pe-firm-francisco-partners-will-spin-under-new-name | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref>\n \n===Recent developments===\nIn 2016, Qualcomm developed its first beta processor chip for servers and PCs called \u201cServer Development Platform\u201d and sent samples for testing.<ref name=\"dalihgeahrocin\">{{cite news | first=Aaron|last=Tilley|title=Qualcomm Launches The First 10nm Server Chip | newspaper=Forbes | date=December 7, 2016 | url=http://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2016/12/07/qualcomm-launches-the-first-10nm-server-chip/#50f9ae034b62 | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In January 2017, a second generation data center and PC server chip called Centriq 2400 was released.<ref name=\"dalihgeahrocin\"/> <i>PC Magazine</i> said the release was \"historic\" for Qualcomm, because it was a new market segment for the company.<ref name=\"Shah 2016\">{{cite web | last=Shah | first=Agam | title=Sleeping giant Qualcomm awakens with aim to crush Intel at its own game | website=PCWorld | date=December 12, 2016 | url=http://www.pcworld.com/article/3149749/components-processors/sleeping-giant-qualcomm-awakens-with-aim-to-crush-intel-at-its-own-game.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also created a Qualcomm Datacenter Technologies subsidiary to focus on the PCs and servers market.<ref name=\"eWeek.com 2016\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Names Upcoming Server Family Centriq | website=eWeek.com | date=August 19, 2016 | url=http://www.eweek.com/servers/qualcomm-names-upcoming-server-family-centriq.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In 2017, Qualcomm introduced embedded technology for 3D cameras intended for augmented reality apps.<ref name=\"Captain 2017b\">{{cite news | last=Captain | first=Sean | title=Qualcomm\u2019s New Camera Will Give Smartphones 3D Vision | newspaper=Fast Company | date=August 15, 2017 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/40451913/qualcomms-new-camera-will-give-smartphones-3d-vision | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm is also developing and demonstrating laptop processors and other parts, as of 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Takes Another Shot at Ending Intel PC Stranglehold | website=Bloomberg|first=Ian|last=King | date=December 5, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-12-05/qualcomm-takes-another-shot-at-breaking-intel-pc-stranglehold | accessdate=August 16, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn 2000, Qualcomm formed a joint venture with [[Ford Motor Company|FORD]] called Wingcast, which created [[telematics]] equipment for cars, but was unsuccessful and closed down two years later.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Ford, Qualcomm form auto-telecom venture|publisher=The Associated Press|first=Justin|last=Hyde|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1129&amp;dat=20000801&amp;id=4oUNAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=aW8DAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=5050,221397|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Mark|last=Lewis|date=June 4, 2002|title=Ford Grounds Its Wingcast Venture|url=http://www.forbes.com/2002/06/04/0604telematics.html|accessdate=October 24, 2014|newspaper=Forbes}}</reF><ref>{{cite news|first=Ben|last=Charny |date=June 4, 2002|url=http://www.zdnet.com/news/qualcomm-grounds-wingcast-venture/123199|title=Qualcomm grounds Wingcast venture|publisher=ZDNet|accessdate=October 24, 2014 }}</reF> Qualcomm acquired the wireless electric car charging company, HaloIPT, in November 2011<Ref>{{cite news|title=University sells off wireless technology|first=Catherine|last=Harris|newspaper=The Press|date=November 10, 2011|page=A.14}}</ref> and later sold the company to WiTricity in February 2019.<ref name=\"Sawers 2019\">{{cite web | last=Sawers | first=Paul | title=WiTricity acquires Qualcomm Halo to accelerate wireless charging for electric vehicles | website=VentureBeat | date=February 11, 2019 | url=https://venturebeat.com/2019/02/11/witricity-acquires-qualcomm-halo-to-accelerate-wireless-charging-for-electric-vehicles/ | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Qualcomm also started introducing Snapdragon system-on-chips<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm brings its Snapdragon chip to the car|first=James|last=Niccolai|publisher=IDG News Service|date=January 6, 2014|url=http://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1320552&page_number=1|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</ref> and Gobi modems<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm launches 64-bit chips for high-end phones at MWC 2014|first=Shara|last=Tibken|date=February 23, 2014|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-launches-64-bit-chips-for-high-end-phones-at-mwc-2014/|publisher=CNET|accessdate=October 23, 2014}}</reF> and other software or semiconductor products for self-driving cars and modern in-car computers.<ref name=\"Velazco 2017\">{{cite web | last=Velazco | first=Chris | title=Qualcomm wants to make smarter cars by sharing sensor data | website=Engadget | date=January 3, 2017 | url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/01/03/qualcomm-wants-to-make-smarter-cars-by-sharing-sensor-data/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Condon 2017\">{{cite web | last=Condon | first=Stephanie | title=New Qualcomm auto chipset advances vehicle-to-everything communications | website=ZDNet | date=August 31, 2017 | url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/new-qualcomm-auto-chipset-advances-vehicle-to-everything-communications/ | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n \n==Patents and patent disputes==\nAs of 2017, Qualcomm owns more than 130,000 current or pending patents.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\">{{cite web | last=Chafkin | first=Max | last2=King | first2=Ian | title=Apple and Qualcomm\u2019s Billion-Dollar War Over an $18 Part | website=Bloomberg.com | date=October 4, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/features/2017-10-04/apple-and-qualcomm-s-billion-dollar-war-over-an-18-part | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> By the early 2000s, Qualcomm had more than 1,000 patents.<ref name=\"eight\">{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&amp;dat=20000916&amp;id=TrkeAAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=8s8EAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=6534,472942|title=Qualcomm streamlines for wireless battle|first=Michael|last=White|date=September 16, 2000|accessdate=June 5, 2014|publisher=Associated Press}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&amp;dat=20000726&amp;id=jbM0AAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=OiEGAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=3257,3098830|publisher=Associated Press|date=July 26, 2000|accessdate=June 3, 2014|title=Qualcomm spinning off businesses}}</ref> As the sole early investor in CDMA research and development, Qualcomm's patent portfolio contains much of the intellectual property that is essential to CDMA technologies.<ref name=\"Klemens2010\"/>\n \nSince many of Qualcomm's patents are part of an industry standard, the company has agreed to license those patents under \u201cfair, reasonable, and non-discriminatory\u201d terms.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> Qualcomm's royalties come out to about 5% or $30 per mobile device.<ref name=\"Chafkin King 2017\"/> According to Fortune Magazine, this is about 5-10 times more than what is typically charged by other patent-holders.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> Qualcomm says its patents are more expensive because they are more important and its pricing is within the range of common licensing practices.<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\"/> However, competitors, clients, and regulators often allege Qualcomm charges unreasonable rates or engages in unfair competition for mandatory patents.<ref name=\"Delta2009\">{{cite book|first=George|last=Delta|title=Law of the Internet|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=0eMafpE7A0YC&pg=RA1-SA7-PA23|year=2009|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-7559-2|pages=1|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \n===Broadcom===\nIn 2005, Broadcom and Qualcomm were unable to reach an agreement on cross-licensing their intellectual property,<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm punished with phone import ban|first=Kathryn|last=Balint|date=June 8, 2007|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20070608/news_1n8qualcomm.html|newspaper=Union-Tribune San Diego|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> and Broadcom sued Qualcomm alleging it was breach ten Broadcom patents.<ref name=\"wsjwsjwsjjj\">{{cite news|title=Broadcom Levels Suit on Qualcomm|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB111651086084838082|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=May 20, 2005}}</ref><ref name=\"Mei2012\">{{cite book|first=Lei|last=Mei|title=Conducting Business in China: An Intellectual Property Perspective|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=IelMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA161|date=November 8, 2012|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-976022-0|pages=161}}</ref> Broadcom asked the International Trade Commission to prohibit importing the affected technology.<ref name=\"wsjwsjwsjjj\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom seeks injunction in intellectual property war|newspaper=Financial Times|date=May 20, 2005|first=Simon|last=London|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/5b00902c-c8cb-11d9-87c9-00000e2511c8.html#axzz39iO1EwRz|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> A separate lawsuit alleged Qualcomm was threatening to withhold UMTS patent licenses against manufacturers that bought their semiconductors from competitors, in violation of the standards agreement.<ref name=\"Stern2005\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Suit by Broadcom Says Qualcomm Seeks a Monopoly|first=Don|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|date=July 6, 2005|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB112056555346377303|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Stern2005\">{{cite journal|last1=Stern|first1=R.H.|title=Standardization skullduggery update: UMTS standard|journal=IEEE Micro|volume=25|issue=4|year=2005|pages=73\u201376|issn=0272-1732|doi=10.1109/MM.2005.76}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Rival Names Qualcomm in Antitrust Suit|publisher=Bloomberg|date=July 6, 2014|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2005/07/06/technology/06broadcom.html?_r=0|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm alleged Broadcom was using litigation as a negotiation tactic and that it would respond with its own lawsuits.<ref name=\"Stern2005\"/><ref>{{cite news|first=Andrew|last=Simons|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom Fight Stands to Be Costly|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=July 18, 2005|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/17871652/qualcomm-broadcom-fight-stands-be-costly}}</ref> Qualcomm sued Broadcom, alleging it was using seven Qualcomm patents without permission.<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm sues Broadcom over patents|first=Grant|last=Gross|publisher=IDG News Service|date=July 11, 2005|url=http://www.networkworld.com/article/2322556/network-security/qualcomm-sues-broadcom-over-patents.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> By late 2006, more than 20 lawsuits had been filed between the two parties and both sides claimed to be winning.<ref name=\"bwuyda\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom Face Off|first1=Ron|last1=Grover|first2=Olga|last2=Kharif|date=October 3, 2006|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2006-10-03/qualcomm-broadcom-face-off|newspaper=BusinessWeek|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \nIn September 2006, a New Jersey court judge ruled that Qualcomm's patent monopoly was an inherit aspect of creating industry standards and that Qualcomm's pricing practices were lawful.<ref name=\"bwuyda\"/><ref name=\"Stern2006\">{{cite journal|url=http://ieeexplore.ieee.org/xpl/login.jsp?tp=&arnumber=1709817&url=http%3A%2F%2Fieeexplore.ieee.org%2Fiel5%2F40%2F36071%2F01709817.pdf%3Farnumber%3D1709817|accessdate=August 9, 2014|last1=Stern|first1=R.|title=New Jersey federal court holds Qualcomm's unFRANDly acts no antitrust violation|journal=IEEE Micro|volume=26|issue=5|year=2006|pages=9\u201385|issn=0272-1732|doi=10.1109/MM.2006.97|date=September-October 2006}}</ref> In May 2007, a jury ordered Qualcomm to pay Broadcom $19.6 million for infringing on three Broadcom patents.<ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom Wins Verdict Against Rival Qualcomm|first1=Roger|last1=Cheng|first2=Don|last2=Clark|date=May 30, 2007|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118046894245217541|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> In June 2007, the ITC ruled that Qualcomm had infringed on at least one Broadcom patent and banned corresponding imports.<ref name=\"Mei2012\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom versus Qualcomm: Patents and the International Trade Commission|first=Jay|last=Sandvos|date=July 18, 2007|url=http://www.edn.com/electronics-news/4315644/Broadcom-versus-Qualcomm-Patents-and-the-International-Trade-Commission|newspaper=Electronic Design News|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> Qualcomm and Broadcom reached a settlement in April 2009, resulting in a cross-licensing agreement, a dismissal of all litigation and Qualcomm paying $891 million over four years.<ref name=\"julione\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm, Broadcom reach $891 million settlement|publisher=CNET|url=http://www.cnet.com/news/qualcomm-broadcom-reach-891-million-settlement/|first=Brooke|last=Crothers|date=April 26, 2009|accessdate=July 29, 2014}}</ref>\n \nDuring the litigation, Qualcomm claimed it had never participated in the JVT standards-setting process.<ref name=\"handbook\">{{cite book|title=Antitrust and Associations Handbook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=azpqjkiybX0C&pg=PA153|year=2009|publisher=American Bar Association|isbn=978-1-60442-392-1}}</ref>{{RP|153}} However, an engineer's testimony led to discovery of 21 JVT-related email Qualcomm lawyers had withheld from the court and 200,000 pages of JVT-related documents.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\"/> Qualcomm's lawyers said the evidence was overlooked by accident, whereas the judge said it was gross misconduct.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\"/><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm battles in federal court|date=October 13, 2007|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1876&dat=20071013&id=f2o1AAAAIBAJ&sjid=xNAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=1893,4820957|accessdate=June 5, 2014|newspaper=Herald Journal}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|title=Broadcom Lands Blows to Rival|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB118648775574690358?mg=reno64-wsj&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fonline.wsj.com%2Farticle%2FSB118648775574690358.html|first=Don|last=Clark|date=August 8, 2007|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</reF> Qualcomm was fined $8.5 million for legal misconduct.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Court Rules For Former Qualcomm Lawyers, Blasts Qualcomm Employees|first=Dona|last=Clark|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB10001424052702303411604575168631785800738|accessdate=August 9, 2014|date=April 7, 2010}}</ref> On appeal, the court held that Qualcomm could only enforce the related patents against non-JVT members, based on the agreements signed to participate in JVT.<ref name=\"handbook\"/><ref name=\"BlockEpstein1995\">{{cite book|author1=Dennis J. Block|author2=Michael A. Epstein|title=The Corporate Counsellor's Deskbook|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=myNUO_May5kC&pg=SA13-PA141|date=December 1995|publisher=Aspen Publishers Online|isbn=978-0-7355-0381-6}}</ref>{{RP|7}}\n \n===Nokia and Project Stockholm===\nSix large telecommunications companies<ref name=\"randommm\">{{cite news|title=E.U. Drops Antitrust Case Against Qualcomm|date=November 25, 2009|url=http://dealbook.nytimes.com/2009/11/25/eu-drops-antitrust-case-against-qualcomm/|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> led by Nokia<ref name=\"goodsource\">{{cite news|title=Why Qualcomm Folded to Nokia|first=Jennifer|last=Schenker|date=July 24, 2008|newspaper=BusinessWeek|url=http://www.businessweek.com/stories/2008-07-24/why-qualcomm-folded-to-nokiabusinessweek-business-news-stock-market-and-financial-advice|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</reF> filed a complaint against Qualcomm with the [[European Commission]]'s antitrust division<ref name=\"goodsource\"/> in October 2005.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Business Model Attacked|first=Elliot|last=Spagat|publisher=Associated Press|date=January 26, 2007|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2007/01/26/AR2007012600826_pf.html|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</reF> They alleged Qualcomm was abusing its market position to charge unreasonable rates for its patents.<ref name=\"DodgsonGann2013\">{{cite book|author1=Mark Dodgson|author2=David M. Gann|author3=Nelson Phillips|title=The Oxford Handbook of Innovation Management|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=s0dYAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA571|date=November 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-969494-5|pages=571}}</ref><ref name=\"Lundqvist2014\"/> Qualcomm alleged the six companies were colluding together under the code name Project Stockholm in a legal strategy to negotiate lower rates.<reF>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm says competitors conspiring in patent dispute|first=Jonathan|last=Sidener|date=March 21, 2008|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.utsandiego.com/uniontrib/20080321/news_1b21conspire.html|newspaper=Union Tribune San Diego}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|date=January 24, 2007|title=Qualcomm warns of escalating costs|first=Chris|last=Nuttall|newspaper=The Financial Times|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/806e3634-abff-11db-a0ed-0000779e2340.html#axzz39iO1EwRz|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"battle\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm's Legal Battles Hold Big Implications for Cellphones|first=Don|last=Clark|date=September 7, 2006|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=August 9, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/news/articles/SB115759241325855938}}</ref> These events led to a protracted legal dispute.<ref name=\"randommm\"/>\n \nQualcomm filed a series of patent-infringement lawsuits against Nokia in Europe, Asia, the United States, and with the ITC.<ref name=\"post\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Files Lawsuits Against Nokia|first=Bruce|last=Meyerson|publisher=The Associated Press|date=November 7, 2005|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/11/07/AR2005110700505.html|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><Ref name=\"timeline\"/> The parties initiated more than one dozen lawsuits against one another.<Ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite news|title=TIMELINE: Qualcomm vs Nokia patents battle|publisher=Reuters|date=February 25, 2008|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2008/02/25/us-nokia-qualcomm-idUSL257876620080225|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> Several companies filed antitrust complaints against Qualcomm with the Korean [[Fair Trade Commission]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Broadcom and TI take action on Qualcomm|first=Song|last=Jung-a|date=July 3, 2006|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/80f8b628-0aac-11db-b595-0000779e2340.html#axzz39uAwmWk9|newspaper=Financial Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> who initiated an investigation into Qualcomm's practices in December 2006.<Ref name=\"ten\">{{cite news|date=January 5, 2007|title=South Korea's fair trade regulators steps up Qualcomm probe|accessdate=June 5, 2014|url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&amp;dat=20070105&amp;id=fsQ0AAAAIBAJ&amp;sjid=fiEGAAAAIBAJ&amp;pg=2776,337753|publisher=The Associated Press}}</ref> The dispute between Qualcomm and Nokia escalated, when their licensing agreement ended in April 2007.<ref name=\"nokia\">{{cite news\n|title=In settlement, Nokia will pay royalties to Qualcomm\n|first=Matt\n|last=Richtel\n|newspaper=The New York Times\n|date=July 24, 2008\n|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/24/technology/24qualcomm.html?_r=0\n|accessdate=July 23, 2014\n}}</ref>\n \nIn February 2008, the two parties agreed to halt any new litigation until an initial ruling is made on the first lawsuit in Delaware.<ref name=\"BagleySavage2009\">{{cite book|author1=Constance E. Bagley|author2=Diane Savage|title=Managers and the Legal Environment: Strategies for the 21st Century|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=I2ezeH8IpSgC&pg=PA386|date=February 5, 2009|publisher=Cengage Learning|isbn=0-324-58204-8|pages=386}}</ref><Ref name=\"timeline\"/> Nokia won three consecutive court rulings with the German Federal Patent Court, the High Court in the United Kingdom, and the International Trade Commission respectively. Each found that Nokia was not infringing on Qualcomm's patents.<ref name=\"goodsource\"/><ref name=\"Lundqvist2014\">{{cite book|author=Bj\u00f6rn Lundqvist|title=Standardization under EU Competition Rules and US Antitrust Laws: The Rise and Limits of Self-Regulation|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=PySeAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA64|date=May 30, 2014|publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing|isbn=978-1-78195-486-7|pages=64}}</ref><Ref>{{cite news|title=Nokia: German court rules Qualcomm patent invalid|date=July 23, 2008|url=http://in.reuters.com/article/2008/07/23/idINL2310194220080723|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=August 8, 2014}}</ref> In July 2008, Nokia and Qualcomm reached an out-of-court settlement that ended the dispute and created a 15-year cross-licensing agreement.<ref name=\"goodsource\"/>\n \n===Recent disputes===\n \nParkerVision filed a lawsuit against Qualcomm in July 2011 alleging that it infringed on seven ParkerVision patents related to converting electromagnetic radio signals to lower frequencies.<ref name=\"parker\">{{cite news|first=Brad|last=Graves|title=Qualcomm Likely to Appeal $173M Verdict|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/91945397/qualcomm-likely-appeal-173m-verdict}}</ref> A $173 million jury verdict against Qualcomm was overturned by a judge.<Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Wins Ruling Tossing ParkerVision $173M Verdict|first=Susan|last=Decker|date=June 23, 2014|publisher=Bloomberg|accessdate=August 7, 2014|url=http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-06-23/qualcomm-wins-ruling-tossing-parkervision-173m-verdict.html}}</reF>\n \nIn November 2013, the China National Development and Reform Commission initiated an anti-trust investigation into Qualcomm's licensing division.<ref name=\"reutreur\"/><ref name=\"wsjsj\"/> The [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] also started an investigation into whether Qualcomm breached antibribery laws through its activities in China.<ref name=\"wsjsj\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Profit Rises; Company Notes 'Challenges' in China|first1=Don|last1=Clark|first2=Josh|last2=Beckerman|date=July 23, 2014|accessdate=August 6, 2014|url=http://online.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-profit-rises-company-notes-challenges-in-china-1406147672|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</reF><Ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm not talking about bribery probe|first=Mike|last=Freeman|date=February 5, 2012|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/2/03f68896-77a3-11de-9713-00144feabdc0.html#axzz2xMChLKki|accessdate=August 9, 2014|newspaper=Union-Tribune San Diego}}</reF> The Chinese regulator raided Qualcomm's Chinese offices in August 2013.<ReF name=\"reutersssst\">{{cite news|title=China accuses Qualcomm of overcharging, abusing dominance|first1=Kevin|last1=Yao|first2=Matthew|last2=Miller|date=February 19, 2014|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/02/19/us-china-ndrc-idUSBREA1I0A820140219|publisher=Reuters|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The dispute was settled in 2015 for $975 million.<ref name=\"Clark 2015\">{{cite web | last=Clark | first=Don | title=Qualcomm to Pay $975 Million Antitrust Fine to China | website=WSJ | date=February 8, 2015 | url=http://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-settles-china-probe-1423518143 | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> In late 2016 The Korea Fair Trade Commission alleged Qualcomm abused a \"dominant market position\" to charge cell phone manufacturers excessive royalties for patents and limit sales to companies selling competing semiconductor products.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016hsj\">{{cite news | title=Why South Korea Just Hit Qualcomm with a Record $854 Million Fine | newspaper=Fortune | date=December 27, 2016 | url=http://fortune.com/2016/12/27/qualcomm-korea-antitrust/ | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> The regulator gave Qualcomm a fine of $854 million, which the company said it will appeal.<ref name=\"Fortune 2016hsj\"/>\n \nIn April 2017, Qualcomm paid a $814.9 million settlement with [[Blackberry]] as a refund for prepaid licensing fees.<ref name=\"Cao 2017\">{{cite web | last=Cao | first=Jing | title=BlackBerry Jumps as $814.9 Million Qualcomm Refund Bolsters Cash | website=Bloomberg.com | date=April 12, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-04-12/blackberry-wins-814-9-million-from-qualcomm-in-royalty-dispute | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> In October 2017, Taiwan's Fair Trade Commission fined Qualcomm another $773 million.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Fined Record $773 Million in Taiwan Antitrust Probe| website=Bloomberg | date=October 11, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-11/qualcomm-fined-773-million-in-taiwan-for-antitrust-violations | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref> However, in late 2018 Qualcomm paid a settlement to Taiwan for $93 million in fines and a promise to spend $700 million in the local Taiwan economy.<ref name=\"Mickle 2018\">{{cite web | last=Mickle | first=Tripp | title=Qualcomm, Taiwan Reach Settlement in Patent-Licensing Dispute | website=WSJ | date=August 10, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/qualcomm-taiwan-reach-settlement-in-patent-licensing-dispute-1533872303 | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Lee 2018\">{{cite web | last=Lee | first=Yimou | title=Qualcomm settles anti-trust case with Taiwan regulator for $93 million | website=U.S. | date=August 10, 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-qualcomm-taiwan/qualcomm-settles-with-taiwan-antitrust-regulator-for-t2-73-billion-idUSKBN1KV07Z | accessdate=August 17, 2018}}</ref>\n \n===Apple===\nIn January 2017, the Federal Trade Commission initiated an investigation into allegations that Qualcomm charged excessive royalties for patents that are \"essential to industry standards.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm shares plunge amid US antitrust case|url=http://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/17/qualcomm-shares-plunge-after-report-said-it-will-face-us-antitrust-case.html|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=CNBC|date=January 17, 2017}}</ref> That same year, Apple initiated a $1 billion lawsuit against Qualcomm in the U.S. alleging Qualcomm overcharged for semiconductors and failed to pay $1 billion in rebates.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apple files $1 billion lawsuit against chip supplier Qualcomm|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-lawsuit-qualcomm-idUSKBN1542SG|accessdate=21 January 2017|work=Reuters|date=21 January 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Balakrishnan|first1=Anita|title=Qualcomm blasts 'baseless' $1 billion Apple royalties lawsuit|url=http://www.cnbc.com/2017/01/20/apple-sues-qualcomm-for-1-billion.html|accessdate=January 21, 2017|work=CNBC|date=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Apple also filed lawsuits in China<ref name=\"Pressman 2017\">{{cite web | last=Pressman | first=Aaron | title=Qualcomm Slams Apple Over Lawsuits | website=Fortune | date=January 26, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/01/26/qualcomm-apple-patent-fight-analysts/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref name=\"adfljajdcpajdpfijaoiwec\">{{cite web | title=Apple Is Expanding its War with Qualcomm | website=Fortune | date=March 3, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/03/03/apple-qualcomm-legal-battle/ | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref>\n \nApple alleged Qualcomm was engaging in unfair competition by selling industry-standard patents at a discount rate in exchange for an exclusivity agreement for its semiconductor products.<ref name=\"King McLaughlin Rosenblatt 2017\">{{cite web | last=King | first=Ian | last2=McLaughlin | first2=David | last3=Rosenblatt | first3=Joel | title=Qualcomm Accused of Forcing Deal on Apple to Thwart Rivals | website=Bloomberg.com | date=January 17, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-01-17/qualcomm-forced-apple-to-exclusively-use-modem-chips-ftc-says | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> An FTC report reached similar conclusions.<ref name=\"King McLaughlin Rosenblatt 2017\"/> Qualcomm filed counter-claims alleging Apple made false and misleading statements to induce regulators to sue Qualcomm.<ref name=\"Forbespatents\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Is Suing iPhone Manufacturers In Backlash Against Apple | website=Forbes | date=May 17, 2017 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/aarontilley/2017/05/17/qualcomm-suing-apple-contract-manufacturers/#e0eea6a183a7 | accessdate=October 4, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also sued Apple's suppliers for allegedly not paying Qualcomm's patent royalties, after Apple stopped reimbursing them for patent fees.<ref name=\"Forbespatents\"/><ref name=\"Fortune 2017Apple\">{{cite web | title=Apple Stops Paying Qualcomm Royalties | website=Fortune | date=April 28, 2017 | url=http://fortune.com/2017/04/28/apple-iphone-royalties-qualcomm/ | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm petitioned the International Trade Commission to prohibit imports of iPhones, on the premise that they contain stolen Qualcomm patents after Apple's suppliers stopped paying.<ref name=\"King Decker 2017\">{{cite web | last=King | first=Ian | last2=Decker | first2=Susan | title=Qualcomm Said to Seek U.S. Import Ban for iPhones | website=Bloomberg.com | date=May 3, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-05-03/qualcomm-said-to-seek-u-s-import-ban-for-iphones | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref>\n \nIn August, the International Trade Commission responded to Qualcomm's complaints by starting an investigation of Apple's use of Qualcomm patents without royalties.<ref name=\"Heavey Nellis 2017\">{{cite web | last=Heavey | first=Susan | last2=Nellis | first2=Stephen | title=U.S. to review Qualcomm's complaints about Apple iPhone patents | website=U.S. | date=August 8, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-qualcomm/u-s-to-review-qualcomms-complaints-about-apple-iphone-patents-idUSKBN1AO23R | accessdate=October 5, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also filed suit against Apple in China for alleged patent infringement in October 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Seeks China iPhone Ban, Expanding Apple Legal Fight | website=Bloomberg | date=October 13, 2017 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-10-13/qualcomm-seeks-china-iphone-ban-escalating-apple-legal-fight | accessdate=August 12, 2018|first=Ian|last=King}}</ref> The following month, Apple counter-sued, alleging Qualcomm was using patented Apple technology in its Android components.<ref name=\"Nellis 2017\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=Apple accuses Qualcomm of patent infringement in countersuit | website=U.S. | date=November 29, 2017 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-apple-qualcomm/apple-accuses-qualcomm-patent-infringement-in-countersuit-idUSKBN1DT1UU | accessdate=August 12, 2018}}</ref>\n \nIn December 2018 Chinese<ref name=\"Nellis 2018\">{{cite web | last=Nellis | first=Stephen | title=China court bans sales of older iPhone models in Apple-Qualcomm global battle | website=U.S. | date=December 11, 2018 | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-qualcomm-apple-idUSKBN1O91LD | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> and Germany<ref name=\"Feiner 2018\">{{cite web | last=Feiner | first=Lauren | title=Apple will stop selling some iPhone models in its stores in Germany following ruling in Qualcomm patent case | website=CNBC | date=December 20, 2018 | url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/20/qualcomm-reportedly-wins-injunction-against-apple-in-munich.html | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref> courts held that Apple infringed on Qualcomm patents and banned sales of certain iPhones. Some patents were held to be invalid,<ref name=\"Bloomberg 2019\">{{cite web | title=Apple Dodges One Import Ban in Qualcomm Fight, Faces Another| website=Bloomberg | date=March 26, 2019 | url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-26/apple-infringes-qualcomm-patent-judge-recommends-iphone-ban | accessdate=December 18, 2019|first1=Susan|last1=Decker|first2=Ian|last2=King|first3=Mark|last3=Gurman}}</ref> while others were infringed by Apple.<ref name=\"Nieva 2019\">{{cite web | last=Nieva | first=Richard | title=Apple dealt legal blow as jury awards Qualcomm $31 million | website=CNET | date=March 15, 2019 | url=https://www.cnet.com/news/apple-qualcomm-patent-infringement-verdict/ | accessdate=December 18, 2019}}</ref>\n \nIn April 2019, Apple and Qualcomm reached an agreement to cease all litigation and sign a six-year licensing agreement.<ref name=\"daoijdaiew\">{{cite web | title=Apple and Qualcomm Settle All Disputes Worldwide | website=The New York Times | date=April 16, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/04/16/technology/apple-qualcomm-settle.html | first1=Don|last1=Clark|first2=Daisuke|last2=Wakabayashi|accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> The settlement included a one-time payment from Apple of about $4.5 to $4.7 billion.<ref name=\"daiuowbavinadsewmgn\">{{cite web | title=Qualcomm Pegs Payment From Apple at $4.5 Billion to $4.7 Billion | website=The New York Times | date=April 1, 2019 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/01/technology/qualcomm-apple-payment.html | accessdate=January 11, 2020}}</ref> Terms of the six-year licensing agreement were not disclosed, but the licensing fees were expected to increase revenues by $2 per-share.<ref name=\"daoijdaiew\"/><ref name=\"daiuowbavinadsewmgn\"/>\n \nIn January 2018, the European Competition Commission fined Qualcomm $1.2 billion for an arrangement to use Qualcomm chips exclusively in Apple\u2019s mobile products.<ref name=\"Olson 2018\">{{cite web | last=Olson | first=Parmy | title=Qualcomm Hit With $1.2 Billion EU Antitrust Fine | website=Forbes | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/parmyolson/2018/01/24/qualcomm-1-2-billion-eu-antitrust-fine/ | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"danonqveroidnsiun\">{{cite web | title=E.U. Fines Qualcomm $1.2 Billion Over Apple Deal |first=Chad|last=Bray| website=The New York Times | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/24/business/eu-qualcomm-fine-antitrust.html | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Drozdiak Greenwald 2018\">{{cite web | last=Drozdiak | first=Natalia | last2=Greenwald | first2=Ted | title=Qualcomm Is Slapped With $1.23 Billion EU Fine for Illegal Payments to Apple | website=WSJ | date=January 24, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/eu-to-fine-qualcomm-over-exclusivity-payments-to-apple-1516783685 | accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Qualcomm is appealing the decision.<ref name=\"Olson 2018\"/><ref name=\"danonqveroidnsiun\"/><ref name=\"Drozdiak Greenwald 2018\"/>\n \n==Operations and market-share==\nQualcomm develops software, semiconductor designs, patented intellectual property, development tools and services, but does not manufacture physical products like phones or infrastructure equipment.<ref name=\"Kodama2012\">{{cite book|first=Mitsuru|last=Kodama|title=Interactive Business Communities: Accelerating Corporate Innovation through Boundary Networks|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=iYu-lGHtkK4C&pg=PA94|date=August 28, 2012|publisher=Gower Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-1-4094-5950-7|pages=94}}</ref> The company's revenues are derived from licensing fees for use of its intellectual property, sales of semiconductor products that are based on its designs, and from other wireless hardware, software or services.<reF name=\"primary\">{{cite|date=November 6, 2013|title=Form 10-K Annual Report|accessdate=July 26, 2014|publisher=Qualcomm|url=http://investor.qualcomm.com/secfiling.cfm?filingID=1234452-13-483}}</ref>\n \nQualcomm divides its business into three categories:<ref name=\"primary2\">{{cite web | title=About Qualcomm | website=QUALCOMM Incorporated | date=August 23, 2019 | url=https://investor.qualcomm.com/about-qualcomm/overview |accessdate=January 10, 2020}}</ref>\n* QCT (Qualcomm CDMA Technologies): CDMA wireless products; 60 percent of revenue\n* QTL (Qualcomm Technology Licensing): Licensing; 19% of revenue\n* QSI (Qualcomm strategic initiatives): Investing in other tech companies; 1% of revenue\n \nQualcomm is a predominantly fabless provider of semiconductor products for wireless communications and data transfer in portable devices.<ref name=\"newceo\">{{cite news|title=Qualcomm calling on a new CEO amid intensifying competition|first=Stuart|last=Pfeifer|date=February 16, 2014|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-stock-spotlight-qualcomm-20140217-story.html#axzz2tmGtq2XB|newspaper=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=June 5, 2014}}</ref> According to the analyst firm Strategy Analytics, Qualcomm has a 39 percent market-share for smartphone application processors and a 50 percent market-share of baseband processors.<ref name=\"FierceWireless 2016\">{{cite web | title=Report: Qualcomm led smartphone application processor market in 1H 2016 | website=FierceWireless | date=October 12, 2016 | url=http://www.fiercewireless.com/wireless/report-qualcomm-led-smartphone-application-processor-market-1h-2016 |accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Its share of the market for application processors on tablets is 18 percent.<ref>{{cite news|first=David|last=Manners|date=October 18, 2016|title=Apps processor market grows 3% while tablet AP market sinks 34%|url=http://www.electronicsweekly.com/news/business/487606-2016-10/|newspaper=Electronics Weekly}}</ref> According to analyst firm ABI Research, Qualcomm has a 65 percent market-share in LTE baseband.<ref name=\"Mott 2017\">{{cite web | last=Mott | first=Nathaniel | title=FTC: Qualcomm Has Unfair Monopoly In Smartphone Market | website=Tom's Hardware | date=January 18, 2017 | url=http://www.tomshardware.com/news/ftc-qualcomm-baseband-processors-monopoly,33443.html | accessdate=January 21, 2017}}</ref> Qualcomm also provides licenses to use its patents, many of which are critical to the CDMA2000, TD-SCDMA and WCDMA wireless standards.<ref name=\"Asif2011\">{{cite book|first=Saad|last=Asif|title=Next Generation Mobile Communications Ecosystem: Technology Management for Mobile Communications|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=zgqQ4MX3uIUC&pg=PT378|date=February 25, 2011|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-119-99581-4|pages=378|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> The company is estimated to earn $20 for every smartphone sold.<ref name=\"Cannady2013\">{{cite book|first=Cynthia|last=Cannady|title=Technology Licensing and Development Agreements|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=3NFMAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA67|date=April 4, 2013|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-538513-7|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>{{RP|64}}\n \nQualcomm is the largest public company in San Diego.<ref>{{cite news|first=Allen|last=Mike|title=San Diego's Largest Public Company Remains a Work in Progress|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=June 20, 2011|url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/61993682/san-diegos-largest-public-company-remains-work-progress|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"six\">{{cite|url=http://www.sandiegohistory.org/journal/v55-1/pdf/v55-1west.pdf|publisher=The Journal of San Diego History|title=Before Qualcomm: Linkabit and the Origins of San Diego\u2019s Telecom Industry|first=Joel|last=West|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref> It has a philanthropic arm called The Qualcomm Foundation.<ref>{{cite news|title=X Prize finalists design Trekkie-inspired health tools|first=Michelle|last=Healy|newspaper=USA Today|date=August 27, 2014|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2014/08/27/qualcomm-tricorder-xprize/14586959/|accessdate=October 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Allen|first=Mike|title=Stadium perks `Q' up for Qualcomm|newspaper=San Diego Business Journal|date=March 31, 1997}}</reF> A January 2013 lawsuit resulted in Qualcomm voluntarily adopting a policy of disclosing its political contributions. According to <i>The New York Times</i>, Qualcomm's new disclosure policy was praised by transparency advocates.<ref name=\"randomname\">{{cite news|title=State Comptroller Sues Qualcomm for Data About Its Political Contributions|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=January 3, 2013|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/04/nyregion/new-york-comptroller-sues-qualcomm-for-data-on-political-giving.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Aw%2C%7B%222%22%3A%22RI%3A13%22%7D|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Qualcomm Reveals Its Donations to Tax-Exempt Groups|first=Nicholas|last=Confessore|date=February 22, 2013|url=http://cityroom.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/02/22/qualcomm-agrees-to-reveal-donations-to-tax-exempt-groups/?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Aw%2C%7B%222%22%3A%22RI%3A13%22%7D|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=August 9, 2014}}</ref>\n \n==See also==\n* [[Qualcomm Snapdragon]]\n \n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n \n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.qualcomm.com/ Official website]\n{{Finance links\n| name = QUALCOMM, Inc.\n| symbol = QCOM\n| sec_cik = 804328\n| yahoo = QCOM\n| google = QCOM\n}}\n\n{{Open Handset Alliance Members}}\n{{NASDAQ-100}}\n{{Major networking hardware companies}}\n{{Major semiconductor companies}}\n{{Electronics industry in the United States}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Qualcomm| ]]\n[[Category:1